753,10824268117139,2024-08-24T10:43:11.811Z,Mary Pollock,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and Artificial Intelligence on social media and other platforms.  Viewers need to know that content has been altered, especially when it comes to candidates, elections, and issue ads associated with candidates and elections whether or not paid for by candidates, candidate PACs, third party organizations or individuals.",371
754,1082422405071,2024-08-24T10:43:56.612Z,Anthony Tursak,,,"AI, absolutely MUST be regulated by the FCC!!  In social media it is dangerous, and will be used to cause disinformation!!",122
755,1082459668199,2024-08-24T10:50:07.513Z,Pete Wilson,,,"I support the proposal made by the FCC to regulate deepfakes and AI, in order to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.  Voters indeed all residents of this country deserve the protection the US government would provide by forcing ALL AI creations to be digitally watermarked for permanent identification producing the provenance of those creations.",429
756,10824063525519,2024-08-24T10:52:20.569Z,Cynthia L. Miller,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections. In a time where misinformation and deepfakes are increasingly prevalent, transparency about the origins of content is crucial. Knowing that an ad has been generated or altered by AI helps viewers and listeners critically evaluate the information being presented and discern whether it is authentic or manipulated. Also, AI-generated content can be highly persuasive and tailored to exploit emotional or cognitive biases. By requiring disclosure, the rule aims to mitigate the risk of AI being used to manipulate public opinion in deceptive ways. Furthermore, political ads can have a substantial impact on elections and public policy. Ensuring that AI-generated content in these ads is clearly identified helps maintain the integrity of the political process and prevents potential misuse of AI technologies to mislead voters. Lastly, this rule could serve as a model for other forms of media and platforms, including social media, where AI-generated content is also prevalent. By establishing a standard for disclosure, it paves the way for broader regulations that can address the challenges posed by AI in various contexts.",1307
757,1082483753710,2024-08-24T11:05:49.599Z,Richard Lawrence Clough Jr,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.",180
758,108242566715418,2024-08-24T11:09:07.258Z,Bruce Hoelzer,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.",180
759,10824593906987,2024-08-24T11:20:54.002Z,Mr. Matt Hobson,,,"I am writing to express my serious concerns regarding the FCC's proposed rulemaking for AI-generated content in political advertisements. Alarmingly, in its attempt to justify this overreach, the FCC has revived sweeping, decades-old agency precedents. Specifically, the agency references a policy statement from the 1960s, which announced the FCC’s expectation for broadcasters to “take all reasonable measures to eliminate any false, misleading, or deceptive matter” under threat of license revocation. This policy statement suggests a regulatory authority far beyond simple disclosure requirements, effectively positioning the FCC as the nation’s speech police.

Such an expansive interpretation of the FCC’s authority is deeply troubling. The regulatory power claimed by the FCC today would enable the agency to operate as an arbiter of truth in political speech, a role that is both inappropriate and unconstitutional. This overreach threatens to stifle free speech and disrupt the democratic process by imposing undue burdens on broadcasters.

Your proposed AI definition is so broad that any political ad targeted for censorship -- including by corrupt ""third-party"" fact-checkers -- could be implicated.

Congress has clearly defined the boundaries of the FCC’s authority, which do not include acting as a gatekeeper for political speech. The revival of such far-reaching precedents is an alarming step towards undermining free speech and the democratic process.

I strongly urge you to immediately withdraw the proposed rule.

Sincerely,
Mr. Matt Hobson",1562
