1039,10825059832032,2024-08-25T23:26:40.610Z,Dorian Carli-Jones,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.",180
1040,108250671902105,2024-08-25T23:54:25.721Z,Joan Engelhaupt,,,"For democracy to work, voters must have accurate information on the candidates and issues on which they are to vote.  AI has already demonstrated that it can subvert the facts regarding candidates and issues.",208
1041,108250420500072,2024-08-25T23:55:13.856Z,Valerie wald,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and Artificial Intelligene (AI), to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.  Political campaigns have already been using AI-created deepfakes to mislead voters and influence election outcomes.  Our democracy depends on having voters express their political preferences based on accurate information.  US residents also rely on accurate information when spending money on goods and services. The federal government has a role in regulating false content to protect everyone living here.",615
1042,1082559708164,2024-08-25T23:57:59.933Z,Bobby Morrison,,,"I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our elections.",180
1043,10826267157703,2024-08-26T00:30:34.113Z,Mr. William Blackman III,,,"Congress has explicitly granted the Federal Election Commission (FEC)—not the FCC—the exclusive statutory authority to interpret, administer, and enforce the Federal Election Campaign Act (52 U.S.C. § 30106(b)). This includes the authority to establish disclosures for political communications on television and radio (52 U.S.C. § 30120). The courts have consistently recognized the FEC’s unique role in regulating political disclosures, even when other agencies have attempted to circumvent or supplement its rules, concluding that “the FEC is the exclusive administrative arbiter of questions concerning the name identifications and disclaimers” for political communications (Galliano v. United States Postal Service, 836 F.2d 1362, 1368–70 (D.C. Cir. 1988)).

Currently, the FEC is actively considering the very issues implicated by your proposed rule, and legislators in Congress are engaged as well. A DNC-backed petition has asked the FEC to impose new regulations on AI-generated political speech—a proposal that mirrors the FCC’s current initiative—before voters hit the ballot boxes this fall (See Petition of Public Citizen, July 13, 2023; Comments of Democratic National Committee, REG 2023-02, Oct. 16, 2023).

The FEC Chairman has warned that the FCC’s proposal would encroach upon the FEC’s exclusive jurisdiction, directly conflict with existing laws and regulations, and sow chaos among political campaigns for the upcoming election.

I strongly urge the immediate withdrawal of these proposed regulations.

Sincerely,
Mr. William Blackman III",1559
