Thank You.",1000
1050,10826277620979,2024-08-26T03:48:52.059Z,Sandra Clark,,,"We need to fully regulate deepfakes and AI on social media platforms overall, but especially when it comes to candidates and elections.  Even now deepfakes are being used to denigrate citizens including stars and government officials with lies and misinformation possibly even to blackmail people.

""I support the FCC's proposal to regulate deepfakes and AI, to create more clarity and understanding for listeners and viewers of content, especially when it comes to our reputations, the ability of bad actors to rob people blind and our elections.""",548
1051,1082635215046,2024-08-26T04:00:33.658Z,Mr. Douglas Riddle,,,"I am writing to express my serious concerns regarding the FCC's proposed rulemaking for AI-generated content in political advertisements. Alarmingly, in its attempt to justify this overreach, the FCC has revived sweeping, decades-old agency precedents. Specifically, the agency references a policy statement from the 1960s, which announced the FCC’s expectation for broadcasters to “take all reasonable measures to eliminate any false, misleading, or deceptive matter” under threat of license revocation. This policy statement suggests a regulatory authority far beyond simple disclosure requirements, effectively positioning the FCC as the nation’s speech police.

Such an expansive interpretation of the FCC’s authority is deeply troubling. The regulatory power claimed by the FCC today would enable the agency to operate as an arbiter of truth in political speech, a role that is both inappropriate and unconstitutional. This overreach threatens to stifle free speech and disrupt the democratic process by imposing undue burdens on broadcasters.

Your proposed AI definition is so broad that any political ad targeted for censorship -- including by corrupt ""third-party"" fact-checkers -- could be implicated.

Congress has clearly defined the boundaries of the FCC’s authority, which do not include acting as a gatekeeper for political speech. The revival of such far-reaching precedents is an alarming step towards undermining free speech and the democratic process.

I strongly urge you to immediately withdraw the proposed rule.

Sincerely,
Mr. Douglas Riddle",1565
