1091,10826942903342,2024-08-26T20:30:24.113Z,Mr. Alick andreades,,,"Congress has explicitly granted the Federal Election Commission (FEC)—not the FCC—the exclusive statutory authority to interpret, administer, and enforce the Federal Election Campaign Act (52 U.S.C. § 30106(b)). This includes the authority to establish disclosures for political communications on television and radio (52 U.S.C. § 30120). The courts have consistently recognized the FEC’s unique role in regulating political disclosures, even when other agencies have attempted to circumvent or supplement its rules, concluding that “the FEC is the exclusive administrative arbiter of questions concerning the name identifications and disclaimers” for political communications (Galliano v. United States Postal Service, 836 F.2d 1362, 1368–70 (D.C. Cir. 1988)).

Currently, the FEC is actively considering the very issues implicated by your proposed rule, and legislators in Congress are engaged as well. A DNC-backed petition has asked the FEC to impose new regulations on AI-generated political speech—a proposal that mirrors the FCC’s current initiative—before voters hit the ballot boxes this fall (See Petition of Public Citizen, July 13, 2023; Comments of Democratic National Committee, REG 2023-02, Oct. 16, 2023).

The FEC Chairman has warned that the FCC’s proposal would encroach upon the FEC’s exclusive jurisdiction, directly conflict with existing laws and regulations, and sow chaos among political campaigns for the upcoming election.

I strongly urge the immediate withdrawal of these proposed regulations.

Sincerely,
Mr. Alick andreades",1554
