1693,1090360873990,2024-09-03T16:20:05.032Z,Peggy Fry,,,"I am sending in a comment to support the proposal from the Federal Communications Commission that would require on-air and written disclosure of AI-generated content in radio and television advertisement. This would be a crucial and much overdue necessary first step to regulating artificial intelligence on social media.

I worked as a radio professional from 1982- 2009. I took my professional duties seriously, but just as seriously, I also took the rules the FCC had in place that required radio stations to devote a certain number of airtime hours to public service announcements and programs and conduct any news and public service broadcasting in a responsible, honest manner. Those rules and regulations taught me how important public trust in the programming of news and information that is broadcast is to citizens in a democratic and free society, and also how that trust can be undermined when those outlets of information are not maintained with honesty, integrity, and accountability.

Already, deep fakes using AI in political ads and social media regarding the upcoming elections in the United States have proliferated, exposing millions of American citizens to deceptive and fraudulent information. This should deeply worry all of us. So, speaking as a former radio professional who prided herself on conducting on-air programming with honesty, fairness and integrity, I strongly support this crucial first step to help restore integrity, transparency, honesty and most importantly, trust in the communications industry I was so proud to be a part of.

Peggy Fry
Wilmington, NC",1594
1694,109030366504709,2024-09-03T16:21:36.575Z,Cynthia & Thomas Markevich,,,"Federal Communications Commission
45 12th Street SW
Washington, D.C. 20554
Dear Commissioners,
We write to express our strong support for the Federal Communications
Commission’s proposed rulemaking No. 24-211, particularly the provisions concerning
the disclosure of AI-generated content in political communications.
These measures are essential to ensuring transparency and protecting the integrity of our
democratic processes. A trustworthy information ecosystem is the bedrock of a
functioning democracy: If voters are unsure whether they can trust the information in
front of them, it undermines informed decision-making and the overall health of our
democratic processes.
A lack of transparency in AI-generated content can erode public confidence, potentially
leading to voter apathy and distrust of all information, regardless of its veracity.
Establishing strong regulations for disclosing AI in political ads is the first step towards
ensuring a robust information ecosystem in the wake of these new capabilities.
We support the following aspects of the proposed rules:
On-Air and Written Disclosure Requirements: We favor requiring both on-air disclosures
and written disclosures in broadcasters’ political files when AI-generated content is used,
especially when AI is used to create deceptive deepfakes.
Application to Both Candidate and Issue Advertisements: Extending the disclosure
requirements to both candidate and issue advertisements recognizes the broad impact of
AI-generated content and ensures that all political messaging is subject to the same
transparency standards.
Inclusive Application to Broadcasters and Other Entities: Applying the disclosure
requirements to all pertinent content carriers ensures that all major content platforms
under the FCC’s jurisdiction are covered at the local, state, and federal levels. We believe
that these measures could enhance transparency and protect voters from deceptive
practices. We urge the commission to adopt these rules and to continue its efforts to
safeguard the integrity of our elections in the face of rapidly evolving technological
challenges.
Sincerely,
Cynthia & Thomas Markevich
schemeofthings@comcast.net",2185
