1698,1090330166419,2024-09-03T16:59:48.540Z,Martha Van Haitsma,,,"Federal Communications Commission
45 12th Street SW
Washington, D.C. 20554
Dear Commissioners,
I write in strong support of the Federal Communications Commission’s proposed rulemaking No.
24-211. I am especially in favor of mandating the disclosure of AI-generated content in political
communications. Democracy cannot function in an environment in which we cannot distinguish
between real and fake information. Transparency is essential to our democratic system.
A democracy requires a marketplace of ideas in which we can attribute the actual things leaders
and candidates say and do to the actual people who say and do them. Voters cannot elect leaders
who represent their views if they cannot clearly distinguish between what actual candidates and
leaders say and do, and computer-generated fakes that make it appear candidates and leaders are
saying or doing things they are not saying or doing.
AI and deep fakes pose a serious challenge to our democracy. Establishing regulations that tightly
mandate disclosure of AI in political ads is needed as at least a first step in protecting our
democratic system.
I support the following aspects of the proposed rules:
On-Air and Written Disclosure Requirements: AI-generated content and deceptive deep fakes
should at the very least be labeled as what they are, both verbally on air and in written form for all
political advertising and speech.
Application to Both Candidate and Issue Advertisements: Political campaigning works through
both direct ads concerning specific candidates and broader issue advertisements. To have an
impact, disclosure requirements should be applied to both.
Inclusive Application to Broadcasters and Other Entities: To work effectively, disclosure
requirements should apply to all content carriers at the local, state, and federal levels.
Regulations create the basis for enforcing transparency and protecting voters from deceptive
practices. I urge the commission to adopt these rules and to continue its efforts to safeguard the
integrity of our elections in the face of rapidly evolving technological challenges.
Sincerely,
Martha Van Haitsma
mvh@uchicago.edu",2143
