I. Summary
The Lawyers’ Committee for Civil Rights Under Law submits these comments in
response to the Federal Communications Commission’s (“Commission”) Notice of Proposed
Rulemaking, In re Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in
Political Advertisements, FCC 24-74, MB Docket No. 24-211 (July 25, 2024).
The Lawyers’ Committee uses legal advocacy to achieve racial justice, fighting inside
and outside the courts to ensure that Black people and other people of color have the voice,
opportunity, and power to make the promises of our democracy real. The organization’s Digital
Justice Initiative works at the intersection of racial justice, technology, and privacy to address
predatory commercial data practices, discriminatory algorithms, invasions of privacy,
disinformation, and other online harms that disproportionately affect Black people and other
people of color. Everyone is entitled to the equal enjoyment of the internet’s goods and services
without discrimination.
In recent years, mis- and disinformation have proliferated regarding political candidates,
eligibility requirements for voting, how to vote, and the safety of voting. This includes
propaganda campaigns where bad actors specifically target Black voters and others with voter
suppression materials designed to deceive people out of their right to vote. For example, in the
2016 election, a disinformation campaign sought to trick voters into thinking they could vote by
text message instead of going to the polls. In the 2020 election, bad actors sent voter intimidation
robocalls designed to deceive Black voters about the safety of voting by mail—robocalls that
were later held to violate the Voting Rights Act, Ku Klux Klan Act, and Telephone Consumer
2
Protection Act. And earlier this year, robocalls in New Hampshire impersonated the voice of
President Joe Biden to deceive primary voters. In these comments, we catalog numerous
examples of deceptive voter suppression. The use of generative artificial intelligence in
broadcasted1 political advertisements has the potential to supercharge the risks of deceptive
voter suppression. Already these technologies can persuasively imitate voices and create
photorealistic images of real people and events. Absent guardrails, artificial intelligence poses
grave risk to the compelling public interest in electing our representatives based on facts, values,
and policies, not deception, defamation, and intimidation.
The Commission’s proposed rules are necessary and appropriate for protecting the right
to vote. In these comments, we provide some feedback on how to improve the proposed rules.
Specifically, the definition of “AI-generated content” needs to be revised to function as intended.
We offer additional recommendations regarding how the Commission should structure the time,
place, and manner of disclosures and recordkeeping. In particular, the Commission should adopt
a standardized AI symbol to be used in visual disclaimers, and educate the public about its use.
We also offer additional support for why these proposed rules are consistent with the First
Amendment, as well as how they can further the Commission’s efforts to advance diversity,
equity, and inclusion.
II. The use of AI to supercharge disinformation and voter suppression
poses a severe threat to free and fair elections.
In this section we respond to the Commission’s requests for comment on the risks
associated with AI-generated political content, equity-related considerations, and how the
proposed rules will address these concerns. In recent years there have been countless examples
of bad actors using disinformation in myriad forms to engage in voter suppression, particularly
targeting Black communities and other communities of color. The advent of generative AI
substantially increases these risks by reducing the cost of creating deceptive information, making
it easier to create deceptive information without skilled labor, enabling microtargeting of
deceptive information at scale, and creating more persuasive content whose falsity is harder to
discern. The ability to use broadcasting to reach large audiences with election disinformation
poses a severe risk to free and fair elections. The disclosure requirements proposed by the
Commission would have a positive impact to help mitigate these risks in the context of
broadcasters. While these types of disclaimers will not eliminate all risks from disinformation,
they will be a significant step in the right direction that will prevent and reduce harm within the
zone of the Commission’s authority.
1 In these comments, we use the term “broadcasters” and “broadcasting” generically to refer to all types of entities
addressed in the NPRM, for ease of reference.
3
a. Disinformation campaigns and other forms of deception are used to
disenfranchise Black voters and other voters of color.
In this subsection we respond to the Commission’s request for comment in paragraph
10, concerning voting rights threats from AI-generated content in political ads. We also address
equity-related considerations in response to the request for comment in paragraph 37.
Over the past several election cycles, bad actors have repeatedly used disinformation and
other deceptive practices to attempt to disenfranchise or mislead Black voters and other voters of
color. Here, we provide some key examples that either were or could be exacerbated with AI-
generated content. While these examples do not necessarily involve broadcasters, they
demonstrate myriad types of common voter suppression tactics which could be adapted to
broadcast contexts, particularly when targeting ads to broadcasters that primarily serve
communities of color, immigrant communities, and other discrete markets. Misinformation in
media disproportionately harms Black Americans. A recent survey from Free Press found that
while “the vast majority of Americans” are concerned about political misinformation, “Black
Americans are disproportionately encountering misinformation when seeking accurate news.”2
In 2016, the Russian government used social media platforms to attempt to interfere in
the U.S. presidential election, including specifically targeting content to Black Americans
intended to undermine confidence in the election and dissuade them from voting.3 The Russian
campaign also used racially divisive issues in targeted ads.4 Foreign adversaries used
conventional advertising and targeting tools on social media,5 showing the dangerous ways in
which off-the-shelf advertising tools can be abused.6
Also in 2016, a presidential campaign’s data team put 3.5 million Black voters into a
category for people they sought to deter from voting and used that categorization for Facebook
ad targeting.7 The number of Black voters in the “[d]eterrence” category was disproportionate to
2 Kari Paul, Black Americans disproportionately encounter lies online, survey finds, THE GUARDIAN (May 30,
2024), https://amp.theguardian.com/technology/article/2024/may/30/black-americans-online-misinformation.
3 See S. Rep. No. 116-290 (2020), https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/publications/report-select-committee-
intelligence-united-states-senate-russian-active-measures; Scott Detrow, What Did Cambridge Analytica Do During
The 2016 Election?, NAT’L PUBLIC RADIO (Mar. 20, 2018), https://www.npr.org/2018/03/20/595338116/what-did-
cambridgeanalytica-do-during-the-2016-election; see also Gregory Eady et al., Exposure to the Russian Internet
Research Agency Foreign Influence Campaign on Twitter in the 2016 US Election and Its Relationship to Attitudes
and Voting Behavior, 14 NATURE COMMC’NS 1, 9 (Jan. 9, 2023), https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-
35576-9 (“In a word, Russia’s foreign influence campaign on social media may have had its largest effects by
convincing Americans that its campaign was successful.”).
4 See Renee DiResta et al., The Tactics & Tropes of the Internet Research Agency, NEW KNOWLEDGE (Oct. 2019),
https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/533-read-report-internet-research-
agency/7871ea6d5b7bedafbf19/optimized/full.pdf.
5 See FTC Imposes $5 Billion Penalty and Sweeping New Privacy Restrictions on Facebook, FED. TRADE COMM’N
(July 24, 2019), https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/news/press-releases/2019/07/ftc-imposes-5-billion-penalty-
sweeping-new-privacy-restrictions-facebook.
6 See Craig Silverman, Google Allowed a Sanctioned Russian Ad Company to Harvest User Data for Months,
PROPUBLICA (July 1, 2022), https://www.propublica.org/article/google-russia-rutarget-sberbank-sanctions-ukraine.
7 Channel 4 News Investigations Team, Revealed: Trump Campaign Strategy to Deter Millions of Black Americans
from Voting in 2016, CHANNEL FOUR TELEVISION CORP. (Sept. 28, 2020),
4
their share of the electorate in the swing states being targeted. The campaign targeted Black
voters with negative ads designed to suppress turnout. The full extent of the campaign is
unknown because there was no transparency as to what ads were sent to whom.8 Recent research
indicates that the sophistication and scope of political microtargeting will only accelerate as
generative AI makes it easier and cheaper to create customizable targeting and ad copy at scale.9
In another incident arising out of the 2016 election cycle, a social media influencer was
convicted of conspiring with other Twitter users to spread deceptive images and tweets to
supporters of Hillary Clinton.10 The images and tweets falsely suggested that voters could cast
their votes via text message or social media. The convicted influencer, who was ranked as the
107th-most important influencer for the 2016 presidential election by MIT Media Lab, had
specifically discussed the importance of limiting “black turnout” and targeting suppressive
messaging towards “Black social spaces.”11 One of the images posted as part of the
disinformation campaign was falsely framed as a Clinton campaign ad depicting a Black woman
with an “African Americans for Hillary” sign and encouraging voters to “Avoid the Line” and
“Vote from Home.”12 Generative AI tools can make these types of deceptive content more
convincing, and at lower cost, than previously-available tools, and they can enable less-skilled
bad actors to make fraudulent content that they otherwise would be unable to make.
Those seeking to engage in voter suppression can also use datasets of personal
information combined with robocalls, robotexts, email, and other mass communications tools to
microtarget and spread voter intimidation at a scale and low cost previously unimagined. In one
prominent example from the 2020 election, two men sent over 80,000 robocalls targeted to Black
voters, seeking to deter them from voting by mail.13 They spent only $1,000 on the robocalls.14 A
federal court held this conduct violated the Voting Rights Act and the Ku Klux Klan Act.15
Notably, the content of the robocall included false information read by a voice actor who used a
fake name to try to trick listeners that the speaker was the mother of Breonna Taylor—an
innocent Black woman killed in her home by police, whose story has become a rallying cry for
