Similarly, in 2022, a political action committee linked to a former member of Congress
sent robotexts to Kansas voters to trick them into voting contrary to their preferences on a ballot
initiative seeking to remove legal protections for abortion.18 With AI-generated content, these
types of “analog” deceptions could be made much more persuasive and harder to discern. Voice
emulation, in particular, has become highly accurate and difficult to detect.
In the 2020 and 2022 election cycles, disinformation on social media in non-English
languages, particularly Spanish, was rampant and continues to be a major problem.19 For
example, Facebook ads targeting Hispanic populations inaccurately described prominent
American politicians as “communist” and compared them to socialist presidents in South
America.20 Ahead of the 2022 midterm elections, disinformation about election fraud, anti-
discrimination policies, and reproductive rights saturated WeChat, a social media platform used
by an estimated 60% of the Chinese American community.21 These same voter suppression
strategies can be undertaken in broadcast media as well, especially targeting small, non-English
broadcasters that serve immigrant communities with high numbers of naturalized citizens.
The Commission should also consider the interrelationship between broadcast
advertisements and social media. After campaigns create ads for broadcasters, they will often
post and share those ads on social media platforms as well. Organizations and individuals
supporting or opposing a candidate frequently share the broadcast ads online as well. Once
uploaded, the online content is often seen by far more people than the original broadcasted
advertisement. This means that AI disclosures embedded in the broadcast advertisement will
have beneficial secondary effects when that content is shared online.
