Social media plays a key role in disinformation campaigns that spread conspiracy
theories and seek to undermine election integrity.22 The structure of the platforms, their profiling
of users, and the use of recommendation engines to maximize user engagement at all costs can
create a perfect storm for the spread of disinformation and disenfranchisement.23 Misinformation
is often more likely to be engaged with and shared than factual information, and platforms with
greater pathways for virality are more likely to amplify misinformation.24 So if a political
advertiser uses AI-generated content to spread disinformation in a broadcast ad, that content is
likely to be shared even more broadly online by secondary actors.
The proliferation of disinformation on social media was a major contributor to false
narratives and conspiracy theories attacking the outcome of the 2020 election,25 culminating in
the violent attack on the U.S. Capitol on January 6, 2021.26 In a leaked draft report, the
congressional January 6 Select Committee described how platforms ranging from Facebook,
Twitter, and YouTube to Parler, Gab, and 4Chan, failed to stop disinformation, violent rhetoric,
and tactical organization by users leading up to the insurrection.27 Following the attack, the
major platforms have lost interest in self-regulating to combat election disinformation on their
services, even when their staff sound the alarm internally.28 “[T]o tackle thorny issues like
misinformation, [Facebook employees] often had to demonstrate that their proposed solutions
wouldn’t anger powerful partisans or come at the expense of Facebook’s growth.”29 YouTube
was more likely to recommend videos involving election fraud conspiracy theories to users
known to be skeptical about election validity, amplifying fringe disinformation.30 Its AI content
moderation system struggled with combatting disinformation in the short-form YouTube Shorts
