Finally, false and deceptive politicized information, including through issue advertising,
can exacerbate hate-fueled violence. Approximately 77% of American adults agree that
misinformation increases hate crimes, including violence on the basis of race, gender, or religion;
and 74% believe that misinformation in general is a major problem.32 Following the May 14,
2022, attack on the Black community in Buffalo that left ten Black people dead, the New York
Attorney General published a report which found that false online memes helped the shooter
learn about the “great replacement” white supremacist conspiracy theory and motivated his
behavior.33
b. AI poses a serious risk of exacerbating these threats to voting rights.
In this subsection we provide further background information on potential harms and
equity considerations in response to request for comment in paragraphs 10 and 37. We
address deficiencies in the design and operation of generative AI tools and discuss examples of
the use of these tools to foster disinformation and election interference. We then discuss some
hypothetical scenarios in which use of AI—or the false allegation of its use—could interfere with
voting rights or election administration.
Leading AI chatbots often produce misleading, inaccurate, and harmful election
information. For instance, when five of leading text AI models were tested with 26 common
questions about the elections, researchers found that 51% of answers were inaccurate, such as
telling users that California voters can vote by text (they cannot), and that 40% of answers were
harmful, including responses that discouraged users from voting.34 Another study looking at
misinformation in European elections found that Microsoft’s Bing chatbot (since rebranded as
Copilot) gave wrong answers 30% of the time.35 An AI chatbot released by Meta was found to be
propagating false accusations of sexual harassment against elected officials.36 It is reasonably
foreseeable that an advertiser may use or rely on these types of generative AI tools when creating
content for political ads, and mistakenly portray this content as coming from an authoritative
source.
