Large language models and other AI trained on real-world data sets often capture and
reproduce racist stereotypes and biases.37 Meta developed an AI chatbot, and within a few days
of studying online chatter, it began spreading election denialism and antisemitic conspiracy
theories.38 An AI chatbot developed by Google produced racist responses that included
impressions and stereotypes. The company did not adequately invest in diversity or AI ethics,
according to a fired engineer.39
Even more alarming, research has shown that as AI models become more advanced, they
are also developing biases that are less explicit, harder to detect, and harder to fix. A study of
large language models, including ChatGPT and Google’s Gemini, found that these models
“exhibit[ed] covert stereotypes that are more negative than any human stereotypes about African
Americans ever experimentally recorded” when engaging with African American Vernacular
English, while the models’ “overt stereotypes about African Americans are much more
positive.”40 An example of overt racism would be if a model is asked to generate a description of
a group and analyze stereotypes within it.41 A model that exhibits covert racism may be so-called
“colorblind” on its face but exhibit prejudices in how it makes decisions. For example, the
language models in this study were more likely to suggest that speakers of African American
Vernacular English “be assigned less prestigious jobs, be convicted of crimes, and be sentenced
to death.”42 The researchers found, moreover, that existing methods of attempting to mitigate
racial bias in model training (e.g., increasing model size or adding human feedback in training)
just exacerbated the implicit nature of the baked-in prejudice.43
While generative AI poses risks of replicating discriminatory stereotypes, research has
shown that fake images and other false information created with it has proliferated at an
exponential rate. Earlier this year, researchers affiliated with Google assessed misinformation
trends dating back almost 30 years. “The researchers found that about 80% of fact-checked
misinformation claims involve media such as images and video, with video increasingly
dominating those claims since 2022” and that “generative-AI images are now a sizable fraction
of all misinformation-associated images.”44 Another study from the Center for Countering
Digital Hate found that AI tools can easily mimic voices of prominent politicians like President
