We are already seeing examples of generative AI being used to interfere with civil rights
and democratic processes. Recently, foreign nations have used generative AI services to engage
in propaganda operations. OpenAI reported that it “caught groups from Russia, China, Iran and
Israel using its technology to try to influence political discourse around the world” using
ChatGPT.46 Generative AI can also be used to threaten, harass, intimidate, or defame election
workers, voters, and partisans. A high school athletic director was arrested after allegedly using
AI to create a deepfake audio clip of the school principal having a racist conversation.47
AI-generated content has already been used to interfere in the current election cycle.
During the 2024 New Hampshire primaries, bad actors used AI to create robocalls of President
Biden to discourage voters from showing up at the polls.48 As the Commission noted, the
robocaller “used an AI-generated voice that sounded like President Biden’s, telling them to stay
home and ‘save your vote’ by skipping the state’s primary.”49 We agree with the Commission
that “[w]hile this example involved robocalls, AI tools could be used to create similar messages
for political ads aired on radio or television.”50 To educate the public about the risk of AI
deepfakes, an Arizona journalist published deepfake videos of Arizona Republican senatorial
candidate Kari Lake.51
III. The definition of “AI-generated content” needs improvement.
In this section we respond to the request for comment in paragraphs 11 and 12
regarding the proposed definition “AI-generated comment.” We do not think the definition as
proposed will accomplish the goals of the NPRM and strongly recommend the Commission
consider a different definition that accounts for the issues discussed below. As a threshold
matter, we think the definition of “artificial intelligence” adopted from 15 U.S.C. § 9401(3) is
adequate.
