10
The NPRM proposes to define “AI-generated content” as: “an image, audio, or video that
has been generated using computational technology or other machine-based system that depicts
an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation, including,
in particular, AI-generated voices that sound like human voices, and AI-generated actors that
appear to be human actors.”52
The problem with this definition is the first clause—“an image, audio, or video that has been
generated using computational technology or other machine-based system…” This framing will
encompass practically all images, audio, or video because these media are almost always generated
digitally these days and “using computational technology or other machine-based system” just means
“using a computer.” In short, this definition means that any use of a computer to create media will meet
the definition, whether or not AI is used at all. For example, if someone takes a picture with a digital
camera and does no editing to it whatsoever, the resulting image is still “generated using computational
technology” because the camera’s internal computer has to compute how to translate light hitting its
sensor into pixels on a screen. Even a purely analog film camera or tape recorder likely still qualifies as a
“machine-based system.” Consequently, this definition will not be limited in scope to just content
generated with AI, frustrating the intent of the proposed rules.
The Commission should adopt a different set of definitions. We recommend the following:
• The term “artificial intelligence” has the meaning given such term in section 9401(3) of Title 15,
United States Code.
• The term “generative artificial intelligence” means “a machine-based system that uses artificial
intelligence to generate text, audio, video, or images as an output in response to an input prompt
consisting of text, audio, video, or images.”
• The term “AI-generated content” means “any media, including an image, audio, or video, that
appears to depict, in whole or in part, an event, circumstance, situation, human being, or human
voice, where such image, audio, or video was created in whole or in part, directly or indirectly,
using generative artificial intelligence.”
These proposed sets of definitions have several advantages. First, they are rooted in a statutory
definition of artificial intelligence set by Congress in 15 U.S.C. § 9401(3). Next, they use that statutory
definition to help define “generative artificial intelligence,” which is the type of AI that would typically
be used to generate the synthetic media that this rulemaking seeks to address. Then this definition of ""AI-
generated content” hinges on the use of generative AI, and includes any media made with generative AI
that could reasonably be interpreted to depict some sort of realistic situation, whether it is an event, a
person, or a person’s voice. Including the phrase “in whole or in part” recognizes that the AI-generated
components of media may be just a piece of a larger organic work, but that can still be highly impactful.
For example, a genuine landscape photo of a candidate with their family in front of their car could take on
an entirely different message if someone used generative AI to put a small but realistic-looking hate
symbol bumper sticker on the car. Including the phrase “directly or indirectly” recognizes that media
containing AI-generated content can be inserted into other media. For example, a video slideshow
compilation of images taken from social media, where one of the images was created using generative AI.
52 NPRM at ¶ 12.
11
IV. The proposed disclosure requirements will help prevent election
disinformation and protect voting rights.
We agree with the Commission’s proposals in paragraph 13 regarding the procedure for
inquiring about, disclosing, and recording the use of AI-generated content. Requiring
broadcasters to disclose the use of AI-generated content in political ads is consistent with their
statutory obligation to serve the public interest because the public has a compelling interest in
eliminating deception about elections, candidates, and the right to vote.
These disclosure requirements are necessary and highly beneficial to the public interest.
Disclaimers and disclosures that inform the public when they are looking at AI-generated content
have a two-fold set of benefits. First, they prevent immediate deception by the content in
question. Second, they improve the media literacy of the public over time, by allowing the public
to learn how to discern authentic and inauthentic content.
For example, in some localities, election officials are attempting to educate voters about
how to spot disinformation while promoting accurate election information. Called “pre-
bunking,” these programs seek to build up trusted voices to “[c]ommunicate early and
transparently about the elections process to the American people,” said an election security
expert at the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.53 Disclosure and labeling
requirements like those the Commission is proposing are an essential prophylactic because
researchers have found that it “is nearly impossible to counter election misinformation once it
has taken root online.”54
Absent the proposed disclosure requirements, media consumers would often have no idea
when they are viewing AI-generated content in political ads. This could lead to highly deceptive
situations, such as voters being misled about the actions or positions of candidates, the truth or
falsity of past events, and even the circumstances and safety of their own polling places.
Deceptive political ads can use AI-generated content to distort democratic processes, deceive or
intimidate voters, and deprive the right to vote. There is a clear and compelling public interest in
preserving election integrity, and that is what these proposed rules seek to achieve.
V. Time, Place, and Manner of Disclosures and Recordkeeping
In this section we offer recommendations to improve the proposed rules on which the
Commission requests comment in paragraphs 15 to 21.
In paragraph 15, and in similar portions of other paragraphs, the Commission seeks
comment on how a broadcaster should inquire whether an advertisement contains AI-generated
content. Broadcasters should not run advertisements if they do not receive a response to the
53 Cat Zakrzewski et al., Debunking misinformation failed. Welcome to “pre-bunking”, WASH. POST (May 26,
2024), https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2024/05/26/us-election-misinformation-prebunking/.
54 Id.
12
inquiry about AI-generated content. There is little burden to the broadcaster to ask the question
to the advertiser and there is little burden to the advertiser in answering it. If a broadcaster ran an
advertisement even if the advertiser did not respond to the inquiry, it would vitiate the whole
purpose of these rules. Deceptive advertisers would simply not answer the question if their ad
contained AI-generated content. In the alternative, the Commission should require broadcasters
to use the AI disclosure if the advertiser fails to answer the inquiry. However, this is a
suboptimal outcome because some of the advertisements likely will not contain AI-generated
content, and viewers/listeners will be misled into thinking that they do contain it. This would
impair efforts to educate the public about how to spot AI-generated content.
In response to the requests for comment in paragraph 17, we make several
recommendations for standardizing and improving the disclosures. It is important for the
Commission to recognize that while these ads may run on broadcast airwaves initially, the
broadcasts are likely to be shared and disseminated subsequently online as well, including
through social media. That online content will be consumed primarily on small screens: phones,
tablets, and laptops. Therefore, it would be beneficial to develop a standard that is easily
perceived even in these resharing scenarios—as well as being easy to comprehend quickly while
watching TV.
For these reasons, we recommend the Commission create, adopt, and mandate the use of
a standardized AI symbol in visual media. This symbol could be the letters “AI” in a circle,
similar to the © copyright symbol. When used in visual media, this symbol should be in a bold
font and in an attention-grabbing color that is highly contrasted to its background. It should be at
least ten percent of the vertical picture height, not four percent as proposed in the NPRM, to
ensure that it is easily visible on mobile devices. Because it is only two letters in a circle, instead
of a whole sentence, this increased size will still take up less screen space than the proposed text
disclosure.
We recommend that the Commission undertake a public education campaign to teach the
public what this new symbol means and propagate its use. Once the public is familiar with it,
spotting the symbol could be a much faster and easier way for viewers to understand that a piece
of media involves AI-generated content, rather than having to read or listen to a disclaimer. It
also would be visible when the audio is muted. In addition, a standardized symbol can be used in
all broadcasts regardless of the language of the programming. If the symbol comes into common
use, screen readers and other assistive devices for people with disabilities could be programmed
to recognize it. The Commission could require the use of both the symbol and textual disclaimers
for an initial period of two or three years while educating the public and then reevaluate whether
the symbol on its own is a sufficient disclaimer.
We respond to questions in paragraphs 15 and 17 regarding what to do if a broadcaster
learns that a political ad contains AI-generated content but the advertiser did not tell the
broadcaster. In these circumstances, the broadcaster should immediately cease broadcasting the
13
ad. If the advertiser wants to run the ad, they should answer the inquiry honestly. In response to
the request for comment in footnote 57, there are other third parties that could be considered
credible third parties for these purposes. These include federal and state election officials, the
Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, and other entities with a demonstrated history
of combatting disinformation and who do not have any interest or partisanship in the underlying
political topic. For example, Microsoft has a demonstrated history of identifying hostile foreign
election interference operations and notifying the public.55
In response to the request for comment in paragraph 18, and similar proposals in other
paragraphs, we support the proposal to require broadcasters to keep a publicly-accessible record
of the AI-generated political ads in their political files. This measure would foster transparency
and aid researchers studying the use of AI in political campaigning.
In response to the request for comment in paragraph 21, we support applying the
disclosure requirements to network or syndicated programming. The risks of viewers and
listeners being deceived is even greater in a network or syndicated program than other
programming because these programs will reach wider audiences.
VI. The proposed rules are consistent with the First Amendment.
In paragraphs 29 to 35, the Commission discusses and seeks comment on the
constitutionality of its proposed rules under the First Amendment. We agree with the
Commission’s assessment that these proposed rules—as well as the recommendations we make
in our comments above—are consistent with the requirements of the First Amendment. We write
here to note some additional relevant case law that further supports the analysis.
The Supreme Court and lower courts have held that restrictions on speech—even political
speech—can survive even strict scrutiny when they are narrowly tailored to serve the compelling
government interest of protecting the right to vote and election integrity. In Burson v. Freeman,
504 U.S. 191 (1992). the Supreme Court upheld an electioneering ordinance against a First
Amendment challenge. There, a Tennessee statute prohibited electioneering (i.e., solicitation of
votes and displays or distribution of campaign materials) within 100 feet of the entrance of a
polling place. Electioneering is unquestionably a core form of political speech that plays a vital
role in the democratic process. But the Court recognized “that the right to vote freely for the
candidate of one’s choice is of the essence of a democratic society” and the “State has a
compelling interest in protecting voters from confusion and undue influence” as well as “in
preserving the integrity of its election process.” Id. at 199 (cleaned up). The Court discussed how
this type of statute was meant to protect the privacy of the secret ballot against “voter
intimidation and election fraud.” Id. at 206. The Court held the 100-foot restriction was a
narrowly tailored mechanism for achieving the state’s compelling interest. Id. at 209.
55 See, e.g., MICROSOFT THREAT ANALYSIS CTR., Iran steps into US election 2024 with cyber-enabled influence
operations (Aug. 9, 2024), https://cdn-dynmedia-1.microsoft.com/is/content/microsoftcorp/microsoft/final/en-
us/microsoft-brand/documents/5bc57431-a7a9-49ad-944d-b93b7d35d0fc.pdf.
14
More recently in National Coalition on Black Civic Participation v. Wohl, 661 F.Supp.3d
78 (SDNY 2023), a federal district court held that election disinformation robocalls were not
protected by the First Amendment. While the primary holding of the court was that these
robocalls constituted true threats that did not receive First Amendment protection, the court made
a secondary holding that the application of the Voting Rights Act to the disinformation robocalls
would survive both intermediate and strict scrutiny. Id. at 120-21 and n.29. “[P]roscribing this
election disinformation is tied to the government’s interest in protecting voting rights and the
integrity of elections.” Id. at 121.
Another court recently came to the same conclusion in United States v. Mackey, 652
F.Supp.3d 309 (EDNY 2023). There, the defendant spread disinformation on social media about
how to vote in the 2016 election, tricking others into thinking they could vote by text message
instead of going to the polls. Mackey was charged with conspiring to deprive rights under 18
U.S.C. § 241, the criminal analogue to the Ku Klux Klan Act. The court held Mackey’s speech
was not protected by the First Amendment because he was using false speech effectively to
defraud others out of their right to vote. See Mackey, 652 F.Supp.3d at 340-41.
Mackey relied heavily on an earlier Supreme Court case that is also relevant to the
Commission’s analysis, United States v. Alvarez, 567 U.S. 709 (2012). Alvarez concerned when,
whether, and how the First Amendment protects false speech. In Alvarez, the Court invalidated a
federal law that prohibited false claims that a person had received the Congressional Medal of
Honor. The Supreme Court held that as a general matter, most false speech is protected speech
under the First Amendment. But, there are important exceptions to that general rule. For
example, false statements that are a component of “defamation, fraud, or some other legally
cognizable harm” are not protected or receive less protection. See id. at 718-19. Alvarez also
holds that laws that “protect the integrity of Government processes” can constitutionally restrict
false speech, such as perjury, making false statements to government officials, or
misappropriating the name of a federal agency to deceive others. Id. at 720-21. Elections, too, are
government processes whose integrity is vital. Like perjured testimony, election disinformation
“is at war with justice because it can cause” the voters “to render a judgment not resting on
truth.” Id. at 720.
The Supreme Court also observed in dicta in Minnesota Voters Alliance v. Mansky, “We
do not doubt that the State may prohibit messages intended to mislead voters about voting
requirements and procedures.” 585 U.S. 1, 18 n.4 (2018).
VII. The proposed rules protect diversity, equity, and inclusion.
Like any technology, AI is a tool that can be used to help or harm. In response to the
request for comment in paragraph 37, we write briefly to note that AI-generated content—
when used responsibly—can be beneficial to diversity, equity, and inclusion. For example, a
candidate can use AI to translate their statements into languages they do not speak, which can
engage more citizens in the democratic process and help their voices be heard. Generative AI
could also be a cost-effective way for candidates to produce professional-grade campaign
advertisements. This could allow candidates from low-income communities to compete on a
15
more equal footing with well-funded candidates. This could foster closer alignment between
candidates and the needs of their constituents rather than the priorities of deep-pocketed donors.
VIII. Conclusion
We appreciate the opportunity to comment on this Notice of Proposed Rulemaking. We
encourage the Commission to use every tool in its toolkit to protect the right to vote against
deceptive communication practices, including AI-generated disinformation.
