The National Hispanic MediaCoalition (NHMC)respectfully submitsthesecomments in
response to the Federal Communication Commission’s (“FCC” or “Commission”) Notice of
Proposed Rulemaking published on July 25, 2024, and seeking “comment on structuring an
outreach grant program.”1 NHMC is a38year-oldnonprofit organization thatadvocates for civil
rights, eliminating hate, ending racism, and discrimination against the Latino community. To
achieve thesegoals,NHMCutilizes education,policy work,and mediaadvocacy.
I. INTRODUCTION
The National Hispanic Media Coalition (NHMC) has represented the interestsandrights
of the Latino community before the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), other
agencies, Congress, and the White House for nearly four decades. Our ongoing work in
Hollywood in Latino representation, andcorporateaccountabilityas wellas ourongoing workin
Washington, D.C. in fighting for digital equity, platform accountability, and media diversity is
immensely affectedbytherise andcomplicationsof artificialintelligence(AI).
NHMC believes the FCC has a responsibility and obligation to protect consumers from
the harms of AI when used by FCC license holders, and agrees with the proposed disclosure
rules.2 We believe that the disclosure rules proposed in this proceeding are appropriate and
necessary to protect all people from potential harms to democracy and to ensure healthy
information ecosystems.
