RE: Comment in the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements: MB Docket No. 24-211
Dear Ms. Berthot:
A. Support for the Proposed Rule
We want to express support for the proposed rule. The use of manipulated media and Artificial
Intelligence (AI) should be identified and labeled in all paid political communications, including
paid digital communications, in an effort to level the playing field for campaign communications.
The Federal Communication Commission’s (“FCC’s”) proposed rule has the right intentions and
is a step in the right direction, but unfortunately will fail to capture bad actors working to spread
misinformation in the primary space it lives and flourishes: online.
B. For True Impact, The Rule Should Apply to Digital Platforms
Without clear regulations in place, digital platforms sometimes write their own rules with little
accountability over enforcement. For example, Twitter created a rule about misinformation that
they failed to enforce: allowing Elon Musk to post an AI-generated video with no ramification or
label. Meta, on the other hand, has clear policies in place for labeling AI in ads. However, there is
little transparency into how this rule is enforced or implemented. Google has similar policies in
place, but consumers and voters are reliant on these platforms to enforce their own rules, which
they often do not do. Yet, when the quantity of ads is so astronomical – with 5 million individual
ads already aired this cycle – it’s often hard to spot abnormalities.
Bad actors will continue to use every tool in their toolbox - including AI. Clear and consistent
rules are important to make sure everyone can have the same set of tools. Simply asking for
manipulated media to be labeled is not a limitation to any campaign’s or cause’s ability to
communicate. The label merely provides additional transparency to help the American public
navigate what they are seeing on their screens. We support the FCC taking this challenge head on.
C. FCC Has the Authority to Regulate AI
The Notice of Proposed Rulemaking seeks comments on extending the current political
programming and recordkeeping requirements applicable to broadcasters to cable operators, direct
broadcast satellite providers, and satellite digital audio service licensees engaged in origination
programming. Although the FCC has previously stated that it “does not regulate online content,”1
the current rulemaking offers the FCC the opportunity to reexamine this position in light of the
dangers posed by AI in digital political advertising. The FCC should consider whether current
political programming and recordkeeping requirements, or other proposals, can be applied to AI
in online political advertising.
The FCC has broad authority to regulate radio, television, wire, and satellite across the United
States.2 To that end, the Act empowers the FCC, as “public convenience, interest, or necessity
requires . . . to make such regulation and prescribe such restrictions . . . as necessary to carry out
the provisions of the [Communications Act of 1934].”3 Consistent with this broad mandate, the
FCC is not prohibited from assessing proposals that address the use of AI in online political
advertising. As explained in the Notice, the FCC has relied on various provisions of the Act to
“enact rules in the public interest,” in many contexts.4 And recently, the FCC explained that
“Congress has relied on the Commission to determine whether a particular service or provider”
meets the certain statutory definitions that trigger regulation.5 And the FCC should do so here, and
rely on its broad grant of authority, and expand the current rulemaking to consider rules that relate
to AI in political online advertising.
As explained in the Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, AI technology “has the potential to produce
‘deepfakes’ and other deceptive and misleading information, sowing confusion and distrust among
the voting public.”6 By expanding the current rulemaking to address AI in online digital political
advertisements, the FCC, at a minimum, will be able to create a full record of proposals and
arguments that fully examine these important issues. The FCC’s longstanding position that online
activities are generally outside of its jurisdiction is largely grounded in the First Amendment right
to free speech. But the First Amendment is not a categorical bar to the government creating
narrowly tailored rules where there exists a compelling governmental interest.
1 See FCC and Free Speech, https://www.fcc.gov/consumers/guides/fcc-and-
speech#:~:text=Nevertheless%2C%20what%20power%20the%20FCC,obscenity%2C (last visited Aug. 26, 2024).
2 See 47 U.S.C § 151.
3 In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, 89 Fed Reg. 63,381, 63,386 (Aug. 5, 2024) (quoting 47 U.S.C. §
303(r)).
4 Id.
5 Safeguarding and Securing the Open Internet, Restoring Internet Freedom, 89 Fed. Reg. 45,404, 45,452 (May 22,
2024), https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2024-05-22/pdf/2024-10674.pdf.
6 In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, 89 Fed Reg. 63,381, 63,389 (Aug. 5, 2024).
In its Notice, the FCC tentatively concluded that the proposed disclosure and political file
requirements comport with the First Amendment.7 Specifically, the FCC concluded that it has “a
compelling interest in providing greater transparency regarding the use of AI-generated content in
political advertising.”8 This interest, the Notice explains, is sufficient to extend “the disclosure and
political file requirements to broadcasters, cable operators, direct broadcast satellite providers, and
satellite digital audio service licensees.”9 Indeed, rather than abridge these entities free speech
rights, the FCC observed that the proposed rules “would further the goals of the First Amendment
and the Communication Act by ensuring broadcasters and other regulated entities take reasonable
measures to address potentially, false, misleading, or deceptive political advertising and enhancing
the public’s ability to evaluate political ads, thus promoting an informed electorate and improving
the quality of public discourse.”10
This interest is equally, if not more, compelling in the online political advertising context as
Americans continue to absorb more content online. Indeed, the potential proliferation of AI in
political advertising online has the greatest potential to undermine U.S. elections. There is no
reason to have a more stringent First Amendment analysis for online political advertising for
purposes of the specific rules under consideration in this Notice. Regardless of the medium, entities
that are already subject to the FCC’s jurisdiction should take reasonable measures “to address
potentially false, misleading, or deceptive material” in political ads that they carry.11 Accordingly,
the First Amendment does not require a more stringent test for online political advertising that
contains AI.
The need to expand the current rulemaking would thus allow the FCC to consider proposals to
comprehensively address AI in the political advertising context. For instance, the FCC could obtain
comments from key stakeholders on whether its existing authority to regulate cable operators and
other licensees would permit it to address AI in online political advertising and feasibility of
proposed rules. The FCC has previously acknowledged that it has the authority to regulate
broadband providers such as Comcast and AT&T.12 In particular, the FCC has reaffirmed its
authority to establish net neutrality rules to prohibit such providers from engaging in
discriminatory internet practices to advance their own interests. And previous iterations of these
rules have previously been considered and upheld by the United States Court of Appeals for the
D.C. Circuit.13
This proposed rulemaking offers an opportunity for the FCC to address the dangers posed by AI
in political advertising, regardless of whether the advertising airs on television or through digital
ads. The dangers posed in both scenarios are real, and the First Amendment should not be used as
a basis to exempt online political advertising containing AI from regulation. Accordingly, we urge
