Via Electronic Filing
RE: In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated
Content in Political Advertisements, [MB Docket No. 24–211; FCC 24–74; FR ID235498]
Notice of Proposed Rulemaking
The National Council of Negro Women (NCNW) strongly supports Commission's proposed rules
requiring disclosure of artificial intelligence (AI)-generated content in political advertising. We
commend the FCC for recognizing the potential dangers of AI-generated ads and taking proactive
steps to ensure voters are informed and protected.
We support the proposed requirement for broadcasters to inquire about the use of AI in political
ads they air and encourage the FCC to mandate that broadcasters conduct due diligence beyond
simply accepting advertisers' claims. Penalties for nondisclosure could help ensure compliance.
Importantly, the FCC's proposal to mandate disclosures for both candidate advertisements and
issue advertisements acknowledges the wide-ranging impact of AI-generated content. By holding
all political messaging to the same transparency standards, regardless of whether it comes from a
candidate or addresses a broader political issue, the Commission is taking a comprehensive
approach to protecting voters.
Furthermore, we strongly support the FCC's plan to apply these disclosure requirements not just
to broadcasters, but also to cable operators, DBS providers, SDARS licensees, and other regulated
entities engaged in origination programming. By covering all major content platforms under the
FCC's purview at the local, state, and federal levels, the Commission is ensuring that there are no
gaps in transparency that bad actors could exploit. This inclusive approach is necessary to fully
safeguard our communities.
NPRM AI in Elections Disclosure page 2
We also urge the Commission to strengthen the on-air disclosure requirements. Audio and visual
disclosures should be mandated to maximize accessibility, and disclosures should be provided in
Spanish and other commonly spoken languages in the broadcast area, not just English.
Disclosure requirements should fully apply to political ads embedded in network and syndicated
programming. All broadcasters mentioned must take responsibility for all political content they
air, even if that means altering programming to include necessary disclosures.
We do ask that the Commission carefully weigh the compliance burden on smaller Black-owned
regulated entities against the paramount need for transparency. Exemptions or assistance may be
warranted to avoid undue burdens especially amongst a community that has struggled to remain
owners and providers in the telecommunications space.
Finally, we encourage the FCC to consider a targeted prohibition on AI-generated content in
political ads in the 30 days prior to an election, when the risk and impact of voter confusion is
the greatest.
Black women have historically endured voter suppression and disenfranchisement. We cannot
permit new technologies to further erode our hard-fought voting rights. We urge the Commission
to enact robust, broadly applicable AI disclosure rules to safeguard the integrity of our
democracy. Our community is counting on you.
Sincerely,
Shavon L. Arline-Bradley
NCNW President & CEO",3393
