Comments on MB Docket No. 24-211, Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements
September 15, 2024
To whom it may concern,
My name is Hayden Goldberg and I am a resident of Kirkland, Washington. I submit this
comment regarding the Federal Communication Commission’s (“FCC” or “the Commission”)
notice of proposed rulemaking regarding the disclosure of AI-generated content in political
broadcasts.1
In August 2024 I submitted my thesis for the degree of Masters of Science in Social
Science of the Internet from the Oxford Interest Institute at Oxford University. My thesis
examined 10 state laws prohibiting unlabeled AI-generated content in political ads.2 Specifically,
I examined legislative testimony and the text of the laws to assess the risks that legislators were
trying to address, and the risks that the laws actually addressed. I compared these risks to the
risks other election related laws could address, such as voter intimidation (prohibited under
§ 11(b) of the Voting Rights Act). A true and correct copy of my thesis can be found at the link in
footnote 2 and a copy is provided in Appendix B. My thesis makes me uniquely situated to
provide insight into how FCC’s proposed regulations compare to existing state laws, where there
are gaps, and what lessons can be learned from them.3
1 See Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Media, Notice of
Proposed Rulemaking, MB Docket No. 24-211 (rel. July 25, 2024) (herein after “NPRM”).
2 See Hayden Goldberg, States Legislating Against Digital Deception: A Comparative Study of Laws to Mitigate
Deepfake Risks in American Political Advertisements (Masters Thesis, August 2024), available at
https://ssrn.com/abstract=4912795. In my thesis I referred to “AI-generated” content as “deepfakes”. While I discuss
the definition the FCC proposes at length, infra at 3-6, for the purposes of drawing lessons from my thesis and
applying them here, the content being referenced with the terms “deepfake” and “AI-generated content” is the same.
3 Ongoing state and federal actions are discussed in NPRM, supra note 1, at ¶ 7-8. My thesis and comments can help
supplement their discussion of state action.
2
Part 1 of this comment provides responses to specific areas the FCC requested comment
in their Notice of Proposed Rulemaking. I focus on definitions, disclosures, penalties,
collaboration with other agencies, and then address other matters the Commission requested
comment on.
Part 2 and Appendix A bring a problem with this public comment process to the FCC’s
attention. While writing this letter I noticed repeated and strangely named comments. Upon
investigation, these comments (or at least the names used to submit them) appeared to be
generated using artificial intelligence such as ChatGPT or Claude. Part 2 and Appendix A detail
my investigation into comments submitted August 19 and 20, 2024. However, the pattern and
problem repeated itself throughout the public comment process, and I encourage FCC staff to
investigate it more thoroughly and refer the case to appropriate authorities if necessary.
Part 1: Response to Proposed Rules
I strongly support the FCC’s proposal to include a disclaimer for AI-generated content, as
the limited state laws currently in effect are insufficient to address the harms caused by
deepfakes. Disclaimers can help inform the public and encourage additional critical thinking by
them about the veracity and message conveyed in a political advertisement.4 These will
complement existing “truth in campaign advertising” laws that require disclosure about who paid
for an ad.5
I provide comment on AI-generated content, disclosures, penalties, how this rule interacts
with other agencies and laws, and briefly comment on other matters the FCC specifically
4 This responds to NPRM, supra note 1, at ¶12-13.
5 See e.g. 47 U.S.C. § 315(b)(2)(C)(ii) (candidate ads shall include “a clearly readable printed statement, identifying
the candidate and stating that the candidate has approved the broadcast and that the candidate’s authorized
committee paid for the broadcast”.
3
requested comment on. Each section contains recommended action item(s); Part 1’s conclusion
collects these in one place.
Throughout my comment and the ruling making process, it is important to keep in mind
that the use of artificial intelligence or generative AI in campaign ads is a fundamentally opt-in
process. There is no requirement or obligation to use this technology. Therefore, the rule does not
impact campaigns and ad buyers who simply do not use AI-generated content. This means some
First Amendment concerns can be avoided, since advertisers can simply not use the technology.
Definition of AI-Generated Content
In paragraph 11 the FCC requests comment on their definition of “AI-generated content”.
This section provides a response. The proposed definition is,
an image, audio, or video that has been generated using computational technology or
other machine-based system that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct,
or an event, circumstance, or situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that
sound like human voices, and AI-generated actors that appear to be human actors.6
This proposed definition focuses on the interpretation of a piece of content (does it “depict an
individual’s appearance... that appear[s] to be human...”?) rather than on the underlying
mechanism of creation or its potential deceptive effects. This is good because it allows for
change over time in the technology used to create it. Additionally, the definition rightly draws
attention to how the viewer perceives the ad. By focusing on voice and actors, the rule is narrow
and deals with the humans depicted in an ad, as opposed to scenery or background material. The
language “an event, circumstance, or situation” is broad enough to also cover the scenery,
images, or other background in the ad. However, this latter language is problematic because it
has the potential to be unclear.
6 Id. at ¶ 12.
4
The definition appears to create a test focused on the imitation of humans. However, it
does not do as good of a job being clear about the role of “event[s], circumstances[s], or
situation[s]”. It is unclear what types of “event[s], circumstance[s], or situation[s]” the rule
applies to. Only those also involving human imitation? Or does AI-generated content of
“event[s], circumstance[s], or situation[s]”, independent of/without any human voice or actor,
need to be labeled? I recommend the latter and suggest the FCC clarify this language. Under this
suggested amendment, still images generated by AI used in a Ron DeSantis ad from June 2023
must unequivocally be covered by this rule.7
My interpretation of the FCC’s proposed rule is that the rule attempts to prohibit
“deepfakes”. “Deepfakes” are false, fictionalized images, audio, and video that look realistic and
are created using artificial intelligence technologies like neural networks or generative
adversarial networks.8 Deepfakes differ from existing technologies like Photoshop by being
wholly generated, rather than merely edited versions of something that already exists. If this
interpretation is correct, then the rule is intended to be much narrower in scope than some have
made it out to be.9
To further clarify the narrow scope of this rule and assuage concerns, I suggest the FCC
either 1) provide a list of examples in which they see the rule applying, an advisory opinion, or
similar tool the FCC is authorized to use or 2) change language in the prohibition from “AI-
7 See Nicholas Nehamas, DeSantis Campaign Uses Apparently Fake Images to Attack Trump on Twitter, N.Y. TIMES,
Jun. 8, 2023, https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/08/us/politics/desantis-deepfakes-trump-fauci.html.
8 See Robert Chesney & Danielle Citron, Deep Fakes: A Looming Challenge for Privacy, Democracy, and National
Security, 107 CAL. L. REV. 1753, 1758–1759 (2019).
9 See e.g. The Heritage Foundation, Public Comment on Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements, FCC Docket 24-211 at 2 (Sept. 5, 2024) (submission ID
10904922804373) (fearing that the rule could apply to a broad swath of technologies).
5
generated content” to “deepfakes” or “synthetic media”.10 These two options are not mutually
exclusive; indeed, implementing both could be beneficial.
Option 1 would work similarly to the European Union’s Digital Services Act and its
regulations of elections content for Very Large Online Platforms. Under the Digital Services Act,
the European Commission can propose and update guidelines for systematic risks to electoral
processes.11 The commission’s guidance provides approved and acceptable behaviors, such as
“clearly label[ing]… [content] appreciably resemble existing persons, objects, places, entities,
events, or depict events as real that did not happen or misrepresent them, and falsely appear to a
person to be authentic or truthful (i.e. deepfakes).”12 By providing examples of behavior and
which types of content need to be labeled, European regulation can prevent over labeling.
Over labeling occurs when ad creators are uncertain of if their content meets the
definition and include a label to avoid liability and protect themselves. When everything is
labeled, the value of a label decreases. The FCC can avoid creating a situation that incentivizes
over labeling by providing examples of content that do and do not fall under the rule. This list of
examples might assuage concerns brought up in other public comments.13 The FCC has created
similar processes before with the Open Internet Advisory Process14 and Infrastructure Act.15 This
procedure could allow the rule to focus on the type or impact of content.
10 Option 1 might also use a declaratory ruling, authorized at 47 CFR § 1.2. Option 2 follows state laws regarding
the term it defines. See Goldberg, supra note 2, at 58 (discussing differences in the definitions of what states prohibit
and their terminology).
11 See Commission Guidelines for providers of Very Large Online Platforms and Very Large Online Search
Engines on the mitigation of systemic risks for electoral processes pursuant to Article 35(3) of
Regulation (EU) 2022/2065, Apr. 26, 2024, available at http://data.europa.eu/eli/C/2024/3014/oj.
12 Id. at ¶ 40(b) (emphasis in original removed).
13 See NetChoice, Public Comment on Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in
Political Advertisements, FCC Docket 24-211 at 7 (Aug. 22, 2024) (submission ID 10822287829849) (fearing a
“proliferation of disclaimers which would render an otherwise truthful political ad labeled with a self-declaration of
‘fake’… caus[ing] confusion among voters and undermin[ing] the effectiveness of political communication.”).
14 See 47 C.R.F. 8.6; see also Open Internet Advisory Opinion Procedures, GN Docket No.14-28 (rel. July 2, 2015)
available at https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/DA-15-692A1.pdf.
15 See 47 C.R.F. 16.7.
6
To that end, below are a series of non-exhaustive examples of video and image content,
along with my opinion as to if they should count as AI-generated content under this rule.
• The rule (in its current or possible amended form) should not apply to so called “cheap
fakes” where an existing video is merely edited or slowed down.16 One example is a
video of House Speaker Emeritus Nancy Pelosi which was slowed down to make her
appear drunk.17
• The rule should apply to videos or audio of candidates speaking a language they do not
know.18 While it is undoubtedly beneficial for expanding the reach of democratic
activities to constituents and citizens speaking language the candidate does not,19 viewers
should be aware that it is not actually the candidate speaking that language.
• The rule should apply to, and prohibit, still images which are AI generated and included
in an advertisement.20 To be the best of my knowledge, an image of President Trump with
African American voters21 was not used in a campaign ad, but if it was, then it should be
prohibited under the rule.
• An ad that uses AI-generated audio of a candidate or other person saying something they
did not.22
Recommendations
• Use advisory opinions or other tools to provide examples of what the law is supposed to
target. This will mitigate fears raised by others that the regulation is overbroad and targets
too much speech
• Clarify language regarding the role of “event, circumstance, or situation” in the definition
of AI-generated content
16 See Richard Hasen, Deep Fakes, Bots, and Siloed Justices: American Election Law in a Post-Truth World, 64 ST.
LOUIS U. L. J. 535, 552 n.83 and accompanying text (2020) (defining a “cheap fake”).
17 Id.
18 New York City Mayor Eric Adams did this in his campaign. See Justine Calma, NYC Mayor Eric Adams uses AI to
make robocalls in languages he doesn’t speak, THE VERGE, Oct. 17, 2023,
https://www.theverge.com/2023/10/17/23920733/nyc-mayor-eric-adams-ai-robocalls-spanish-mandarin; see also
Chris Glorioso & Hilary Weissman, AI company hired to clone Mayor Adams' voice linked to Biden deepfake,
researchers say, NBC NEWS N.Y., Feb. 1, 2024, https://www.nbcnewyork.com/investigations/ai-company-hired-to-
clone-mayor-adams-voice-linked-to-biden-deepfake-researchers-say/5093499/.
19 This principle can be found in the language minority provisions in the Voting Rights Act and National Voter
Registration Act. This is one benefit that AI can provide. See NPRM, supra note 1 ¶ 17 (requesting comment on if
disclosures should be in the primary language of the ad). See also Id. ¶ 9 (discussing this issue).
20 See e.g. Shannon Bond, DeSantis Campaign Shares Apparent AI-Generated Fake Images of Trump and Fauci,
NPR, Jun. 8, 2023, https://www.npr.org/2023/06/08/1181097435/desantis-campaign-shares-apparent-ai-generated-
fake-images-of-trump-and-fauci (AI generated image of Dr. Anthony Fauci and hugging President Donald Trump).
21 See Marianna Spring, Trump Supporters Target Black Voters with Faked AI Images, Mar. 4, 2024,
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-68440150 (last visited Sep 14, 2024).
22See e.g. Louis Jacobson & Loreben Tuquero, Ad Using AI to Create Trump’s Voice Likely Won’t Be the Last,
Politifact (Jul. 18, 2023), https://www.politifact.com/article/2023/jul/18/a-pro-ron-desantis-ad-used-ai-to-create-
donald-tru/.
7
Disclosures
Paragraphs 14-15, and 17 ask for comment regarding the burden additional labels will
place on campaigns.23 This section articulates why these burdens are minimal to marginal.
Video editing software allows prerecorded audio or visual content to be easily “drag and
dropped” into videos. This method is likely already used by groups making campaign
advertisements to fulfill existing requirements to disclose who pays for an ad. The FCC’s
proposal would merely require them to create an additional set of prerecorded statements and
include these in ads. The time and effort advertisement creators spend implementing the
disclosure will be negligible at best.
Likewise, the FCC’s proposal to add a new disclosure in the Political File with local
stations provides a strong benefit to cost ratio. The required line of text amounts to a new
checkbox on the form, making its cost minimal. Creating a mandatory paper trail is a major
benefit. Academics and researchers can scrape Political Files to acquire information about what
ads are using AI to conduct studies or experiments.; required statements can be a data source to
ascertain if an ad is AI-generated. This will assist in studies to ascertain the efficacy of this
regulation and assess the need for future regulations.
I suggest the FCC mandate a line of text as opposed to using checkboxes. This will assist
scraping and the use of optical character recognition to make the document searchable. It may be
advisable to require a timestamp in the Political File of where in the advertisement AI-generated
content is used. Additionally, it should state what was AI-generated (e.g. “the voice of person X
being depicted” or “the background imagery in the middle third of the screen”). The detail will
increase transparency for the public. The timestamp and additional detail should not be required
in the on-air disclosure, as that might be interpreted as compelled speech.
23 See NPRM, supra note 1 ¶ 14-15, 17.
8
The proposed rule should also be modified by adding a time constraint so it only applies
within a predetermined amount of time before an election.24 This will make the law more
narrowly tailored, which is necessary to comply with Supreme Court precedent.25 Only some
state laws contain this limit, and when they do it is between 30-90 days before an election.26 This
time period can be interpreted as the amount of time a state believes AI-generated information
can be harmful to voters and needs to be identified as artificially generated.
The FCC should follow Michigan and revise the rule to only apply within 90 days of an
election. I believe that in federal elections and high profile state-wide elections, 30 days is too
close to election day and intensive campaigning and advertisements start earlier.27 Additionally,
in low information races down the ballot, a misleading statement in an ad may be the only
communication the voter receives about a candidate. Not having safeguards against misleading
(AI-generated) content goes against democratic principles.28 This is akin to negative political
mailers, which can have a larger effect in down ballot races.29 Outside of the 60-90 day process,
campaigns and the media can fact check AI-generated content that is misleading.
24 See NPRM, supra note 1, at ¶ 36 (requesting comment on if the rules should have a time restriction on them).
25 Williams-Yulee v. Florida Bar, 575 U.S. 473, 444 (2015) (speech restrictions need to be “narrowly tailored to
serve a compelling interest.”); see also United States v. Alvarez, 567 U.S. 709, 738 (2012) (Breyer, concurring)
(describing the need for “a more finely tailored statute”).
26 See e.g. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 168.932f(1)(b) (West) (limiting the law prohibiting unlabeled deepfakes to
only apply within 90 days of an election); TEX. ELEC. CODE ANN. § 255.004(d)(2) (West) (prohibiting deepfakes
within 30 days of an election).
27 60 days would be acceptable instead of 90, but I believe 45 is too short.
28 Specifically, the Supreme Court has consistently advocated for the market for information. For a review of the
early history of this framework see ERIC T. KASPER & TROY A. KOZMA, THE SUPREME COURT AND THE
PHILOSOPHER: HOW JOHN STUART MILL SHAPED US FREE SPEECH PROTECTIONS 45–62 (2024); see also Red Lion
Broad. Co. v. F.C.C., 395 U.S. 367, 390 (1969) (“It is the purpose of the First Amendment to preserve an uninhibited
marketplace of ideas in which truth will ultimately prevail”). Labels are consistent with the marketplace because
they inform consumers and help minimize information asymmetries.
29 See e.g. Alan S. Gerber, Daniel P. Kessler & Marc Meredith, The Persuasive Effects of Direct Mail: A Regression
Discontinuity Based Approach, 73 J. POLITICS 140 (2011) (finding that a 10% increase in negative mailers led to a
1.5-3.5% increase for the opponent in state attorney general race).
9
The FCC also seeks comment regarding if the entity buying airtime should be expected to
know if the ad was created using AI-generated content.30 Florida legislators raised similar
concerns that a sub-contractor might lie or not tell the truth about the origin of a campaign ad.31 I
believe this is a reasonable expectation and business incentives are sufficient to ensure they have
the knowledge. First, contracts between the entity buying airtime and (sub)contractor can require
the (sub)contractor to disclose if the ad was created using AI-generated content. If a
(sub)contractor is later found out to have lied to the entity buying airtime, it is possible they will
face business repercussions, creating an incentive for them not to lie. However, for the sake of
clarity and to reduce future uncertainty regarding who is responsible for false statements, the
FCC can and should amend the proposed rule to clarify that truthfully filling out the Political File
is ultimately the responsibility of the entity buying airtime.
Finally, the FCC should amend the proposed rule to allow broadcasters to make an
amendment to the Political File if the airtime buyer does not respond to an inquiry. Broadcasters
likely cannot prohibit an ad from being aired if they do not get a response from ad buyer to the
former’s inquiry about being AI-generated.32 Therefore, an appropriate step for the station or
broadcasters should be to add an addendum to the Political File stating that the inquiry was not
responded to.
Recommendations
• Maintain, as currently written, the text for the disclosure in broadcasts and Political
Files
30 See NPRM, supra note 1, at ¶ 15.
31 See Hearing on H.B. 919 Before the H. State Affairs Comm., 126th Leg., 2024 Reg. Sess. (Fla. 2024) (statement of
Rep. Ashley Viola Gantt at 01:53:43) (“Who would be the responsible party if it was a third party was contracted
and created images or documents that fall under this bill with AI without the knowledge of the purchaser?”)
32 See 47 U.S.C. § 315(a) (“If any licensee shall permit any person who is a legally qualified candidate for any
public office to use a broadcasting station… [t]hat such licensee shall have no power of censorship over the material
broadcast under the provisions of this section…”); see also 47 CFR § 73.1941.
10
• Revise the proposed rule to only apply within 60 or 90 days of an election (general,
primary, or other type)
• Amend the proposed rule to require broadcasters include a statement on the Political
Disclosure saying the ad buyer failed to respond to the inquiry
• Add space on the Political File for a qualitative description that allows the reader to
identify which part of the ad uses AI-generated content (e.g. a timestamp of where AI-
generated content was used, like “audio of Candidate X from 0:15 to 0:18”)
• Clarify that the entity buying airtime is ultimately responsible for truthfully filling out
the Political File
Penalties
Concerningly, the proposed rule lacks penalties for non-compliance by stations and ad
buyers. Both should be penalized for their respective non-compliance.
A major finding of my thesis was that states have two approaches for penalties.33 First,
they view AI generated content as something to not be created in the first place, and create a
criminal penalty to discourage its creation.34 Second, they view AI generated content as
something harmful to candidates and the public, and create a civil cause of action allowing for
injunctive relief for those harmed.35 Almost uniformly, states give candidates standing, with
significant variation in the granting of standing to others.36
The lack of a specific penalty in the proposed rules concerns me because a bad actor is
not disincentivized from intentionally avoiding the rule. To fill this gap, I believe the FCC has
two potential options. First, they could write a penalty into the proposed rule. Second, they could
investigate if there is general purpose civil or criminal statute providing for remedy or penalties
for failure to comply with promulgated rules. If there is, they should state that that law applies to
33 See Goldberg, supra note 2, at 60-63.
34 Id. at 60-61 (discussing criminal penalties).
35 Id. at 62-63 (discussing injunctive relief).
36 Id. at 58-60 (discussing variation in grants of standing among state laws).
11
this new rule. Alternatively, they should investigate if general torts, such as negligence, are
appropriate.
However, before proceeding with either approach, the FCC must ensure the penalty
adequately addresses the harms caused by AI-generated content. They should articulate which
harms the penalty is seeking to address so that they can tailor the penalty to those harms.
To that end, my thesis found that state legislators were concerned with election security
risks faced by society, reputational risks to candidates, and informational risks to the public.37
Specifically, candidates can be injured by false or deceptive content about themselves and their
reputations, while the public is at risk of being deceived.38 The appropriate penalty (criminal or
civil, injunctive relief, damages, etc.) changes based on which of these risks is being addressed.39
States’ overwhelming emphasis on harms to candidates is why injunctive relief became the go to
remedy. Therefore, the FCC must ensure the penalty they select is consistent with the risk and
type of harm. I discuss the different philosophies of risk and how this should inform penalties
more in § 5.2 of my thesis.40
If taking the second approach for penalties, a a general purpose law would apply to ad
buyers’ failure to respond to station inquiries. This law would need to either contain criminal
penalties to discourage non-compliance from the outset or injunctive relief against both 1) the
person or people and 2) the entity involved. It is easy for new campaign groups to be formed for
a specific purpose.41 Merely providing injunctive relief against the entity means the same people
37 See Id. at 49-57 (developing a theory of risk based on legislative testimony).
38 Id.
39 Id. at 57-66.
40 See Id.
41 One notable example of an entity “popping up” for a specific purpose was the Swift Boat Veterans for Truth
group, created to run an ad opposing then Presidential candidate John Kerry in 2004.
12
behind the entity could create a new one and repeat the actions. Thus, injunctive relief also needs
to be applied to the people involved at that entity and follow them as they move between entities.
Broadcasters and stations meanwhile, should also be penalized for failure to conduct
reasonable inquiries into if content is AI-generated. I believe this penalty should be a fine
equivalent to at least 200% of the ad buy or other revenue attached to the transaction. This
ensures the fine is proportional to the ad buy and is actually a penalty (i.e. more than the
revenue) and not just a cost of doing business. Additional fines may be justified for repeated
offenders.
Finally, anyone depicted should be able to file a complaint with the FCC that a broadcast
contains unlabeled AI-generated content. This should be investigated promptly and
expeditiously, owing to the time sensitive nature of elections and content contained within
campaign ads.
Recommended Action Item:
• Amend the proposed rule to include penalties for non-compliance by ad buyers
• Amend the proposed rule to fine stations and broadcasters that do not inquire into if
content is AI-generated
• Allow depicted individuals to file a complaint if the AI-generated content is unlabeled
Collaboration and Patchwork Solutions
The FCC should continue with their rule making procedure, even in absence of Federal
Election Commission (“FEC”) action. No solution is perfect and addressing the harms of
deepfakes takes a whole of government approach. The two agencies are complementary, which is
why they share jurisdiction over political campaigns: the FCC regulates campaign ads and their
funding, while the FEC regulates campaign finance. As long the FCC continues to collaborate
with the FEC and keeps them informed of what they are doing at the staff level, a patchwork
13
solution – with only one regulation for the moment – is acceptable, even though it insufficiently
addresses the whole problem in the long term.
In my thesis, I found that in some cases, new laws complement existing laws prohibiting
fraudulent misrepresentations and specific types of lies, however the existing laws are
insufficient to fully address the problem.42 Thus, I strongly support a uniform, national rule
applying to all candidates and all political broadcasts to ensure candidates run on an even playing
field.43
To support their work, if they are not already, I encourage the FCC contact state agencies
already engaged in rule-making procedures. For example, Washington’s Public Discourse
Commission (“PDC”), the state campaign finance agency, was granted authority to issue
supplemental rules and assist with compliance for the state law prohibiting unlabeled deepfakes
and synthetic media,44 and their experience could aid FCC staff during the rule making process.45
Other Matters
Below, I provide short responses for specific places and issues the FCC has requested
further comment. The relevant paragraphs each bullet point responds to are given in the
footnotes.
• I agree with the FCC’s analysis in ¶ 30-32, finding that there is a governmental interest in
maintaining transparency and that there is a need for rules to be narrowly tailored.
42 See Goldberg, supra note 2, at 68-70, 74.
43 See also Id. at 59 (discussing the importance of “competitor’s standing” and all candidates abiding by the same
rules).
44 See RCW 42.62.040.
45 General Counsel Sean Flynn has been leading the PDC’s work and could be of assistance. See e.g. Sean Flynn,
Rulemaking drafts re “deepfakes” and yard sign sponsor ID (Memo, April 18, 2024); Hearing on S.B. 5152 Before
the H. State Gov't & Tribal Relations Comm., 68th Leg., 2023-2024 Reg. Sess. (Wash. 2023) (March 10, 2023)
(statement of Sean Flynn, General Counsel, Public Disclosure Commission), available at
https://tvw.org/video/house-state-government-tribal-relations-2023031173/?eventID=2023031173.
14
o The Supreme Court has recognized disclosure requirements as “the least
restrictive means of curbing the evils of campaign ignorance and corruption”.46
Moreover, “disclosure often represents a less restrictive alternative to flat bans on
certain types or quantities of speech.”47 Legal scholars have interpreted this in a
straight forward, common sense manner, expressing support for labels and
skepticism regarding the legality of outright bans.48
• I support the FCC’s decision to apply the rule to both “issue advertisements” and
campaign advertisements.49
• Disclosure of AI generated content is consistent with their statutory obligation to serve
the public interest.50 There is a significant line of case law upholding the state’s interest in
regulation the information environment in political campaigns to reduce confusion among
voters.51 Other case law has reaffirmed the legality of disclosures on campaign ads.52
• Television ads should be required to have both audio and visual disclaimers to comply
with the Americans with Disabilities Act.53
• The language a television and/or radio disclaimer is in should be the primary language of
the ad.54 Given that political ads are used to target specific language speaking
communities,55 this is necessary to ensure listeners receive equal protection under the
law.
• The proposed disclosures and political file requirements will not prevent false,
misleading, or deceptive material in and of themselves.56 Rather, they represent an initial
step to help inform voters about the veracity of the information in front of them.
46 Buckley v. Valeo, 424 U.S. 1, 68 (1976) (Per Curiam).
47 McCutcheon v. Federal Election Comm., 572 U.S. 185, 223 (2014) (Roberts, J.) (plurality opinion).
48 See e.g. Richard L. Hasen, Cheap Speech, 99 (2022) (“Requiring the labeling of deep fakes is a more narrowly
tailored means of dealing with the voter competence problem than laws that would punish deep fakes or require their
removal from websites and social media platforms.”).
49 See NPRM, supra note 1, at 2 n.4.
50 See NPRM, supra note 1, at ¶ 13 (requesting comment on this issue).
51 See e.g. Eu v. S.F. Cnty. Democratic Cent. Comm., 489 U.S. 214, 228–29 (1989) ((“[California argues] it is
necessary to protect primary voters from confusion and undue influence. Certainly the State has a legitimate interest
