Conclusion
In summary, I provide the following recommendations to the FCC regarding their
proposed rule.59
• Use advisory opinions or other tools to provide examples of what the law is supposed to
target. This will mitigate fears raised by others that the regulation is overbroad and targets
too much speech
• Clarify language regarding the role of “event, circumstance, or situation” in the definition
of AI-generated content
• Maintain, as currently written, the text for the disclosure in broadcasts and Political Files
• Revise the proposed rule to only apply within 60 or 90 days of an election (general,
primary, or other type)
• Amend the proposed rule to require broadcasters include a statement on the Political
Disclosure saying the ad buyer failed to respond to the inquiry
• Amend the proposed rule to include penalties for non-compliance by ad buyers
• Amend the proposed rule to fine stations and broadcasters that do not inquire into if
content is AI-generated
• Allow depicted individuals to file a complaint if the AI-generated content is unlabeled
Part 2: AI Generated Content in Public Comments
I believe that many of the comments submitted in response to this rule proposal were
automatically generated, potentially with the assistance of a generative AI tool such as ChatGPT
or Claude. Specifically, I believe the list of names used, used this tool. This part outlines that
concern, using submissions from August 19 and 20, 2024 as an example. However, this pattern
continued throughout the submission cycle and I encourage FCC staff and other relevant entities
to investigate it in more depth to get a full understanding of the problem.
57 See Id. at ¶ 7-8.
58 A catalog of the 10 state laws I examined can be found at Goldberg, supra note 2 at 78.
59 The list of bullet points below seek to aid the reader by collecting all of the recommendations provided in Part 1 in
one place.
16
Concern
On August 19 and 20, 2024 over 230 messages were submitted as public comment to the
FCC for Proceeding MB 24-211. I believe that many, if not most, of these were fraudulently
submitting using artificial intelligence. While below I only investigated these submissions, this
pattern repeated throughout the public submission process (using many of the same comments as
on these two dates), meaning the problem may be more extensive then discussed here.
Message Content
I downloaded a CSV of the results on public comment and manually copy/pasted the
“Brief Comment” from each unique URL into the “Comment” column, which was empty in
Microsoft Excel. I examined the main “core” of each message by removing “sincerely” at the
end, and then used filtering and pivot tables to summarize them. There were six unique texts, but
they form a core of four substantially identical ones.
First, Submission ID 108190369622092 from “Penny Bowdish” wrote “circumstancei”
instead of “circumstance”, generating a unique response. Second, Submission ID
1082071957299 from “Mrs. Michelle Waldrip” showed up as a unique response, but a manual
check of the submission revealed this not to be the case. Thus, there were four substantially
identical messages posted on August 19 and 20.
This is an initial red flag, suggesting a mass campaign to post comment. While this is not
unheard of and many advocacy organizations will encourage their members to do so with
prewritten messages (such as when sending messages to members of Congress), there are two
other red flags.
17
Names and Titles
The inconsistent case in names and (ir)regular use of titles raise additional red flags that
signal this might be AI Generated.
The general pattern in submissions is that a title like Mr. or Ms. was used, followed by a
realistic sounding first and last name. However, a portion of these names did not follow the
regular case you would expect.
For example, Submission ID 108202956810431 came from a “Mr. JOHN DALTON” in
all caps and was signed “Sincerely, Mr. JOHN DALTON”. Below is a non-exhaustive list of
other illustrative names that do not follow traditional casing and title usage, with the submission
ID given in parenthesis.
• ANTHONY BUECHLER (10820585005180)
• Ms. L.A. Skutchan (10820139711648)
• MERRILL Arnold (10820062621382)
• Mr. Jerry weiser Weiser (108201262111185)
• Arlan D., Davis (10820159553703)
• Mr. Rev. Harold Hintzman (10820145177071)
• Craig K (10820015994153)
• Daniel Haehn (10820367629435)
• christy duplantie (1082062458485)
• carissa Fairchild (10820375900901)
• Ms. linda Kimball (10820099388221)
Inconsistent use of capitalization and punctuation, and occasional repetition of words are
common mistakes made by Generative AI tools like ChatGPT or Claude. This is the principal
tell-tale to me that the names were written with a large language model.
While it is possible that the messages were written (with or without Generative AI),
names generated using Generative AI, and the signature was concatenated in a spreadsheet using
that name, I think this is unlikely. “Arlan D., Davis” was submission ID 10820159553703, but
her message was signed without the comma, merely reading “Arlan D. Davis”.
18
A straightforward concatenation in a spreadsheet would not have added or removed a
stray comma; a large language model might have. And if a spreadsheet was set up to remove a
stray comma in the concatenation, I would expect the creator to have removed it when verifying
names and their legitimacy. That is to say, the variety of typos and inconsistencies in names
indicate they were created by a large language model, not a sloppy human.
Moreover, the use of titles in submission ID 10820145177071 is wrong. If the title of
“Reverend” or “Rev” is used instead of and not in addition to, a “Mr”/“Ms.”/“Miss”. Someone
who holds the title of The Reverend is likely to know this and use it appropriately. The
inappropriate usage of it indicates to me that Generative AI was used to write the names.
Legal Analysis
18 U.S.C. § 1001(a) prohibits identity theft and making “in any matter within the
jurisdiction of the executive, legislative, or judicial branch… any materially false, fictitious, or
fraudulent statement or representation”.60 “The statute was made to embrace false and fraudulent
statements or representations where these were knowingly and willfully used in documents or
affidavits ‘in any matter within the jurisdiction of any department or agency of the United
States'.”61 Jurisdiction is given a broad meaning. “[T]here is jurisdiction, within the meaning of §
1001, if the false statement is made in some intended relationship to a matter that is within the
jurisdiction of a federal agency.”62
I believe Popow is an apt analogy. It upheld the conviction of Kenneth Popow, who was
accused of lying on a customs form given by duly authorized a customs agent. The FCC form to
60 18 U.S.C. § 1001(a).
61 United States v. Gilliland, 312 U.S. 86, 93 (1941).
62 United States v. Popow, 821 F.2d 483, 486 (8th Cir. 1987) (citing Ebeling v. United States, 248 F.2d 429, 434 (8th
Cir.), cert. denied, 355 U.S. 907 (1957)).
19
submit a public comment is also filled out by a person and given to the agency. Since public
comment is a required part of the FCC's mandate and duties, it clearly falls within the remit of
“jurisdiction”. That is, public comment is “a matter in which a federal agency [here the FCC] has
the power to act”.63
Moreover, “[t]he false statement need not have actually influenced the agency… and the
agency need not rely on the information in fact for it to be material.”64 That is, the FCC does not
have to act on the potentially falsely submitted statements for them to still violate § 1001.
Additionally, case law indicates “common sense”, such as the analysis regarding the use of the
title Reverend, is sufficient for the government to prove the defendant’s knowledge of
unlawfulness.65
Conclusions
While I have grounded my analysis in evidence and postulated that it was used by
Generative AI, it is not definitive proof. However, if it is proven the messages were generated
with the assistance of artificial intelligence, there could be potential consequences. For example,
in 2017 during the FCC’s consideration of removing Net Neutrality rules, industry groups
organized fraudulent comment submission campaigns, and a single person used automated
software to submit over 7.7 million fake comments.66 Three of the companies involved in this
