King, 735 F.3d 1098, 1108 (9th Cir. 2013).
65 See United States v. Charley, 1 F.4th 637, 644 (9th Cir. 2021) (quoting United States v. Ramirez, 714 F.3d 1134,
1138 (9th Cir. 2013)); see also United States Courts for the Ninth Circuit, Manual of Model Criminal Jury
Instructions, 24.10 False Statement to Government Agency (18 U.S.C. § 1001) (2024), available at
https://www.ce9.uscourts.gov/jury-instructions/node/1168 (collecting cases).
66 See Office of the New York Attorney General, Fake Comments: How U.S. Companies & Partisans Hack
Democracy to Undermine Your Voice, (2021), https://ag.ny.gov/sites/default/files/oag-fakecommentsreport.pdf.
20
reached a $615,000 settlement with the New York Office of the Attorney General.67 Additionally,
the invocation of 18 U.S.C. 1001 might be relevant.
Future investigations should proceed along two lines to substantiate it. First, per the
Privacy Policy which must be agreed to when submitting public comment, IP addresses and
operating system information are collected. This could help identify if all responses came from
the same place and substantiate this claim. Second, the time of submission should be consulted;
if all messages were submitted at or about the same time, this would indicate a coordinated effort
and the potential use of an automated system.
