1.2 Research Questions
This thesis investigates deepfake regulation. American states have recently begun passing
laws prohibiting deepfakes in political advertisements (unless they are labeled accordingly),
indicating states see a need for new laws which mitigate the harms of deepfakes. Ensuring
injuries have a remedy is a critical tenet of common law,6 yet scholarly literature has
inadequately assessed if existing laws could mitigate election-related deepfake risks. This
thesis fills this gap by asking the following guiding research question:
• RQ1: Are new laws prohibiting deepfakes in political advertisements necessary?
That is, are existing laws sufficient to address these harms? For example, legislators,
lobbyists, and members of the public have asked if defamation law can be used.7 Answering
RQ1 requires identifying the scope and application of new and existing laws. To do so, I
explicate the risks presented by deepfakes as articulated by legislators and the risks existing
laws attempt to address. This generates two further research questions:
• RQ2: What risks of deepfakes do legislators envision when passing laws prohibiting
deepfakes in campaign ads?
• RQ3: What risks are addressed by existing laws which may be used to prohibit
deepfakes in campaign ads?
