I combine the risks articulating RQ2 and RQ3 into theoretical “models” to answer the
research questions. Then I compare the models to answer RQ1.
This requires marshaling evidence from three sources. First, I conduct a critical
analysis of the laws themselves. Second, I conduct a thematic analysis on legislative and
public testimony on the bills to understand its purpose and intent. Third, I examine American
case law to see how existing laws have been applied with technologies analogous to
deepfakes, assessing if they can be used to mitigate the risks of deepfakes. Even if a law’s
original intent was not to cover deepfakes, a doctrinal analysis reveals if the laws can (and
should) apply to deepfakes. This is particularly relevant to federal laws, which have broader
scope and application than state laws.
1.3 Argument
I argue old laws address five types of risk: voter intimidation, conspiracies to
undermine rights, robocalls, fraudulent misrepresentations, and impediments to giving
support or advocacy for federal candidate. Two upcoming decisions will be crucial to
determining if a subset of these laws can apply to deepfakes.
Committee hearings on new laws reveals legislators intended the laws to address risks
concerning election security, candidate reputations, and the information environment. Then I
analyze the text of the laws to understand the legal mechanisms being used to address these
risks. I argue deepfake laws enact different legal philosophies via differences in who can be
injured, the role of intent, and different behavioral outcomes.
Overlaying the two risk models, I answer RQ1 and argue the laws reflect differences
in kind of risk, not of degree 8 New laws are candidate and information centric, while old
laws center on effectuating voting rights. The most overlap between the models is found with
8 This language borrows from Animal Legal Def. Fund v. Herbert, 263 F. Supp. 3d 1193 (2017).
Goldberg 10
fraudulent misrepresentations and deceptive injures, which both concern how voters perceive
candidates.
1.4 Road Map
This thesis proceeds as follows. First, I review the literature on deepfakes and their
risks, focusing specifically on electoral risks. 9 I discuss the current state of American election
law, including key decisions on campaign finance and lying, and existing legal scholarship on
deepfakes.
Second, I discuss my methodology for collecting and categorizing laws and
testimony. A major challenge with conducting legal research on state (case) law is the
decentralization of resources. Indeed, this is why most legal scholarship is on federal law. I
discuss how I overcame this barrier to acquire, transcribe, and analyze testimony for the new
laws. By taking an interdisciplinary approach combining law and social sciences, I follow
recent calls to approach deepfakes from an interdisciplinary perspective.10
Third, I develop two theoretical models to answer RQ3 and RQ2. Proceeding
chronologically, RQ3 identifies gaps in old laws, followed by RQ2’s examination of
testimony and the new laws’ text. Fourth, I compare the models to answer RQ1. Fifth, I
discuss how my findings can inform 1) states considering legislation and 2) national rules
proposed July 25, 2024. Finally, I conclude and sketch future research.
