2 Literature Review
This thesis intersects a multidisciplinary literature regarding deepfakes, free speech, and
election law. Accordingly, I first review deepfakes in general, discussing how they impact the
information environment; I do not provide a technical overview.11 Second, I review the risks
AI and deepfakes specifically are posing to elections. Throughout these sections, special
attention is given to the election risk, as this contextualizes the risks new laws seek to
address. Finally, I review the legal context, steadily getting more narrow by reviewing
campaign finance regulation, the “right to lie” in political campaigns, the legal implications
of deepfakes, and legal scholarship specifically examining deepfakes and elections.
2.1 Deepfakes
One form of artificial intelligence (“AI”) is deepfakes. Deepfakes are artificially
generated images, audio, or video purporting to demonstrate a person saying or doing
something they did not do in reality.12 Created using generative adversarial networks, these
are a type of generative AI which is trained on imagery of someone and can replicate their
likeness, including voice and facial expressions.13 Deepfakes only need to be trained on a
small selection of records or images of a person before being able to be produced.14
Despite deepfakes all using the same underlying technology, a May 2024 systematic
review found there was no universal definition of deepfakes in the scholarly literature;
definitions varied based on technology and output medium.15 This echoes my finding that
11 For a review of key technical papers, see Anukriti Kaushal, Sanjay Kumar & Rajeev Kumar, A Review on
