legal definitions vary on these same characteristics. Their review is the most comprehensive
interdisciplinary overview to date, finding research is siloed and cross-disciplinary papers do
not cite each other.16
Robert Chesney and Daniel Keats Citron wrote the first major paper exploring the
harms of deepfakes.17 The strength of their paper is in the breadth – rather than depth – of
risks presented. They note deepfakes can harm individuals, groups, or society at large
depending on how they are used.18 Harms occur because a deepfake purports to be a truthful
representation of reality, tricking people into thinking it is real when it is not.19 They invent
the Liar’s Dividend, a new harm occurring when deepfakes are used to deny something
occurred.20 This exists when, “a skeptical public [is] primed to doubt the authenticity of real
audio and video evidence. This skepticism can be invoked just as well against authentic as
against altered content.”21
Deepfakes harm the information environment by 1) making people question the
content in front of them and 2) increasing the amount of disinformation people see. My prior
work theorized the latter as information environment harm, creating negative externalities
labeling mitigates.22 The former is why “seeing is no longer believing”, presenting new
challenges including the Liar’s Dividend, and regarding how people respond to videos about
