2.2 AI and Elections
Narrowing in slightly, many fear deepfakes and AI more generally could harm the
electoral ecosystem. Due to this thesis’ focus on risks, this section emphasizes the real and
imagined risks of AI and deepfakes in elections.
At a high level, Chesney and Citron’s discussion on risks foregrounds a larger
discussion about the benefits and harms of AI in elections. Political communications
researcher Andreas Jungherr suggests considering AI’s impacts on election related topics like
news, the information environment, and persuasion to better articulate its potential impact.25
Despite that, he argues, “AI is unlikely to impact many aspects of democracy directly” but
notes its perceived effects are almost as important as its actual effects.26 Therefore, analyses
must consider its potential effects, especially since legislators – the primary actor studied here
– speak with the rhetorical ethos giving significant persuasive power to shift the public’s
mindset.
To that end, AI has the potential to be used for good and for ill in elections. Most
scholarship picks one side of this binary, risking falling into a trap of techno-determinism and
techno-optimism.27 Optimists claim algorithms could partially automate election
