Plurality opinions bind lower courts.61 “When a fragmented Court decides a case…
‘the holding of the Court may be viewed as that position taken by those Members who
concurred in the judgments on the narrowest grounds.’”62 However, Alvarez is difficult to
parse because, “the disagreement among Justices is one of kind—whether to apply strict or
proportional scrutiny—not of breadth.”63 That is, the standard it enacts is unclear – a problem
of “kind” – not a question of which portion of potentially applicable cases it should apply to.
Scholars and judges have attempted to find this “narrow ground” of agreement using a dense,
quote heavy approach; this section summarizes this secondary literature, rather than reinvent
the wheel.
