covered by many of the old laws discussed below.
2.3.3 Legal Implications of Deepfakes
While Chesney and Citron initiated the legal writings on deepfakes, the scholarship
has grown since. The literature can be classified into three categories: writings about the first
amendment implications of deepfakes, assessing if deepfakes violate existing laws, and
approaching deepfakes as form of misinformation or disinformation. I assess each of these in
turn.
Scholar Marc Blitz has written extensively on the First Amendment implications of
deepfakes.75 His work is highly technical and theoretical, focusing on the distinction between
“coverage”, “protection”, and “authorship”.76 In the political context, Jessica Ice argues
“narrowly crafted injunctions against defamatory political deepfakes should be permitted.”77
Bryn Wells-Edwards considered audio deepfakes and voice in the political context, focusing
on defamation and false light.78 By exclusively analyzing the specific medium of deepfakes
