Matthew Bodi discussed First Amendment questions including, “are deepfakes
protected speech?”80 My comparative approach is more thorough than his brief five-
paragraph comparison of Texas and California deepfake laws.81 Moreover, his comparison
was descriptive, identifying differences like civil or criminal liability but not deeply
examining its impact.82 I expand the descriptive analysis and distinguish myself by covering
more states, using additional evidence, and focusing my comparison on intent.
Second, several student notes have broadly asked the question “do deepfakes run
afoul of an existing law?” They approach this question from perspectives like privacy,
defamation, trademark, and copyright law.83 In the context of deepfake pornography, others
have argued for a private right of action to broaden the scope of recovery laws.84 Finally,
others examined if creating deepfake pornography is actionable under state tort law.85
Third, legal scholars have examined deepfakes from an informational perspective.
Numerous scholars have examined the legality of disinformation and fake news in elections
and postulated different ways to stop it.86 One proposal involves creating a “right of reply”
