3 Methods
This section proceeds as follows. First, I contextualize and justify my methods.
Second, I discuss my inclusion/exclusion criteria and data gathering process, transcription
and coding process, and analytical methods. Third, I discuss methodology for finding old
laws. Finally, I briefly discuss ethical concerns.
Throughout the data collection and analysis process, approximately 35 daily research
memos totaling 16,024 words over 31 single spaced pages were written. These recorded
methods, analysis, and ideas, documenting my evolving thinking over the course of the
project.
3.1 Purpose of Methods
This thesis uses interdisciplinary methods consistent with law and qualitative research.
I have considered the limitations of these methods.
This thesis concerns law. It applies qualitative methods like transcription, coding, and
thematic analysis to legal texts to understand risks envisioned by the speakers and authors.
However, its primary goal is building legal theory to answer research questions. Qualitative
data collection methods are used to the extent that they assist in theory building, but I employ
multiple modes of analysis including thematic analysis and critical analysis to inform theory.
These methods help excavate decision making processes, making them consistent with
qualitative research and my research questions.97 Bridging this disciplinary gap is a major
methodological contribution.
3.2 On Qualitative (Legal) Methods
The literature on legal research methodology is sparse; where it exists, its
methodological language differs from the social sciences. “Qualitative legal research” is
97 See Nikolitsa Grigoropoulou & Mario L. Small, The Data Revolution in Social Science Needs Qualitative
Research, 6 NATURE HUM. BEHAV. 904, 904 (2022).
Goldberg 26
defined in opposition to quantitative legal research.98 Qualitative work analyzes texts, seeks
patterns and trends, and crafts arguments based on them.99 Unlike social science research,
legal scholarship is not concerned about data quality, positionality, and inclusion/exclusion
criteria. Even when legal scholars conduct case studies, they approach evidence considered
by courts a priori and do not investigate the role of the Rules of Evidence in shaping the legal
reasoning and outcome; legal scholars examine evidence in a vacuum.100 Law reviews do not
prioritize deep discussions of methodology, with most legal scholarship relegating a methods
explanation to a footnote or appendix.101
Thus, qualitative and legal scholars speak different languages, even though they use
similar methods like case studies.102 Katerina Linos and Melissa Carolson’s attempt to bridge
this gap is insightful.103 They argue doctrinal work lacks generalizability and has selection
bias by virtue of selecting cases from precedential courts.104 They suggest more extensive
sampling methods are needed to make generalizable claims, requiring consideration of
98 Ian Dobinson & Francis Johns, Legal Research as Qualitative Research, in RESEARCH METHODS FOR LAW
18, 19 (Mike McConville & Wing Hong Chui eds., 2 ed. 2017) (“Qualitative legal research [is] define[d] as
simply non-numerical and as such, contrasted with quantitative (numerical) research.”).
99 See e.g. Abbe R Gluck, The States as Laboratories of Statutory Interpretation: Methodological Consensus
and the New Modified Textualism, 119 YALE L. J. 1750 (2010) (classifying state statutory interpretation schemes
based on a reading of case law); Richard Hasen, Reining in the Purcell Principle, 43 FLA. ST. U. L. REV. 427
(2016) (identifying an emergent legal principle based a close reading of case law).
100 This is increasingly concerning because recent scholars have focused on the importance (and problems) of
using the entire docket, rather than just published opinions, in legal research. See e.g. Zachary D. Clopton &
Aziz Z. Huq, The Necessary and Proper Stewardship of Judicial Data, 76 STAN. L. REV. 893 (2024) (discussing
how docket and judicial data are recorded and lost when being uploaded to docket searches and commercial
legal search engines).
101 See e.g. Gluck, supra note 99 at 1773–1774 n.73 (describing methodology for reviewing cases); Katerina
Linos & Melissa Carlson, Qualitative Methods for Law Review Writing, 84 U. CHI. L. REV. 213, 216 n.9 (2017)
(describing search methodology to create tables); Abbe R Gluck & Lisa Schultz Bressman, Statutory
Interpretation from the Inside: Methods Appendix, 65 STAN. L. REV. 1 (2013) (methods appendix for larger, 125
page article).
