3.4 Transcription
Details of each of the 25 hearings, including its transcription method, are in Appendix
3. The first five transcripts were transcribed manually. The structured nature of committee
hearings meant it was possible to get high quality automated transcripts because people did
not speak over each other. Two methods were used. First, Washington and Wisconsin
provided exportable automated transcripts for closed captioning. The recordings were
listened to, and manually cleaned to verify the accuracy of transcripts. Second, .mp3 files
were imported into Microsoft Word Online’s GDPR and University ethics compliant
“Transcribe” function.112 Manual verification was carried out for California, Florida, Idaho,
Michigan, and Minnesota transcripts. Finally, Indiana hearings required manual transcription.
For manual transcription only the portion of the hearing covering the bill was
transcribed. For closed captions and manual verification of automated transcripts, the pre-
generated text was searched for the bill introduction (e.g. “introducing HB 1133”) and only
that portion was cleaned. All transcripts noted where people spoke over each other.113
Treating hearings as audio and not videos was informed by the research question.
They concern the “talk” of qualitative analysis and how this manifests as risk models, not the
interpretation of what legislator’s say or the broader contextual features.114 When looking to
committee hearings, scholars are exclusively interested in the text and generally ignore the
conversation’s broader context and contextual features like nonverbal communication.115
112 This feature was only available for Microsoft Word Online using the Google Chrome browser.
