3.5 Coding Process
Transcripts were imported into NVivo for two rounds of inductive coding, proceeding
alphabetically by state. Coding was guided by the research question, so codes were only
applied to substantive portions of the transcripts (i.e. not to legislative procedure). Notes were
taken in research memos.
The first round coded high level risks and concerns about potential deepfake harms.
The persuasive act of describing the bill to colleagues allowed the sponsor to articulate their
envisioned risks. Other codes focused on alternative solutions to deepfakes and legal
concerns raised by the bill. These revealed themselves in statements of non-sponsoring
legislators.
Between rounds a coding hierarchy was ideated to make sense of the dispersed codes
and organize risks.117
The second round deconstructed the different risk models in more depth, focusing on
how a specific action or fact was a risk. For example, the “election year” code was created in
the second round, as it operationalized a specific type of “election security” risk. This
revealed itself between rounds.
After the second round, a coding hierarchy was created based on four potential themes.
A theory diagram was created linking them together.
116 See e.g. Saouré Kouamé & Feng Liu, Capturing Emotions in Qualitative Strategic Organization Research,
19 STRATEGIC ORG. 97 (2021) (reviewing recent studies in organizational research for how they capture
emotions); Poland, supra note 113 at 291–293 (discussing how emotions and facial expressions are not recorded
on transcripts and how this is a form of data loss).
117 See Tom Richards & Lyn Richards, Using Hierarchical Categories in Qualitative Data Analysis, in
COMPUTER-AIDED QUALITATIVE DATA ANALYSIS: THEORY, METHODS AND PRACTICE 80 (Udo Kelle, Gerald
Prein, & Katherine Bird eds., 1995) (arguing code heiarchys are a useful tool in organizing codes and making
sense of otherwise disparate codes).
Goldberg 31
3.6 Analysis
Informed by the theory diagram, claim tables were made presenting potential themes
and their subcomponents. This process indicated only three were viable (supported by
sufficient evidence). The three themes indicated different risks, and claim tables focused on
identifying their subcomponents. Subcomponents emerged out of the underlying codes.
Claim tables contained the state, speaker, hearing, quote, rudimentary analysis, sub-
claim it represented, and the strength of the quote. This last aspect adopts Rockmann and
Vough’s framework of partial, tantalizing, workhorse, and anchor quotes.118
The claim tables and theory diagram assisted in developing risk models (a type of
conceptual model), and thereby answer RQ3. This process closely hewed to Naeem and
colleagues’ recommendations to develop conceptual models as the last stage in the analysis
process and ensure the model answers the research question.119 Indeed, the research question
lends itself to this by effectively asking, “what is the conceptual model?”
3.7 Old Laws
Shifting to RQ2, preexisting laws were identified and included based professional
knowledge of election law, including frequent causes of action used in civil litigation over the
last five years. This was supplemented with relevant criminal provisions listed in the
Department of Justice’s Prosecution Guide for Election Crimes.120 The laws discussed in §
4.1.2 and § 4.4.2 drew on Ardia and Ringel who summarized and categorized over 150 state
laws.121 Their footnotes were searched for the 10 states of interest, revealing 37 laws which
