rights. Rep. Rubel articulated this distinction by creating (but not sharing) a deepfake of a
colleague, because if real, it might harm her colleague. In other words, “a corollary of the
right to associate is the right not to associate.”210 Effectuating this right requires autonomy a
priori, partly explaining why laws coercing association by all but requiring a form of
association to win have been struck down.211
More philosophically, uncontrolled speech violates autonomy by violating one’s right
to control the public presentation of their image. This slightly diverges from Bernie Hogan’s
concept of curation where third parties share and modify content.212 However, curation is
limited to user uploaded content. Deepfakes diverge from curation by allowing the creation of
realistic fabrications. While Hogan argues there is a distinction between one’s true
representation and a deepfake of them,213 I argue the underlying harm to autonomy is present
in both, constituting a legally cognizable injury: uncontrolled speech. This combination of
autonomy and publicity distinguishes deepfakes from other potentially false representations
of an individual, like writing something misleading about another in a private diary or
journal.
