5.2.1.2 Penalties and Remedies
Broadly, penalties can be sorted into two buckets. Criminal penalties are a prohibition
on creation of deepfakes, while civil relief is available via an injunction upon injury.244 The
details in how states vary within these buckets reveal the specific risks the laws address.
5.2.1.2.1 Texas and Criminal Intent
As a matter of common law, all criminal laws have a mens rea requirement of a
“guilty mind” which requires intent, even if it is not explicitly written into the statute.245
Texas is the only state with criminal prohibitions to have two explicit intent requirements.
The definition of “deep fake video” includes “intent to deceive.”246 An offense is committed,
“if the person, with intent to injure a candidate or influence the result of an election” creates a
deepfake and shares it within 30 days of an election.247 Therefore, intent must be
demonstrated at creation and sharing. In contrast, other states require intent at only one of
these stages. Importantly, this raises the bar for the type of conduct prohibited under the law.
243 MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 168.932f(4) (West).
