7.2 New Proposals
On July 25, 2024 the Federal Communications Commission proposed a new rule
mandating disclosure of the use of AI in radio and television campaign ads.272 They requested
comment, so I briefly sketch out initial thoughts that can be gleaned from this thesis.
The rule should not be interpreted by legislators as a cure for all the risks of deepfakes. It
only mandates broadcasters 1) ask entities buying airtime if the ad contains AI and 2)
disclose the response. It does not provide a remedy if that entity lies in their disclosure.
Additionally, it does not cover social media or platforms like YouTube. While YouTube has
policies prohibiting deepfakes in ads, these are subject to change based on corporate
incentives and are not as rigorous as government regulation.
Thus, while the proposed rule could create a uniform, national policy mandating
disclosure, it does not provide a national remedy for injuries. This only addresses the
informational risks, and not election security or reputational risks because it does not provide
a remedy for uncontrolled speech. Therefore, the rule only mitigates a portion of deepfake
risks.
272 See Notice of Proposed Rulemaking in the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements, MB-Docket No. 24-211 (Federal Commc'n. Comm., July 25,
2024), https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/FCC-24-74A1.pdf.
Goldberg 74
8 Conclusion
To conclude, in this thesis I have asked and answered three research questions:
1. Are new laws prohibiting unlabeled deepfakes in political ads necessary?
2. What risks of deepfakes do legislators envision when passing laws prohibiting
deepfakes in campaign ads?
3. What risks are addressed by existing laws which may be used to prohibit deepfakes in
campaign ads?
To answer RQ2 and RQ3 I analyzed legislative committee hearings, committee
documentation, and case law to develop models of the risks legislators envisioned when
passing new and old laws. I found new laws intend to address risks concerning election
security, legislator’s reputations, and the information environment. In contrast, old laws
addressed voter intimidation, conspiracies to violate civil rights, robocalls, fraudulent
misrepresentations, and barriers towards giving “support or advocacy”. In the limited set of
circumstances where a deepfake does one of these things, the old laws have some potential of
being useful. However, primarily these risks are substantially different from the risks new
laws envision; risks differ in kind, not degree. If the laws differed in degree, then old laws
could be repurposed when faced with the new technology.
Meanwhile, some states have laws prohibiting fraudulently misrepresenting yourself
or lying in certain aspects of campaign speech and political ads. For example, some states
prohibit falsely representing yourself as an incumbent. I argue these “factual prohibitions”
can be used to prohibit specific types of content in a deepfake. But they are not a broad, wide-
ranging prohibition, significantly limiting their utility.
Moreover, I have demonstrated the drafters of new bills did not consider the lessons
from old laws specifically regarding intent requirements. Adding an intent requirement
creates too high of a standard when seeking relief. Additionally, the laws vary in their
Goldberg 75
philosophical approaches to harms, yielding insights for recently proposed federal rules
mandating labels in political ads.
Accordingly, I argued old laws are insufficient to address the risks of deepfakes in
political ads, yielding an affirmative answer to RQ1. While the new laws are an appropriate
step forward to initiate coverage of new risks the legal system is ill-equipped to handle, they
fail to fully address all the risks of deepfakes.
Scholars can build on this project in several ways. Most political science literature on
state policy variation is quantitative,273 but there is room for qualitative approaches
examining the impact of differences in similar but not identical policies on outcomes, and in
how policies are spread between states.274 Additionally, scholars should study the effects of
these laws. Once case law develops, they might consider examining differences or similarities
in outcomes.275 The new state laws have small differences which I have argued could be large
in practice. How are these differences interpreted? Does the difference in definitions or
specific prohibitions explain or yield differential outcomes? In tandem, scholars should study
how well the new laws address their intended risks.
273 Jake Grumbach is the leading scholar of state policy variation. He has investigated the spread of election
laws and subversion policies, and health care, finding strong polarization in their spread. See e.g. JACOB M.
GRUMBACH, LABORATORIES AGAINST DEMOCRACY: HOW NATIONAL PARTIES TRANSFORMED STATE POLITICS
(2022) (investigating a wide array of policies); Jacob M. Grumbach, Laboratories of Democratic Backsliding,
117 AM. POLIT. SCI. REV. 967 (2023) (investigating subnational democratic performance indicators); Jacob M.
