Appendix 1: The American Legal System
American law is highly federated, with states and the federal government maintaining
different powers. States regulate the “time, place, and manner” of federal elections, unless
federal legislation preempts it.276 Both state and federal laws are subject to judicial review in
federal court.277 Federal courts have jurisdiction when challenging a law or making a claim
based on federal law or the constitution.278 A case is only heard in state court if deals with
state law and state constitutional claims.
Both the federal and state courts operate at common law but rarely draw on
international common law. However, they have recognized the English common law tort of
denial of the right to vote279 which originated in Ashby v. White.280 The nature of common
law legal system means the age of case law does not matter as long as it has not been
overturned and is appropriate precedent. Supreme Court precedent controls in all federal
courts is, while circuit decisions only control in their circuit. When confronting a new
question in a circuit, circuit and district courts often look to other circuits.281 States’ take
different views on how controlling Supreme Court decisions are on interpreting similar state
constitutional clauses, but nearly unanimously agree lower federal court interpretations are
not controlling.282
