1756,10918097435179,2024-09-18T00:49:06.075Z,Silas FitzGerald,,,"Before the
FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION
Washington, D.C. 20230

In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements

COMMENTS OF SILAS FITZGERALD

MB Docket No. 24-211

The FCC

The Federal Communications Commission was established by the Communications Act of 1934. Today, it oversees communication across the country via radio, television, wire, satellite, and cable. Its jurisdiction includes areas such as broadband access, fair competition, radio frequency management, and media responsibility.

The proposed rule

The FCC has proposed a rule requiring radio and television broadcast stations, cable operators, DVS providers, SDARS licensees involved in origination programming, and permit holders transmitting programming under section 325(c) of the Act to include an on-air announcement for all political ads that use AI-generated content, clearly disclosing the use of such content in the advertisement.

The Commission also proposes requiring these licensees and regulated entities to include a notice in their online political files for all political ads featuring AI-generated content, indicating that the ad contains such content.

The proposed standard language does not sufficiently specify what aspects of a television ad are AI-generated

For television ads, the Commission proposes requiring broadcasters to state with either sound or text that “This message contains information generated in whole or in part by artificial intelligence.” However, in a television advertisement there are both elements of both sight and sound, and the rule should require broadcasters to specify which aspects of the ad were created with generative AI. 

For example, any visuals that are AI-generated should be accompanied by a text disclaimer along the lines of “This video was generated by artificial intelligence” for the entire duration of the AI-generated visual. And conversely, if an AI-generated voiceover accompanies the ad, an oral disclaimer should precede it, along the lines of “The following narration was generated by artificial intelligence.”

This would better serve the purpose of the rule by more specifically informing viewers which parts of the ad are AI-generated and which are authentic video or voice recording. One can imagine a near future where all political ads use some amount of AI-generation, in which the current proposed rule would be rendered essentially meaningless. 

Although this heightened level of specificity would slightly increase the administrative burden on regulated entities, the increase would be negligible

The Commission describes the administrative burden created by the NPRM as modest. One concern the Commission may have in considering this comment would be that making the disclaimer more specific would require broadcasters and other affected Commission licensees to ask more specific questions in order to get the requisite information from the person or entity requesting the purchase of airtime. 

While this is true, the increased burden would not be significant because they could easily create standardized forms for purchasers to complete. Questions could be, for example, “Does this advertisement contain AI-generated audio?” The slightly increased burden will be well worth it in order to more accurately inform viewers.",3357
