A guide on securing election infrastructure from malign foreign actorsthat wasproducedbythe
CISA, the FBI, and the Office of the Director ofNationalIntelligence16providesinsightintothe
ways in which malign foreign actors might use AI to interfere or attemptto underminebothour
electoral processandour national security.
The guide cites an increase in both the use of AI by foreign actors in theirattempts toinfluence
our electoral process and manipulate the American public and experimentation by these same
foreign actors into new methods of utilizing AI to achieve their objectives.17 And as theevents
detailed below show, the public is starting to see just how these attempts to influence our
elections playout.
In July, the Department of Justice seized two internet domains allegedly used by Russian
operatives posing as Americans that were used to disseminate MDM both here in the United
States and in other countries. These “bot-farms” used AI to create falsesocialmediaprofilesto
push support for theRussianinvasionof Ukraine.18
Then earlier this month, the Department of Justice announced a series of actions specifically
targeting Russian attempts toinfluence this year’sPresidentialElection. First, the Department of
Justice announced that it seized thirty-two more internet domains allegedly being used by
Russian operatives to spreadMDMwith U.S.DeputyAttorneyGeneral LisaMonaco statingthat
three Russian companies were using fake social media profiles to disseminate pro-Russian
MDM.19
Additionally, indictments handed down against two employees of Russianstatemediacompany,
RT, for allegedlyfunneling$10million toright-wingpodcastersvia afrontcompany that wasset
up in Tennessee in efforts to spread pro-RussianMDMwere unsealedin theSouthern District of
New York.20
The value of these attacks was highlighted by Bret Schafer, a senior fellow at the Alliance for
SecuringDemocracyof the GermanMarshallFundwho noted:
