Russia is certainly not the only foreign nation pursuing such attempts to influence our electoral
process, and whilethespecific goals andmethodsofthesevarious malignforeignoperativeswill
of course vary, one thing remains constant, namely the threat their actions pose could have a
detrimental impact on the security of our nation and the American public’s trust in our
institutions.
HowAIIncreasesthe Volumeand Amplification ofMDM
AI tools, like text generators and deep fakes, can create realistic but false content quickly. This
includes fake news articles, misleading videos, and doctored images. AI enables the rapid
production of large volumes of content, making it easier to flood social media and other
platforms with misleading information. A study analyzed over 10 million tweets from a
month-long period toinvestigate thepolarized Brexit discussiononTwitterduring the 2019U.K.
elections.22 It found that misinformation was significantly amplified through interactions
between users and bots, demonstrating how coordinated online activities greatly increased the
spread of falsenarratives.
Additionally, AI-powered bots and fake accounts can engage in discussions, spread false
information, and amplify messages bycreating theillusionof widespreadsupportor controversy.
AI-driven algorithms tend to reinforce existing beliefs by showingusers contentthatalignswith
their views. This can create echo chambers where misinformation is amplified and alternative
viewpointsaresuppressed.
AsDr.WalidSaad, amachine learningexpert atVirginiaTech, hasstated:
The ability to create websites that host fake news or fake information has been
around since the inception of the Internet, and they pre-date the AI revolution.
With the advent of AI, it became easier to sift through large amounts of
information and create ‘believable’ stories and articles . . . This AI-assisted
21 Dan De Luce & Kevin Collier, Russia’s 2024 Election Interference Has Already Begun, NBC NEWS (Feb. 26, 2024),
https://www.nbcnews.com/news/investigations/russias-2024-election-interference-already-begun-rcna134204.
22 MatteoBruno,RenaudLambiotte&FabioSaracco,BrexitandBots:CharacterizingtheBehaviourofAutomatedAccountsonTwitterDuring
theUKElection,11EPJDATASCI.17(2022),https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8938738/.
refinement of how the information is presented makes such fake sites more
dangerous.23
AI’s capabilities in content creation,personalization, andmanipulation make itan unprecedented
and extremelypowerfultool for spreading andamplifying MDM. Wecan nolonger treatthe two
issues separately. While forms of MDM existed well before the rise of AI, the two are now
inextricably intertwined. Now, AI can not only create new sources of MDM, but it can also
exponentially increasethedistribution and reachofthat very sameMDM.
Conclusion
The disclosure requirements contained in the proposed rulewillhelp mitigate, butnoteliminate,
the threats posed by MDM, promote transparency, and will help equip voters with information
they need to navigate the media and electoral landscape with more confidence and trust in our
public institutions.
In 2019, the state of Texas became a national leader in the field of combatting AI-generated
MDM intheelectoral process byaddingthe following provisiontothe Texas ElectionCode:
(d) A personcommitsan offenseif theperson,with intenttoinjureacandidate or
influence theresult ofan election:
(1) createsadeep fakevideo; and
(2) causesthe deepfakevideo tobepublishedor distributedwithin30
daysof an election.
(e) ""deep fake video"" means a video, created with the intent to deceive, that
appearsto depictarealpersonperforming anactionthat didnotoccurinreality.24
While it is outside the jurisdiction of the Commission to implement such a rule at the national
level absent Congressional action, we wanted to provide this information to the Commission as
an example of what furthertypes of actionmay,atsome point intime,beimplementedtofurther
the vital goal of increased transparency that formsthe basisofthis proposedrule. But wewould
be remiss in notpointing out that,as thedeep fakeincidentwithSpeakerPhelan discussedabove
shows, even this first of its kind legislation has proven to be insufficient on its own to staunch
thespread of AIgeneratedMDM.
23 Walid Saad, AI and the Spread of Fake News Sites: Experts Explain How to Counteract Them, VA. TECH (Feb. 22, 2024),
https://news.vt.edu/articles/2024/02/AI-generated-fake-news-experts.html.
24TEX.ELEC.CODE§ 255.004.
Thus, the ever evolving nature of AI requires an equally evolving regulatory and legislative
framework with clear enforcementmechanisms. Asweareall undoubtedly aware,this proposed
rule will not, by itself, end or eliminate the threats posed by AI generated andamplifiedMDM,
but it is,attheveryleast, a stepin theright direction ofaddressing the vitalneedof providing the
American people with more transparency crucial information as they participate inourelectoral
process.
For all of the reasons discussed throughout this comment,TCRP stronglyurges theCommission
to adopt andimplement theproposedruleas expeditiously aslegallypossible.
Sincerely,
CarlBlair Victoria Gonzalez AmyAbbott
