1979,1091859929209,2024-09-18T19:17:43.633Z,Adobe Inc.,,,"Before the
Federal Communications Commission
Washington, D.C. 20554
In the Matter of )
)
Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial )
Intelligence-Generated Content in Political ) MB Docket No. 24-211
Advertisements )
COMMENTS OF ADOBE
Adobe Inc. (“Adobe”) submits these comments in response to the Federal Communications
Commission’s (“Commission” or “FCC”) Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (“Notice”) in the above-
referenced proceeding.1 We thank the Commission for its continued work to provide greater
transparency regarding the use of artificial intelligence- (“AI”) generated content in political
advertising and recognize the challenges the Commission faces in trying to determine whether it has
the statutory authority to adopt the proposed on-air disclosure and political file requirements.
Adobe believes this Notice represents a unique opportunity for the Commission to consider
how to increase transparency for consumers and voters with respect to the use of generative AI
(“GAI”) in political ads. As the Commission considers the extent of its authority in this area and
whether and how best to deploy such authority, we believe the FCC should evaluate how emerging
provenance2 technologies, like Content Credentials, discussed below, could be integrated into the
Commission’s proposed disclosure framework to provide voters increased transparency during an
election cycle. Here, the collaborative work being done in organizations like the Content Authenticity
1 Federal Communications Commission, Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated
Content in Political Advertisements, 89 Fed. Reg. 63381 (Aug. 5, 2024).
2 Provenance refers to the basic trustworthy facts about the origins of a piece of digital content (photo,
video, audio file). That is, how a piece of digital content has changed over time, how it has been edited, combined,
manipulated, etc.
1
Initiative (“CAI”)3 and the Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity (“C2PA”)4 is illustrative of
the types of efforts the Commission should consider leveraging in furtherance of achieving its mission
of upholding the core values of our laws—consumer protection, universal service, national security,
and public safety—all while keeping pace with ever-changing and advancing technologies. We look
forward to engaging further with the Commission on this important topic.
What follows is background on this global coalition and the tools and technologies being
developed to bring layers of verifiable trust and transparency to digital content. We also provide
recommendations for the Commission’s consideration to evaluate how these capabilities could be
integrated into any forthcoming transparency requirements for broadcasters with respect to the use of
AI-generated content in political ads.
Introduction
At Adobe, our mission is to empower everyone to deliver the world’s best digital experiences.
Since our founding in December 1982, we have continued to pioneer transformative technologies that
allow our customers—who range from emerging artists to global brands—to unleash their creativity,
perfect their craft, and power their businesses in a digital world.
Our tools like Photoshop, Illustrator, and Premiere Pro empower millions of creators around
the world to create compelling assets like photos, videos, and illustrations. Our Document Cloud
products support organizations’ digital document needs, and our Experience Cloud business supports
businesses with their website and e-commerce experiences. And, with the release of Adobe Firefly, a
family of creative generative AI (“GAI”) models, Adobe is enabling users to channel their creativity in
3 The Content Authenticity Initiative (“CAI”) is a group of creators, technologists, journalists, and activists
leading the global effort to address digital misinformation and content authenticity. CAI is focused on promoting
and providing an open, cross-industry approach to media transparency.
4 The Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity addresses the prevalence of misleading
information online through the development of technical standards for certifying the source and history (or
provenance) of media content.
2
ways they never imagined possible, all while protecting their creative rights and helping ensure their
creations are safe for commercial use.5
From animating video to quickly changing the color of the sky, AI has powered hundreds of
capabilities across Adobe tools that creators love. And now, GAI is the latest version of AI that is
transforming the way we work, create, and communicate.
We believe that generative Al done right will amplify human creativity and capabilities to new
levels with deeper insights, accelerated task performance, and improved decision-making ability. As
we continue to harness the power of generative Al, we are committed to developing and deploying
generative Al in line with our Al Ethics principles of accountability, responsibility, and transparency,
while considering its broader impact on society.6
While AI is a powerful technology transforming how we work, create, and communicate, it can
be misused by bad actors to erode the pillars of our democracy. Nowhere is this more apparent than
in our political process, particularly with the growing use of AI-generated images in political
campaigns and advertising heading into the 2024 Presidential election. As these technologies
proliferate and their quality increases, and as the Commission notes in its Notice, it will be
“increasingly more difficult for voters to discern what is real and what is fake,”7 particularly without
some way to determine the origins of a piece of digital media and how it has evolved over time.
According to a recent Adobe survey, nearly half of respondents (44%) reported being misled or
believing election-related misinformation in the past three months and 43% are now less likely to trust
election content online. Companies can implement safeguards in their AI systems, as Adobe has done,
such as content moderation and AI governance processes to help combat these challenges. But as
5 Adobe, “Adobe Unleashes New Era of Creativity for All With the Commercial Release of Generative
AI,” (September 13, 2023).
6 Adobe Blog, “Responsible innovation in the age of generative AI,” Dana Rao (March 21, 2023).
7 89 Fed. Reg. at 63383.
3
theuse of GAI in the political space increases, , the Commission also has an important role to play and
should take a proactive approach in determining how to best to ensure that voters are made aware of
the use of AI in political ads.
Many efforts to combat deepfakes have focused on detection. However, detection
technologies still face significant limitations.8 In particular, they tend to struggle to identify when
someone made edits to an original real image, and such technologies often do not catch fake images
of lower quality. Adobe itself reviewed the state-of-the-art detection technology with its AI and image
scientists. But we concluded that detection technology would lag behind the ability to create synthetic
images, and consumers would need an extremely high level of accuracy of an AI deepfake detector
before it could be used. That technology does not seem possible in the medium term.
Instead, we focused on providing a way for good actors to be trusted. When all content can be
disbelieved, it will be critical to give good actors a way to prove what they are saying is true. And so,
along with others, we founded the CAI, which developed an open-source provenance technology,
called Content Credentials, dedicated to this approach.
The CAI and the C2PA
In today’s digital world, content creation is exploding. Thanks to new technologies,
developing, editing, and distributing digital content has become more powerful and more accessible.
However, the same tools used to make and share legitimate content could also be misused by bad
actors to create and spread disinformation or misinformation. Without tools to help people
understand how a piece of content came to be, people risk believing lies and no longer accepting the
truth. However, with new tools and approaches pioneered by the CAI and C2PA, the technologies to
8 See, e.g., Schaul, K., Verma, P., and Zakrzewski, C., “See why AI detection tools can fail to catch election
deepfakes,” WASHINGTON POST (Aug. 15, 2024); available at
https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/interactive/2024/ai-detection-tools-accuracy-deepfakes-election-2024/.
4
provide people with a simple, reliable method of determining the provenance and authenticity of the
digital content they are seeing now exist.
In 2019, Adobe co-founded the CAI, with the goal of restoring trust and transparency in digital
content. In just four years, the CAI has grown to more than 3,000 members across industries, ranging
from technology companies like Adobe, NVIDIA, Qualcomm, and Microsoft; GAl developers like
Stability AI; news organizations like the New York Times and the Wall Street Journal; camera
companies like Nikon and Leica to academic organizations, non-profits, and more. The CAI’s Content
Credentials technology is built upon an open technical standard developed by the C2PA, a non-profit
within the Linux Foundation dedicated exclusively to drafting technical standards and specifications as
a foundation for universal content provenance.
Content Credentials are cryptographically signed, tamper-evident data that can be embedded
into various types of assets (images, videos, audio, documents, etc.) and essentially function as a
“nutrition label” for digital content. Users can choose to turn on Content Credentials, allowing them to
attach information they choose to a piece of content such as their name, the date, and details on the
edits that were made. Because all the data inside a Content Credential is digitally signed, it cannot be
modified without breaking the signature, so if any tampering does occur along the way, the tampering
will be evident, and the public will know to be skeptical. Content Credentials are based on the same
technology (cryptographic hashes and signatures) used by secure websites and secure document
signing. In fact, the U.S. Government Publishing Office (“GPO”) has been leveraging this technology to
securely publish official U.S. government documents for the last 20 years.
Content Credentials can also enable people to see whether AI was used. For example: Adobe
automatically attaches Content Credentials to content generated in our Firefly generative AI family of
models to indicate that it was AI-generated. But, more importantly, especially when AI is used as just
one part of content creation, Content Credentials can show how it was used. . Beyond creative use
5
cases, there are many reasons to use AI in newsworthy content. For instance, say a presidential
candidate would like to use an image of herself shaking hands with voters outside a polling station in
an upcoming campaign ad, but the background of the image has cars in it. The candidate may want to
use AI to quickly remove the visible license plate numbers to protect people’s privacy. Content
Credentials technology gives the good actors, like candidates who want to deliver trustworthy content,
a way to be believed, while still allowing them to use AI to add quality and clarity to their work more
easily and efficiently than ever before. By adding this level of transparency, people can make an
informed decision about whether to trust the AI-edited content they are consuming.
Additionally, Content Credentials technology can help ensure that the engagement of the
public with elected representatives—a cornerstone of democracy—is not drowned out by AI-
generated noise. By providing verifiable information about what they are sharing with their
constituents, elected representatives can foster a sense of trust and transparency in their engagements
with the public. This level of transparency helps citizens make more informed decisions about trusting
what they see online and helps create a more trustworthy digital space. Much the way consumers
have come to look for the Energy Star as a trusted signal to indicate an appliance’s energy efficiency,
with the widespread use of this solution, the American public will come to expect Content Credentials
on trustworthy content they consume and be skeptical when Content Credentials are absent.
Content Credentials works with many forms of media beyond photos, including video, audio,
and documents, and in areas as diverse as forensics, archival collections, scientific reports, AI training,
overhead imagery, and AI-generated campaign materials. Wherever the integrity and authenticity of
information is at stake, Content Credentials can be leveraged to provide trust and transparency.
Recommendations
Federal campaigns will continue to leverage GAI capabilities for campaign communications,
fundraising, and advertising. GAI can be a valuable tool to increase productivity and creativity for
6
campaigns. However, the question then becomes, how do we separate the good actors who are using
AI to add quality and clarity to their work from the bad ones who misuse this technology to mislead
voters, and how do we provide Americans with the transparency they deserve? Adobe believes
Content Credentials technology and the C2PA open standard is part of the solution to the question.
As the FCC determines the extent of its authority to regulate the use of AI in the generation of
political ads, Adobe urges the Commission to review the CAI’s open-source tool kit and Content
Credential technology and require this, or similar provenance technology, in any forthcoming
transparency requirements for broadcasters with respect to the use of AI-generated content in political
ads. This would afford the public a level of transparency about what they are consuming and better
equip them to make an informed decision about whether to trust the material or not.
GAI will continue to be wielded for both good and bad purposes, particularly when it comes to
our elections process. However, the technologies now exist to help prevent the misuse of AI tools to
deceive voters by providing them with more sophisticated information. We respectfully urge the FCC
to assess how these technologies could be used to bring greater transparency to AI-generated content
in political ads.
As an initial step in this assessment, the FCC should direct several of its standing Advisory
Committees to review how these technologies could help achieve important portions of the
Commission’s mission. For example, the FCC should direct both its Technological Advisory Council to
review the technical aspects regarding how equipment manufacturers and other FCC-regulated
entities could and should use Content Credentials to achieve this greater transparency and its
Consumer Advisory Council to examine how malicious GAI imagery in political ads could harm
consumers. Moreover, given numerous recent reports about foreign governments’ attempts to hack
the major candidates’ Presidential campaigns and previously reported efforts by those and other
foreign governments to confuse voters by sowing disinformation and discord using GAI tools to distort
7
political conversations and inject deepfakes into various political contests, the FCC should encourage
review by its Communications Security, Reliability, and Interoperability Council of how FCC-regulated
entities can utilize provenance technologies like Content Credentials to help voters resist these malign
campaigns. Finally, the FCC could establish another Advisory Council to specifically review the
implementation of these technologies given the extraordinary stakes for voters of allowing unlimited
AI-generated content in our election communications without furnishing a technological means for
consumers to determine whether that content has been altered using AI. This will enable campaigns to
leverage the benefits of GAI while ensuring transparency for consumers.
Conclusion
Adobe appreciates the opportunity to comment on this Notice. We recognize the challenge
before the Commission but believe that leveraging industry-developed initiatives and standards such
as the CAI and C2PA would advance the FCC’s efforts to guard against fraudulent misrepresentation in
our elections.
Our recommendation is not a quick fix to the problems of political disinformation, but rather,
should be considered as part of a long-term, holistic strategy to put information in the hands of
American voters so that they can evaluate the trustworthiness of the elections-related content they are
consuming. With the 2024 elections quickly approaching, we are at a pivotal moment. AI has the
power to unleash human creativity in new ways, power human ingenuity to new levels, and bring our
society to unimagined heights, but it must be done right. With the right tools and frameworks, like
Content Credentials and the C2PA open-source standard, we can create a trustworthy digital space for
everyone.
Signed,
8
Anne Perkins
Director, Government Relations
Adobe Inc.
Adobe 345 Park Avenue, San Jose, CA 95110
