2144,1091965381999,2024-09-19T13:44:58.802Z,Taxpayers Protection Alliance,,,"September 19, 2024
Federal Communications Commission
45 L St NE
Washington, DC 20554
Taxpayers Protection Alliance Comments
RE: Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements
MB Docket No. 24-211
The Taxpayers Protection Alliance (TPA) is a rapid-response, non-profit, nonpartisan
organization dedicated to educating the public through the research, analysis, and dissemination
of information on the government’s effects on the economy.
On behalf of the millions of taxpayers and consumers it represents, TPA is pleased to submit
comments regarding the Federal Communication Commission (FCC)’s proposed rulemaking
entitled, “Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements.”1 Artificial intelligence (AI) is a new, and fast-moving, technology, and it
promises to change much about how Americans do business and communicate with one another.
The regulatory devices applied will play a large role in shaping the future of innovation and
American life.
TPA believes that the proposed regulation for AI-generated political advertising misses the mark.
It improperly singles out AI among a host of technologies with similar uses, provides little clarity
on crucial aspects of the proposal, and improperly regulates a specific type of speech. Moreover,
it is dubious that the FCC has the necessary statutory authority to do what it has proposed
because it is not the agency that Congress has tasked with this sort of regulation. It is particularly
unwise to move forward with such a flawed proposal given the fact that the regulation, as
currently constructed, will not achieve its stated goal to make American elections safer and more
transparent. TPA hopes the FCC will heed these concerns and reverse course.
Background
AI tools that allow users to create or edit audio and visual content have raised concerns that such
tools could facilitate the creation of false, misleading or deceptive political advertising. To
address such concerns (as put by FCC):
1 https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2024/08/05/2024-16977/disclosure-and-transparency-of-artificial-
intelligence-generated-content-in-political-advertisements
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
“[The FCC] proposes to require radio and television broadcast stations; cable operators,
DBS providers, and SDARS licensees engaged in origination programming; and permit
holders transmitting programming…to provide an on-air announcement for all political
ads that include AI-generated content disclosing the use of such content in the ad.”2
The agency hopes that this will bring clarity to the American people and ensure political
messaging continues to be of use, instead of descending into a morass of confusion, deception,
and chaos. As TPA will show, however, this proposal takes the wrong approach.
The FCC Lacks the Needed Statutory Authority
The first question for administrative agencies in the American constitutional system is whether
they possess the requisite statutory authority to regulate. The power of all administrative
agencies comes solely from congressional authorization — agencies execute statutes, and
regulate when statutes require it, but they do not write statutes.3 No matter how well-crafted or
badly needed a regulation may be, if an agency lacks proper authorization to promulgate it, that
agency may not move forward. This is a basic requirement of the rule of law; and America is a
republic — a nation in which the highest authority is the law, not any person’s will or discretion.4
The FCC is not the agency Congress entrusted with regulating political speech — that is the
Federal Elections Commission (FEC). In June, FEC chairman Sean J. Cooksey voiced these
concerns in a letter to FCC chairwoman Jessica Rosenworcel.5 “Congress vested the FEC with
the sole authority to interpret, administer, and enforce the Federal Election Campaign Act of
1971, as amended,” Chairman Cooksey wrote. “This includes the disclaimer and reporting
requirements specific to political communications set out under federal law.” Importantly, federal
courts have agreed with his interpretation. As the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit put
it in Galliano v. U.S. Postal Service (1988), with respect to political communications, “the FEC
is the exclusive administrative arbiter of questions concerning the name identifications and
disclaimers.”6
The FCC has attempted to stretch its limited statutory authorities that brush up against political
speech past the point of credulity. Commissioner Brendan Carr illustrated this well in his dissent
to this Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NPRM):
“…Congress has not given the FCC the type of freewheeling authority over these issues
that would be necessary to turn this plan into law. Under the Communications Act, the
FCC’s authority over candidate ads is limited to ensuring that broadcasters provide
candidates equal access, document those ads in the stations’ public file, and disclose the
ads’ sponsors. And even where the FCC has authority (as in the case of sponsorship
2 Ibid
3 https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/essay/artI-S1-1/ALDE_00001311/
4 https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Adams/06-04-02-0026-0004
5 https://radioink.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Sean-Cooksey-Letter-To-Jessical-Rosenworcel.pdf
6 https://casetext.com/case/galliano-v-us-postal-service
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
identification), it cannot force broadcasters to undertake a roving investigation into the
truth or falsity of the disclosure. Likewise, the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act merely
requires the FCC to compile information on electioneering communications that the FEC
may regulate.”7
Likewise, Commissioner Nathan Simington (in his dissent to the NPRM) noted the tenuous
justifications the FCC has advanced to vindicate its claims of regulatory authority. “The rules
this item proposes…lean[s]…on irrelevant or weak authority, in direct defiance of a sister
agency’s legitimate concerns,” Commissioner Simington wrote.8
The alarms sounded in these dissents are not just the varying legal opinions of a dissenting
faction within the commission. In recent years, courts have become increasingly textualist and
increasingly keen on keeping regulators within the strict boundaries of their statutory mandates.
In June, in Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo (2024), the Supreme Court overturned the
infamous Chevron doctrine, which gave agencies far-too-broad latitude to interpret congressional
language.9 In West Virginia v. EPA (2022), the Court made clear that agencies may not mine
statute to discover broad powers of vast economic and political import of which Congress never
dreamed.10 There are too many other such cases to list out here. But the lesson is clear: If
agencies abuse their statutory authority, courts — all the way up to the Supreme Court — will
halt their efforts. All of this will come at the expense of taxpayers who will be forced to pay for
doomed legal defenses of illegally pursued regulations.
The problematic nature of the FCC’s involvement is highlighted by the fact that, while it is
working regulating AI-generated political speech, so too are the FEC11 and Congress. This is a
dysfunctional regulatory dynamic that is foreign to the American system of government. That is
three institutions of the federal government working on the exact same issue. From a strict
constitutionalist perspective, this raises red flags. Administrative agencies should not work as
parallel legislatures to Congress. That is not how the system was designed to work.
It should be noted that Congress has thus far chosen not to regulate on this issue — and not for
lack or proposals. Policy makers must remember that — especially in a free country such as
America — choosing to do nothing is, itself, a respectable and often-salutary policy choice.
Congressional reticence should not be taken per se as an invitation for administrative agencies to
step in. And if an agency is to step in, it should be an agency with clear statutory authority, in this
case, the FEC.
The NPRM Threatens Innovation and Principles of Technological Neutrality
7 https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/FCC-24-74A3.pdf
8 https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/FCC-24-74A4.pdf
9 https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/23pdf/22-451_7m58.pdf
10 https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/21pdf/20-1530_n758.pdf
11 https://www.broadcastlawblog.com/2024/09/articles/fec-to-consider-ai-in-political-ads-at-their-september-19-
meeting-a-new-compromise-proposal-is-advanced/
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
AI is a new and rapidly developing technology. The new products that have appeared in recent
years have been thoroughly staggering, and the innovative pace of the years to come promises
only to increase. This innovation is not assured, however. Government can slow it, or direct it
towards suboptimal ends, by imposing short-sighted restrictions on innovators or distort the
incentives they are faced with. Likewise, ill-considered regulation on industry and consumer uses
of new technologies can do great harm to technological progress. It is the light-touch, pro-
innovation regulatory framework that America has adopted thus far that has facilitated the
current dynamic technological landscape.
AI is creating incredibly novel products, and it is already changing how Americans
communicate, do business, and (in some cases) perceive the world. On the other side of the coin,
regulators must carefully think through how novel technologies should be governed. TPA would
argue that regulators should apply the same sound principles of regulation to AI as have been
applied in many other contexts — e.g., America’s regulation of technology since the 1990s. From
the wheel to the printing press to the industrial revolution to the internet, it is a fact of history
that technological changes in communications and commerce often seem to change the very
fabric of society, and in some ways do. But it is also a fact of history that the laws of economics
— of human action — remain constant, and the general principles of good and prudent
governance remain consistent over time.
TPA is concerned that the FCC’s proposal is decidedly not tech-neutral and would, if finalized,
drive technologists and users away from AI products — for no good reason. The problem the
FCC seeks to address is the potential that nefarious actors will use technology to edit images or
audio to mislead Americans. This concern is not specific to AI-based tools. Nor will it be solved
by the proposed disclosures.
First, AI tools are not the only means to doctor or fabricate audio or visual content. For example,
when using non-AI editing tools, users can selectively edit or splice together video clips to make
a candidate appear to say horrific things. To put it another way, the problems that modern
technology poses for 21st-century political communications are far bigger than AI. Any
regulatory regime should account for the larger picture, not focus on one specific technology —
no matter how much media attention and cultural buzz that technology currently generates.
This points at a larger conceptual problem underlying the FCC’s proposal. Regulators should
consider AI as a general-purpose technology.12 Its outputs should be regulated severally, not as if
they have a special status because of the technology that produced them. To the greatest extent
possible, regulators should seek to apply, mutatis mutandis, existing statutory authorities within
their ordinary field of expertise to new products that come from AI. In other words, AI products
should be regulated as similarly as possible to similarly situated products.
12 https://www.protectingtaxpayers.org/wp-content/uploads/Regulating-AI-TPA.pdf
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
As one FEC proposal puts it, “it does not matter whether a regulated person uses any particular
form of technology, including AI,” to deceive. “The legal question is whether the actor”
participates in the deception, the FEC continues.13
This hyperfocus on AI has led the FCC to propose a solution that will not have the effects for
which agency hopes. As noted, the problem is not AI-generated communications; it is deceptive
communications. Notifying Americans that a political advertisement was created with help from
AI tells them nothing about whether it contains misleading content. In fact, the very fact that an
ad contains a disclosure may mislead many Americans to think entirely truthful advertisements
are misleading in some way.
It is entirely unclear that Americans have cognizable interest in knowing whether AI was used in
a political advertisement, so long as that advertisement does not include deception. This is
especially true given that many very common and mundane editing tools include incorporate AI.
To take the argument to an extreme, Americans certainly have no interest in knowing whether a
spell checker was used to write copy for a political advertisement.
This leads directly to another concern — the lack of specificity with respect to what constitutes
“AI” for the purposes of the FCC’s proceeding. As put in Commissioner Simington’s dissent
(emphases his):
“What is ‘artificial intelligence’ in this context? Don’t get me wrong: this item takes a
serious stab at defining the term, and it draws on other serious attempts to do so for
inspiration. There is some important line-drawing here. Yet a lot of photo, video, and
audio editing and engineering software uses ‘computational technology or other machine-
based system’ to modify the ‘depict[ion of] an individual’s appearance, speech, or
conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation[.]’ A lot. Like, all of it. Given the threat
of penalties (not to mention losing the trust of viewers), will broadcasters and political
advertisers alike have reason to be overinclusive in their disclosures? Absolutely.”14
Commissioner Carr raised similar concerns:
“What does it mean to have ‘AI-generated content’ in a political ad? Is it everything? Is it
nothing? The NPRM proposes to cover any ‘image, audio, or video that has been
generated using computational technology or other machine-based system that depicts an
individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation.’
“That standard is no standard at all…”
The problem is clear. The proposed disclosure’s lack of clarity will confuse those whom they will
regulate, and this confusion will likely lead to the adoption of overinclusive interpretations to
escape lability.
13 https://www.fec.gov/resources/cms-content/documents/mtgdoc-24-39-A.pdf
14 https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/FCC-24-74A4.pdf
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
The FCC proposes to subject an entire phylum of technology to an ill-defined and unequal
regulatory regime — all without providing meaningful benefit to the American people. This will
likely chill the use of AI tools — which have great potential to lower the costs of political
advertising to the benefit of smaller and less powerful voices. Again, all this would produce no
meaningful benefit to the American people.
The FCC’s Proposal is Unnecessary
If there were an epidemic of AI-generated deception ravaging the landscape of political
advertising, the FCC might have a better case. But the fact is that there is no such thing.
According to research from the UK, “Based on our research, of 112 national elections which
have either taken place since January 2023 or are forthcoming in 2024, just 19 were identified to
show AI interference. As of May 2024, evidence demonstrates no clear signs of significant
changes in election results compared to the expected performance of political candidates from
polling data.”15
Moreover, existing law is usually more than sufficient to deal with the few cases of AI-facilitated
deception that have cropped up. Consider the case of robocalls placed to New Hampshire voters
prior to the January 2024 Democratic presidential primary election, which involved a voice that
sounded like President Joe Biden’s telling voters not to vote in that primary.16 This incident was
quickly linked to AI. The person responsible for this wrongdoing was pursued and held
accountable — by the FCC, no less.17
Regulating Only One Outlet for Political Advertising Will Sow Confusion
The fact that the FCC proposes to require advertisements that appear only in certain venues of
communication will cause further confusion. If Americans are notified that a broadcast
advertisement has incorporated AI but receives no such disclosure for a political advertisement
appearing on YouTube, they will likely assume that one was created with AI’s help and the other
was not — regardless of whether this is actually true. This will only exacerbate the uncertainties,
noted above, surrounding AI-based tools’ relationship to truth and the national discourse.
Conclusion
TPA is confident of the FCC’s admirable intentions to ensure that America’s elections remain
free, fair, and transparent. But whenever a new technology arises, or some other societal change
occurs, regulators face a perverse incentive to all jump in at once to do something about it. This
often leads to the implementation of over-hasty policy solutions with significant negative effects
15 https://cetas.turing.ac.uk/publications/ai-enabled-influence-operations-threat-uk-general-election
16 https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-election/nh-attorney-general-says-found-source-fake-biden-robocalls-
rcna137499
17 https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/DOC-402762A1.pdf
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
www.protectingtaxpayers.org
for the American people, even if their effects are not understood fully for years after their
enactment.
TPA appreciates the opportunity to comment and urges the FCC to reconsider its proposals. The
FCC should allow the FEC — the agency with greater subject-matter expertise as well as
congressional authorization — to take the lead on this issue.
All regulators must remember that AI is here to stay — and so, too, will be whatever ill-
conceived regulations are put into place before policy makers understand their full implications.
Taxpayers Protection Alliance, 1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 500 Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 930-1716
