2156,10919296572435,2024-09-19T15:45:58.686Z,"Locality Broadcast, Inc.",,,"September 19, 2024
Ms. Marlene H. Dortch
Secretary
Federal Communications Commission
45 L Street, NE
Washington, DC 20554
Re: In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial
Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements
(MB Docket No. 24-211)
Dear Ms. Dortch:
Locality Broadcast, Inc. (“Locality”) is the broadcast industry’s preeminent local
television solutions provider. Its business is to address the evolving needs of
advertisers by unlocking the power of connecting with television audiences on a local
level through the placement of advertisements on television stations across the country.
With a team of 50 political advertising experts to support elections, campaigns,
candidates and advocacy groups, Locality is well-versed in the political advertising
landscape. Locality is, therefore, pleased to offer its perspective on the FCC’s proposed
new rules regarding the use of artificial intelligence (“AI”) in political advertisements.1
Locality is a key player in the political advertising space.
Locality has been in the broadcast television industry for over 40 years, previously doing
business as CoxReps. During that time, Locality has helped campaigns and brands tap
into the mindset of the local consumer to precisely reach optimal markets on a local
level. As of today, together with its sister company, Locality Streaming, Locality has
served more than 1,500 ad agencies and 4,500 advertisers and offers the best premium
inventory that the video industry has to offer to help advertisers optimize their spend
and target audiences at scale. Locality has representatives in 11 locations around the
country and serves 100% of U.S. DMAs.
On the political side of its business, Locality helps candidates, advocacy and issue
groups, political action committees and other similar advertisers purchase time on
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements,
Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, MB Docket No. 24-211, FCC No. 24-74 (rel. July 25, 2024) (the
“NPRM”).
Ms. Marlene H. Dortch
September 19, 2024
Page 2
television stations to most effectively present issues of social, political and economic
importance to American audiences. By law, advertisements on broadcast television
must disclose that the ad was sponsored and by whom, and Locality assists stations in
fulfilling their disclosure requirements.
Locality appreciates, and shares, the FCC’s concerns about transparency and has no
objection to mandatory disclosure of the use of AI in political ads. Any mandatory
disclosure requirement should not, however, be the responsibility of television
broadcasters. As discussed below, Locality believes that the NPRM would impose an
undue, unwarranted and unnecessary burden on broadcast stations and others without
achieving the goal which the FCC seems to be seeking.
Viewer confusion, not transparency, will result if the proposed rules are adopted.
Under the rules proposed by the FCC, broadcasters would be required to ask
advertisers whether an issue ad contains content generated by AI.2 If an
advertiser/agency responds that AI was used, the broadcaster would be required to
place an on-air disclosure on the ad that states that the message “contains information
generated in whole or in part by artificial intelligence.” The message would be either
spoken or shown on screen with letters of a specified height.
The NPRM seems to stem from the FCC’s well-founded desire to ensure that
consumers are not misled or deceived about important political issues and election-
related facts, including candidates' positions on issues and when and where to vote.
Because generative AI is able to create false and misleading content that looks and
sounds real, including fraudulent deepfakes, the FCC’s goal is a worthy one and various
entities involved in the production and distribution of political advertising – including
candidates, political parties and advocacy groups – presumably share this objective.
Unfortunately, the rules proposed in the NPRM, if adopted, will not achieve the FCC’s
goal of protecting consumers or promoting transparency for the following reasons.
Production uses for AI. Generative AI is widely used in audio and video production for
innocuous purposes, such as enhancing the efficiency of political advertising production
and significantly improving the quality of the audio and video in political ads. As such,
the NPRM would impose a disclosure requirement even if the only uses of generative AI
are related to production. Naturally, this could have the unintended impact of causing
viewers to disregard messages that carry the AI disclosure on the incorrect belief that all
ads with disclosures are fake, provide disinformation or that something else is “wrong”
2 The FCC proposes to define AI-generated content as: “an image, audio, or video that
has been generated using computational technology or other machine-based system
that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance,
or situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that sound like human voices,
and AI-generated actors that appear to be human actors.” NPRM at ¶ 11.
