Ms. Marlene H. Dortch
September 19, 2024
Page 3
with the ad or the advertiser. Moreover, an ad that in fact conveys false information
without using generative AI will have no disclosures and so consumers may mistakenly
believe in its accuracy merely because no AI disclosure is on the ad.
Process for inquiring. The NPRM would require broadcasters to “inquire” about the use
of AI in a political ad but doesn’t specify at what point in the sales and placement
process the inquiry needs to be made. Timing is important because candidates and
other political ad buyers often book time for their broadcast ads weeks prior to their
airing but may then make changes to the content such that AI is used in an ad at the
last minute. For example, it may be easier and faster to use generative AI to record a
minor change in a voice-over than have a human re-record it. Therefore, if the inquiry
was made at the time the advertising schedule was placed, the answer originally
received may no longer be correct. This could lead to an inadvertent failure to comply
by the broadcaster, even though the broadcaster would have no way of knowing the
revised ad used AI. Because broadcasters have no way to tell if an ad is using AI, if it is
determined that generative AI disclosure is necessary, the burden for reporting its use
should be placed on political advertisers and not on broadcasters.
Diluting the message and increasing the cost. Because the NPRM specifies the
parameters necessary for the proposed disclosure, messages will likely be diluted
because the amount of time or space needed to make the disclosure will eat into the
substance of the message and detract from its meaning to viewers. In the context of a
30-second spot, losing 3-6 seconds of airtime to a disclosure means losing 10-20
percent of the value of the ad. In many cases, this will cost political advertisers more to
purchase advertising time since they will essentially be forced to purchase longer spots,
which will in turn have the unintended impact of restricting inventory and limiting
broadcasters’ ability to provide viewers with a variety of advertisements, whether or not
political.
Viewer confusion. The FCC’s rules would apply only to broadcast, locally originated
cable and satellite, meaning that a political advertiser could run the same ad on a
platform such as social media, online outlets or national cable networks without any
disclosure, thereby confusing consumers because of a distinction without a difference.
Audiences will be confused when the same ad airs on a broadcast television station or
cable system with a disclosure but runs without such disclosure when it is aired – even
the same day or in the same program – by a cable network as part of its national feed.
Further, requiring disclosures for some content outlets but not others will create a
competitive disadvantage for broadcasters, as political advertisers may choose to avoid
using the public airwaves in favor of other platforms. Given the ubiquity of free, over-
the-air television broadcast, providing a disincentive to candidates and issue groups to
advertise on television risks potentially limiting voters’ exposure to political ads and
ideas.
Multiple affected entities. A variety of people along the production, inquiry and airing
chain will be impacted by the rulemaking, including the candidate or advocacy group
