creating the ad, agencies, sales representatives, traffic operations and stations, causing
both an undue burden on many as well as multiple opportunities for inadvertent
noncompliance. Parties that do intend to comply, such as television broadcasters and
their partners such as Locality, will continually need to ask about the status of each
political ad (regarding whether it uses AI) at each step of the process, as the answer
could change between when an ad is contracted for and when the ad actually runs.
And of course, if a candidate or issue group determines to use AI in an ad and not
disclose, broadcasters would not be able to detect the use of AI in a timely way.
Television broadcasters therefore will be extremely hard pressed to comply with the
new proposed rules given that they simply will not have the information necessary to
ensure compliance.
Further Comment should be sought before new rules are adopted.
Since the FCC does not have time to adopt new rules on the use of AI in political
advertisements before the November 2024 elections, we urge the Commission to pause
its review of the relevance of AI restrictions at least until the next election cycle and at
that point seek further comment on important issues, if necessary. Such inquiry may
then focus on whether disclaimers on some, but not all, political ads that use AI would
benefit or confuse consumers; whether broadcasters have the technical means to
determine if AI has been used in a political advertisement; whether FCC-regulated
content carriers are the proper parties to police the use of AI in the political advertising
space; and whether the use of AI in an inconsequential manner is meaningful enough to
disclose it to consumers.
* * * * * * *
Locality appreciates the opportunity to provide its perspective to the FCC on whether or
how broadcasters should approach the use of AI in political advertisements. If we can
provide further information, or if FCC staff have any questions, please do not hesitate to
