2164,10919012987174,2024-09-19T16:08:10.627Z,The E.W. Scripps Company,,,"Before the
Federal Communications Commission
Washington, DC 20554
In the Matter of )
)
Disclosure and Transparency of ) MB Docket No. 24-211
Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in )
Political Advertisements )
COMMENTS OF THE E.W. SCRIPPS COMPANY
The E.W. Scripps Company (“Scripps”) submits these comments in response to the
Commission’s Notice in the above-captioned rulemaking proceeding.1 In the Notice, the
Commission proposes to require content providers regulated by the Commission to inquire about
and place disclaimers on political advertisements that use artificial intelligence (“AI”) during the
creative process. If adopted, the Commission’s rules would only apply to television, radio, local
cable, and satellite programmers and would allow social media apps, websites, cable networks,
streamers and other platforms to continue serving the same AI ads unfettered of regulation.
Scripps agrees with the Commission that the emerging use of AI in political
advertisements is a double-edged sword that could, in some instances, benefit the public by
allowing accurate information to reach more people while other uses of AI could, in other
instances, harm the public if AI is used to create content that is deceptive or misleading.2 The
Commission is not, however, proposing to regulate all deceptive or misleading uses of AI, but
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, MB Docket No. 24-211, FCC No. 24-74 (rel.
July 25, 2024) (the “Notice”).
2 Notice at ¶ 1.
rather only to regulate all uses of AI in political advertisements that run on Commission-
regulated content providers.
Scripps supports the Commission’s goals of protecting consumers and promoting
transparency. However, while the Commission’s goals are laudable and its proposals are well
intentioned, the new rules will not protect the public. Instead, if adopted, the proposed rules
would create the confusion and increase the public distrust the Commission wants to prevent.3
Additionally, by requiring new processes proposed in the regulation only for some but not all
content providers, the Commission is putting businesses like those operated by Scripps (i.e. local
television and radio operators) at a competitive disadvantage. Scripps therefore urges the
Commission to step back, gather information about how AI is being used in the current election
cycle, but not adopt any new rules as part of this proceeding.
I. BROADCASTERS SHARE THE COMMISSION’S DESIRE FOR AN INFORMED ELECTORATE.
Scripps has been in the news business since 1878 when company founder Edward W.
Scripps started his first newspaper, the Penny Press, in Cleveland, Ohio. Scripps Broadcasting
Company was established in 1935 with radio and expanded into television in 1947. Today,
Scripps, through its Local Media division, is among the largest U.S. owners of local television
stations with a portfolio of 61 television stations in 41 markets. In addition, through its Scripps
Networks division, Scripps reaches nearly every U.S. television household with eight
programming networks including Scripps News and Court TV.
During the current election cycle, Scripps stations will produce hundreds of hours of local
news, host and air candidate debates, and engage in the type of watchdog journalism that local
audiences need to make informed decisions at the ballot box. Scripps believes that “journalism
3 Id.
2
and free speech are cornerstones of a democratic society”4 and adheres to the company motto
that was adopted in 1923: “Give light and the people will find their own way.” Scripps supports
the Commission’s goal of ensuring the public is informed and has the information needed so they
can evaluate political ads for themselves.5
Unfortunately, the rules proposed in the Notice, if adopted, will not help the Commission
achieve its goal. The primary problem is that the Commission is not the proper governmental
entity to tackle the issue of AI use in political ads.6 The Commission, as the Notice implicitly
recognizes, only has jurisdiction over part of the political advertising ecosystem; while the
Commission can regulate TV, radio, cable and satellite providers, the Commission cannot
regulate websites, streamers or social media.7 The rules the Commission proposes would,
therefore, at best create a confusing and disjointed regulatory regime where a consumer could
see an ad with an AI disclaimer on television during the local news and then, 20 minutes later,
see the exact same ad on social media or on a website with no AI disclaimer. The potential for
consumer confusion in this scenario is high. As such, the Commission’s rules as proposed are
both over inclusive, as they regulate every political advertisement running on certain content
providers that use the new tool of AI, and under inclusive, as they regulate only part of the
political advertising ecosystem.
Scripps will leave to other parties a fulsome discussion of whether the Commission has
the statutory authority to adopt the proposed rules (it does not) or whether the proposed rules
4 See, e.g.¸ https://scripps.com/company/about-scripps/.
5 Notice at ¶ 2.
6 Scripps believes that the major question as to how the use of AI in political ads should be
regulated is best left to Congress.
7 The Commission certainly cannot regulate candidates, political parties or issue groups, or the
advertising agencies that actually create the political ads.
3
would violate the First Amendment (they would). Other parties may also discuss how the
proposed rules, if applied to candidate ads, could run afoul of the statutory equal opportunities,
reasonable access and no censorship provisions of the Communications Act.8 For Scripps, the
overarching concern is that the remedy the Commission proposes, however well intentioned, will
create consumer confusion and therefore will harm, not help, the public interest.
In the Notice the Commission discusses the possible harms of deceptive AI-generated
content and asks whether those “potentially harmful effects support Commission intervention in
order to ensure that the public is informed of the presence of AI-generated content.”9 Scripps
asserts that, at this time, the answer to the Commission’s question is “No.” Rather than rushing
to adopt new rules, the Commission should gather information.
II. THE PROPOSED RULES ARE UNWORKABLE AND BURDENSOME.
Under the rules as proposed in the Notice, regulated entities like the stations and
networks operated by Scripps (“stations”) would be required to do three things. First, stations
would be required to ask the party buying a political ad whether the ad contains any AI-generated
content. Then, for ads that do include AI-generated content, stations would be required to (a)
make an on-air announcement disclosing that the ad used AI; and (b) put a notice about the ad in
the station online political public file.10 The proposed regulations make faulty assumptions that
create obligations that may seem simple, but from a practical perspective create onerous,
complex and potentially time-consuming obligations on stations that are unworkable.
8 See 47 U.S.C. § 312 (the FCC can revoke a station license in the event of willful or repeated
failure to allow reasonable access to a federal candidate); 47 U.S.C. § 315(a) (stations must
provide competing candidates equal opportunities to “use” a station and stations “shall have no
power of censorship over the materials broadcast. . . “).
9 Notice at ¶ 10.
10 Notice at ¶¶ 15-18.
4
The first faulty assumption is the Commission’s hypothesis that the party requesting the
airtime “generally would be aware whether or not a particular ad contains AI-generated content”
is not correct.11 This statement highlights that the Commission does not have a full grasp of the
process of creating, placing and airing a political advertisement. Contrary to the Commission’s
assertion, the party from whom Scripps buys a political ad usually has nothing to do with
creating the content for the ad that eventually runs. Virtually all candidates and issue groups use
ad buying agencies whose sole job is to contract for ad placement with the chosen content
provider. These agencies negotiate the political advertising buys, oftentimes months in advance
of when an ad will air. Then, the actual creative for the ad is produced by a different entity and
sent to the station just before the ad is scheduled to run. Stations usually have no contact with
the entities that produce the creative, which are the only parties that definitively know whether
an advertisement includes AI-generated content. Stations could, therefore, inquire “in writing to
the person or entity making the request for the purchase of political advertising time, at the time
that an agreement is reached to air the political advertising on the station” as to whether the
political advertisements will contain any AI-generated content, but that “person or entity making
the request” will rarely have information about the content of the advertisement or the production
methods used to create it.12
A second challenge to the proposed regulation is that if the new rules are adopted and
stations make the required inquiries, some candidates and issue groups will voluntarily disclose
whether an ad uses AI-generated content and will include the needed disclaimer to the ad for the
stations. If so, burdensome paperwork obligations will remain for the stations, as stations would
11 Notice at ¶ 36.
12 See, e.g., proposed rule 47 C.F.R. § 73.1945(c).
5
need to confirm that the required AI disclosure is associated with the correct ad. This is a
burdensome step because frequently one advertising schedule is split between two or more
different advertisements (which may or may not be coming from different creative agencies) and
the creative associated with a particular schedule can often change last minute or mid-flight. So,
it is common that one advertising contract would have two or more different ads associated with
it.13 If one ad used AI and the others did not, should a station add a notice to the public file
saying that some portion of the messages associated with a particular schedule “contains
information generated in whole or in part by artificial intelligence”?14
The proposed rules raise other conundrums:
 How granular would the public file notice have to be, and how much time and
effort would it take for a station to prepare the needed notations to match up the
schedule in the public file with the AI ads that actually run?
 What happens if an agency thinks an ad will include AI and so a station adds the
notice to the public file, but then the creative is changed and no AI is used –
would the station then need to remove the notice from the public file, and would
that itself create confusion?
 When would the AI notices be uploaded to the public file, given that the
associated contracts in some cases are loaded to the file months in advance of
when the ad will run, whereas the creative is usually determined only days in
advance?
All of these questions must be answered before any public file requirement can be adopted.
The harder case, of course, will be if a candidate or issue group does not disclose the use
of AI using the appropriate disclaimer. If that happens, stations cannot add a disclaimer before or
after an advertisement – stations can only add a disclaimer on the ad itself. This is because
13 For example, during the week of August 12, the Harris for President campaign split its
advertising schedules on television stations in Michigan to run two different advertisements. Per
traffic instructions sent to stations on August 12, beginning on August 12 Michigan stations were
instructed to run 50% of the schedule with an advertisement titled “Tougher” and 50% of the
schedule with an advertisement titled “Knows.”
14 See, e.g., Notice at ¶ 18.
6
station ad breaks are of a set duration and generally broken into pre-set blocks. If one 30-second
ad in a 3-minute advertising block suddenly becomes 33 seconds or 35 seconds, most stations
will have to preempt another advertiser in that time block. Last minute preemptions will create
havoc for station traffic departments and will anger the advertisers who get preempted, especially
if the preemptions happen to candidates or issue groups trying to run ads shortly before an
election.15 Stations also would lose revenue from any ads that are preempted because of added
disclaimers and will be hard pressed to fill the leftover airtime with odd length PSAs or
billboards last minute.16
On the other hand, if broadcasters are required to overlay AI disclaimers on top of ad
content, especially if oral disclaimers are required, that certainly would trigger First Amendment
concerns given the impact on political speech. Further, if done to candidate ads, disclaimer
overlays would violate the statutory no censorship provision of 47 U.S.C. § 315(a).
Alternatively, some stations will choose not to run the offending ad (Scripps generally will not
run political ads without the proper disclaimers) but not running ads from federal candidates with
reasonable access rights, or not running ads from candidates with equal opportunities rights,
would again violate federal statutes.
All of this presupposes that stations have some way to determine if AI was used in an
advertisement so that stations can add the appropriate AI disclosure, if needed, and include the
necessary information in station public files. Unfortunately, Scripps is not currently aware of a
technical process available to stations that can reliably determine whether AI was used in a
15 In many instances, especially right before an election, an entire advertising block can be filled
with only political ads such that a station would be unable to preempt a non-political advertiser
(because there would be none).
16 Given the revenue implications, new rules that require stations to add disclaimers before or
after advertisements might implicate the Takings Clause of the Fifth Amendment.
7
particular ad. Until such technology is widely available so that stations can be sure whether the
ads they are running include AI, the Commission cannot put the burden on broadcasters to police
the use of AI in political ads.
III. THE COMMISSION SHOULD NOT MICROMANAGE COMPLIANCE.
While Scripps does not believe the adoption of new rules about AI-generated content
would be in the public interest at this time, if the Commission nonetheless adopts new rules, it
should not also micromanage how stations comply with those rules. Specifically, in the Notice
the Commission asks questions about how stations should respond if the use of AI in a particular
advertisement is challenged by a “credible third party.”17 Stations certainly should respond if the
content or credibility of a political advertisement is questioned, but the Commission must not
adopt rules specifying how stations should respond.
Complaints about political advertisements are common – the Scripps stations currently
receive multiple complaints per week and the volume will increase as we get closer to the
November elections. The complaints usually are from a candidate but sometimes are from a
company or issue group and they usually assert that a particular advertisement includes material
that is false, misleading, deceptive, or defamatory. Complaints typically include claims that a
candidate did not vote for or believe or say something the ad claims, or that actions the candidate
took (or didn’t take) are being falsely portrayed. Presumably if Scripps receives a complaint
about the use of AI in a political ad, the complaint will say something similar.
Scripps diligently reviews each complaint and has a set protocol for investigating the
claims made. What Scripps has seen after reviewing hundreds of complaints about political
advertisements over many years is that the complaints, even complaints from candidates, often
17 Notice at ¶ 17.
8
include baseless claims and in fact the challenged advertisements are fine. Scripps therefore
does not think it is in the public interest to automatically assume some claims about contested
ads are true or to define some interested complaining persons as “credible.”18 If the Commission
does so, clever political strategists will surely use the Commission’s rules to try to game the
system and obtain a political advantage. Stations already know how to handle complaints about
political ads and will handle complaints about AI-generated content following their already
established processes and procedures – no new Commission rules are needed specifically for AI.
III. THE COMMISSION SHOULD NOT RUSH AND UNINTENTIONALLY ADOPT HARMFUL NEW
RULES.
Scripps appreciates, and shares, the Commission’s concerns about the use of AI in
political ads. However, given that new rules cannot be adopted before the November 2024
elections, there is no need for the Commission to rush and adopt rules that would burden stations
and harm the voting public. The Commission should use this docket to collect information and
see how the use of AI in political ads unfolds. Then, with that information, the Commission can,
18 Notice at ¶ 17 n. 57 (discussing a definition of “credible third party.”).
9
in a Further Notice, determine whether specific rules that apply only to Commission-regulated
entities are in the public interest.
Respectfully submitted,
THE E.W. SCRIPPS COMPANY
By: /s/ David M. Giles
David M. Giles
Executive Vice President, Chief Legal Officer
and General Counsel
By: /s/ Samantha Osborne Reynolds
Samantha Osborne Reynolds
Vice President, Political, Advocacy &
Automation
The E.W. Scripps Company
312 Walnut St.
Suite 2800
Cincinnati, OH 45202
(513) 977-3000
