rationale “no longer serves as a valid justification for the government’s intrusive regulation of traditional broadcasting.” See
Federal Communications Commission, Media Bureau Staff Research Paper, The Scarcity Rationale for Regulating Traditional
Broadcasting: An Idea Whose Time Has Passed (March 2005), 2005 FCC LEXIS 1708 (“The scarcity rationale is based on
fundamental misunderstandings of physics and economics, efficient resource allocation, recent field measurements, and
technology. It is outmoded in today's media marketplace.”).
7 The Court has held that “laws that burden political speech are subject to strict scrutiny.” Citizens United v. Fed. Elec. Comm’n,
558 U.S. 310, 340 (2010) (“Citizens United”) (citing FEC v. Wis. Right to Life, Inc., 551 U.S. 449, 464 (2007)).
8 Id.
