RE: Comment in the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements: MB Docket No. 24-211
The Institute for Strategic Dialogue (ISD) is a non-profit think tank that focuses on
combatting extremism and hate online. Through a combination of research, education and
policy, ISD works with lawmakers, regulators, civil society organizations, and businesses
to deliver solutions that address harms on- and offline. ISD strongly supports the Federal
Communications Commission’s (FCC) efforts to require the disclosure of the use of AI
technologies in political advertisements and welcomes the opportunity to submit
comments in response to this Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NPRM).
While the development and widespread rollout of AI technologies provides opportunities
for innovation, efficiency, and creativity, the rapid deployment of these technologies
without adequate safeguards is subject to abuse. This creates the potential for “providing
deceptive, misleading, or fraudulent information to voters,” per the Commission’s
assessment. In the current election thus far, AI was used to generate a false robocall of
President Biden’s voice telling voters to not participate in New Hampshire’s primary in
January.1 Additionally, Governor DeSantis’ campaign produced a video that contained AI-
generated images of Donald Trump hugging immunologist Anthoy Fauci who he clashed
with during the COVID pandemic.2 Particularly because AI technologies have developed so
quickly and are increasingly sophisticated, we believe the risk of deception will only
increase. Mandated disclosure requirements are needed to ensure that voters receive
accurate information.
In addition, we are concerned that a failure to provide guidance will lead to confusion
since social media platforms have adopted varying labeling requirements for AI-generated
1 Seitz-Wald, Alex and Mike Memoli. (2024). “Fake Joe Biden Robocall tells New Hampshire Democrats not to
vote Tuesday”. NBC News. Retrieved at https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-election/fake-joe-biden-
robocall-tells-new-hampshire-democrats-not-vote-tuesday-rcna134984
2 Bond, Shannon. (2023). “DeSantis campaign shares apparent AI-generated fake images of Trump and
Fauci”. NPR. Retrieved at https://www.npr.org/2023/06/08/1181097435/desantis-campaign-shares-
apparent-ai-generated-fake-images-of-trump-and-fauci
content.3 An overarching federal mandate for broadcasters on radio and television around
AI-generated content in political ads could serve as a helpful model that online information
platforms could adopt. We recommend that the FCC’s proposed definition of AI-generated
content to include “content that has been significantly edited by AI” to align more closely
with that of social media platforms to provide better continuity for regulators and users
alike.4 The FCC notes that it initiated this NPRM “to provide greater transparency regarding
the use of AI-generated content in political advertising”. Mandatory disclosure
requirements will make it easier for broadcasters and the FCC to identify unlabeled ads
containing AI-generated content. Likewise, it will make it easier for recipients to look for
labels to help contextualize the information they see and actively seek out additional
information if needed. It can also play an important role in fostering trust in public
institutions, especially as information consumers are facing an onslaught of misleading
and confusing information over broadcast and online. Consistent disclosure requirements
are also helpful for those both producing and hosting advertisements to adhere to the
same standards. For this reason, we believe that these requirements should extend to
both candidate and issue advertisements so that all political messaging adheres to the
same transparency standards.
We urge the FCC to enact rules that require the clear disclosure by broadcasters and other
regulated entities of AI-generated content in political ads. It is imperative that voters have
comprehensive and accurate information leading up to and during elections, which
includes being aware of AI-generated content present in ads shown to them.
Thank you for the opportunity to comment on this important initiative.
Sincerely,
Ellen Jacobs
Senior US Digital Policy Manager
