2202,10919534725715,2024-09-19T19:16:28.109Z,ACA Connects – America’s Communications Association,,,"Before the
FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION
Washington, D.C. 20554
In the Matter of )
)
Disclosure and Transparency of ) MB Docket No. 24-211
Artificial Intelligence-Generated )
Content in Political Advertisements )
COMMENTS OF ACA CONNECTS AND NTCA
ON THE NOTICE OF PROPOSED RULEMAKING
I. INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY
ACA Connects – America’s Communications Association (“ACA Connects”)1 and
NTCA - The Rural Broadband Association (“NTCA”)2 (hereinafter “Joint Commenters”)
submit these comments in response to the Federal Communications Commission’s
(“Commission” or “FCC”) Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (“NPRM” or “Proposed
Rules”) in the Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content
in Political Advertisements docket.3 The NPRM seeks comment on proposals that
would, among other things, require cable operators engaged in origination programming
1 ACA Connects represents approximately 500 smaller private and public broadband,
video, and voice providers that pass approximately 30 million households across the 50
states and U.S. territories, including six million homes in rural areas.
2 NTCA represents approximately 850 independent, community-based
telecommunications companies and cooperatives and more than 400 other firms that
support or are themselves engaged in the provision of communications services in the
most rural portions of America. All NTCA service provider members are full service
rural local exchange carriers and broadband providers, and many provide fixed and
mobile wireless, video and other competitive services in rural America as well.
3 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, MB Docket No. 24-211, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 24-74
(rel. July 25, 2024) (“NPRM” or “Proposed Rules”).
to (1) provide an on-air announcement for all political ads that include AI-generated
content disclosing the use of such content in the ad and (2) include a notice in their
online political files for all political ads that include AI-generated content disclosing that
the ad contains such content.4
Joint Commenters support the Commission’s goal in the NPRM: to “ensur[e]
broadcasters and other regulated entities take reasonable measures to address
potentially false, misleading, or deceptive political advertising and enhancing the
public’s ability to evaluate political ads, thus promoting an informed electorate and
improving the quality of public discourse”5 While the Commission’s goal in this
proceeding is commendable, we worry that the negative consequences of moving
forward with the Proposed Rules would outweigh any possible benefits.
Adoption of the Proposed Rules would result in disparate treatment of political
advertisements depending on the media platform on which they are carried, which in
turn would cause significant consumer confusion. Moreover, regulation of AI in political
ads is being actively considered by other government authorities with a more direct role
in overseeing political campaigns and elections. We urge the Commission to allow
those efforts to develop a bit further before it considers what complementary role it
might play in this area.
4 See id., para 2.
5 Id., para. 31.
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 2
II. DISCUSSION
The Commission should decline to adopt the proposed rules for several reasons.
To begin with, the proposed AI disclosures would do little to inform the public about the
veracity of a political advertisement. While AI potentially could be used to create a false
image or recording of a political candidate committing a heinous act or endorsing an
unpopular policy, it could also be used to enhance the quality of a sound recording or an
image shown in the advertisement. By grouping all types of artificial intelligence into
one bucket, the Commission risks invalidating any form of artificial intelligence used in
political advertisements without considering potential benefits. By the same token, the
proposals fail to account for the fact that it is entirely possible to create deceptive
political advertisements without use of AI. As pointed out by the Center of Data
Innovation (“CDI”), the arbitrary distinction between “AI-generated content and non-AI
generated content” embodied in the Proposed Rules “could both discourage the
legitimate use of the technology and mislead the public as to the veracity of political
ads.”6
Disparate rules for Commission-regulated entities and other media platforms that
carry political advertisements will create consumer confusion. Even if the proposed
rules were stronger on the merits, their adoption would create two different standards
for political ads: one that applies to Commission-regulated entities, including cable
operators and broadcasters, and another that applies to other entities that carry political
6 See, e.g., Comments of Center for Data Innovation, MB Docket No. 24-211, at 2 (filed
Aug. 23, 2024).
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 3
advertisements, including digital platforms beyond the Commission’s regulatory
purview. Such disparity would not make sense. While “legacy” TV remains the
dominant venue for political advertisements, the status quo is quickly changing: “this
election cycle, digital is expected to attract $3.46 [billion] in spend, or about 28% of total
spend in the cycle. This represents a 156% uptick from 2020 levels.”7 With the rise of
digital viewership compared to traditional TV,8 it is reasonable to expect the prevalence
of advertisements on digital platforms to continue to rise. Accordingly, it is essential to
avoid to arbitrary discrepancies in the rules governing use of AI in political
advertisements, so as to avoid creating confusion amongst the public.
As pointed out by CDI,9 there is a serious risk of public confusion by having
conflicting rules for different platforms – particularly where the platforms are similar in
content. Under the Commission’s Proposed Rules, an AI-generated political ad carried
by a broadcaster or a cable operator engaged in origination programming would come
7 “Record-Breaking 2024 US Political Ad Spend Likely to Disrupt Commercial Media
Landscape,” The Drum (Aug. 21, 2024), available at https://bit.ly/3XotRF9.
8 “Streaming Hits 40% of U.S. TV Usage for the First Time” Statista, available at
https://bit.ly/4d8XKiI (“[S]treaming services reached a record share of 40.3 percent of
TV usage in the United States last month, leaving cable and broadcast far behind at
27.2 and 20.5 percent, respectively. It's been two years since streaming first surpassed
cable TV in July 2022 and, aside for some seasonal fluctuations, its share of TV viewing
has continued growing steadily since then.”).
9 See, e.g., Comments of Center for Data Innovation at 2 (“A better approach would be
to require disclosure of “materially deceptive media” used in political ads, regardless of
the technology used to create such content. However, even these requirements would
be more appropriately addressed by state and federal election laws to create consistent
requirements for all election ads, such as those shared via online streaming platforms
and on social media, not just those distributed on platforms controlled by broadcasters
and other entities regulated by the FCC.”).
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 4
with a government-mandated disclaimer, but the exact same ad that runs on a
streaming service or social media site would not. This nuance will escape the average
consumer, who is unlikely to be aware that different rules would govern the same or
similar ad depending on the platform on which the ad is carried. If consumers of
“traditional” video service come to expect disclosure of any AI-generated content in
political advertisements, they could be lulled into a false sense of complacency when
they see similar advertisements that are unregulated by the Commission and lack a
Commission-mandated disclaimer. The Commission therefore risks creating AI
disclosure rules which can easily be gamed by political advertisement creators who
seek to mislead potential voters. These risks sharply outweigh any potential benefits of
the proposed rules.
The Commission should defer to other governmental bodies that have a more
direct role in regulating elections. Although the Commission plays an important role in
the political speech landscape, it is not the governmental body best suited to leading the
charge on rules related to AI-generated political speech.10 The FEC has the unique
authority to regulate political disclosures. Courts have recognized this unique authority
and rejected other agencies’ attempts to circumvent or supplement the FEC’s rules,
concluding that “the FEC is the exclusive administrative arbiter of questions concerning
10 Whether the Commission has sufficient legal authority to enact the Proposed Rules
remains a significant issue, one that must be resolved before the Commission moves
forward with any rules in this proceeding.
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 5
the name identifications and disclaimers” for political communications.11 On the other
hand, the Commission’s role in regulating political advertisements is more limited; under
the Communication’s Act, the Commission’s authority in this area extends to such
matters as ensuring that broadcasters provide candidates equal access, document
political ads in the stations’ public file, and disclose the ads’ sponsors.12 Congress
reaffirmed the limited role of the Commission in this area with its enactment of the
Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act in 2002, which assigns the Commission the narrow
task of maintaining information on political communications that the FEC is charged with
regulating.13
AI in political speech is being examined by Congress, States, and other
agencies. While the Commission considers the Proposed Rules, governmental bodies
are considering (or have enacted) regulations in the same space. On Capitol Hill, the
Senate Rules Committee has approved three bills relating to AI in elections,14 and
Senator Schumer has suggested that Congressional legislation might be included in a
11 See Galliano v. United States Postal Service, 836 F.2d 1362, 1368–70 (D.C. Cir.
1988) (holding that the U.S. Postal Service may not impose its own disclaimer
requirements on mailers soliciting political contributions).
12 See 47 U.S.C. §§ 315, 317.
13 Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 2002, Pub. L. 107–155, title II, § 201(b), 116 Stat.
90 (2002) (“The Federal Communications Commission shall compile and maintain any
information the Federal Election Commission may require to carry out section 304(f) of
the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 (as added by subsection (a)), and shall
make such information available to the public on the Federal Communication
Commission’s website.”).
14 “FCC Chairwoman Pushes Plan to Tackle AI in Political Ads Amid FEC Concern,”
U.S. News (June 5, 2024), available at https://bit.ly/47pWJl4 (“The topic has emerged
as a bipartisan priority, with Senate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer calling the bills
important.”).
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 6
budget bill later this year.15 At the same time, almost 20 states have their own rules on
this issue,16 and nearly as many states are currently considering rules on the same.17
And the FEC engaged in its own rulemaking process to consider whether or how the
use of AI in political communications should be regulated.18
In all, the Commission is not operating in a vacuum while it considers the
Proposed Rules; Congress and states are considering rules on the same issue that
could potentially create a more level playing field than any rules the Commission might
seek to adopt under its more limited, industry-specific authority. Rather than adopt rules
now, the Commission should wait to see how this topic is regulated by other
governmental bodies. Only then should the Commission consider establishing its own,
complementary rules. This approach will ensure that the Commission does not
establish confusing and contradictory rules that apply to advertisements on traditional
platforms regulated by the Commission but not on online platforms that are rapidly
overtaking them.
15 “FEC Appears Ready to Take a Pass on Regulating AI in Political Ads,” Broadcast
Law Blog (Aug. 11, 2024), available at https://bit.ly/4cUXa7W.
16 “AI In Political Advertising: State and Federal Regulations In Focus,” Mondaq (Aug.
22, 2024), available at https://bit.ly/4dOj7Xz.
17 Id.
18 “Comments Sought on Amending Regulation to Include Deliberately Deceptive
Artificial Intelligence in Campaign Ads,” Federal Election Commission (Aug. 16, 2023),
available at https://bit.ly/3MJOnLe. Joint Commenters note that on September 19,
2024, the FEC voted to not adopt regulations addressing artificial intelligence in political
ads. See, e.g., “FEC Forgoes New AI Rulemaking Ahead of Election,” The Hill (Sep.
19, 2024), available at https://bit.ly/4gwe3J6.
ACA Connects and NTCA Comments
MB Docket No. 24-211
September 19, 2024 7
III. CONCLUSION
ACA Connects and NTCA appreciate the opportunity to participate in this
proceeding and encourage the Commission to take its suggestions into consideration.
Respectfully submitted,
Brian Hurley
Chief Regulatory Counsel
