COMMENTS OF NEXSTAR MEDIA INC.
Nexstar Media Inc. (“Nexstar”) appreciates the opportunity to comment on the Federal
Communications Commission’s (“FCC” or “Commission”) Notice of Proposed Rulemaking
(“NPRM”) in the above-referenced docket.1 Nexstar supports the Commission’s stated objective
of “assist[ing] voters in making informed decisions about candidates for public office and
controversial issues of public importance,”2 which is consistent with Nexstar’s own mission of
informing viewers and serving its communities. Nexstar respectfully submits, however, that the
Commission’s proposals will not serve these shared goals but will instead create an inconsistent
framework for AI disclosures that will breed confusion among the populace while imposing
significant burdens on local broadcasters. Moreover, the proposals advanced raise significant
statutory and constitutional concerns. Accordingly, Nexstar encourages the Commission not to
adopt the rules proposed in the NPRM.
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, MB Docket No. 24-211, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 24-74 (rel. July
25, 2024) (“NPRM”).
2 Id. ¶ 1.
I. INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY
It is central to the mission of Nexstar and other local broadcasters to provide reliable and
trustworthy information to the public. Indeed, “accuracy and truth” and “transparency” are
among the seven journalism principles to which Nexstar’s approximately 6,000 journalists across
the country are held. This commitment to providing viewers with fact-based information has
earned Nexstar more than 500 awards for outstanding journalism and recognition from multiple
watchdog groups for Nexstar’s commitment to unbiased content. In no context is adherence to
these principles more important than in fostering an informed electorate. Accordingly, Nexstar
understands and appreciates the Commission’s desire to combat the potential use of artificial
intelligence (“AI”) to disseminate false or deceptive information that can “sow[] confusion and
distrust among the voting public.”3
Given the NPRM’s extremely broad definition of “AI-generated content,” however, the
FCC’s proposed disclosure requirements would confuse rather than inform broadcast television
viewers. The proposed regulations would also impose disparate economic and operational
burdens on the broadcasting industry while detracting from potentially beneficial uses of
generative AI in the political advertising context. Notably, the same requirements would not be
imposed on online platforms notwithstanding the fact that online platforms, not broadcast
advertisements, are frequently responsible for the spread of misinformation and disinformation,
including most fake political content.4 Finally, adoption of the proposals would raise significant
legal questions, first because the Commission lacks the statutory authority to impose them.
3 Id.
4 See, e.g., Associated Press, AI-Generated Disinformation Poses Threat of Misleading Voters in
2024 Election, (May 14, 2023), available at https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/ai-generated-
disinformation-poses-threat-of-misleading-voters-in-2024-election (describing use of AI in viral
online content).
2
Moreover, the requirements would compel speech in a heavy-handed manner that does not
clearly serve an underlying government interest, in violation of the First Amendment.
For all of these reasons, the FCC’s proposed rules—even if well intentioned—are ill-
advised and should not be adopted.
II. THE NPRM’S PROPOSALS THREATEN TO UNDERCUT BROADCASTERS’
ABILITY TO KEEP VIEWERS AND LISTENERS INFORMED.
Rather than furthering the FCC’s stated goal of ensuring that broadcast viewers and
listeners receive truthful information and transparent disclosures in political advertising, the
proposals advanced in the NPRM actually threaten to detract from broadcasters’ abilities to keep
the public informed. The Commission’s sweeping definition of “AI-generated content” would, if
adopted, impose burdensome obligations on broadcasters that would hamper their ability to
deliver fact-based information. Moreover, the rules would place broadcasters at a further
disadvantage vis-à-vis most cable networks, multichannel video programming distributors
(“MVPDs”), and other online platforms. The NPRM’s on-air disclosure proposal would
inevitably confuse viewers and listeners who are not likely to distinguish between broadcast ads
(that would contain the disclosures) and ads appearing on other platforms (that would not).
Finally, the proposed online filing requirement for AI-generated content would serve no valid
purpose because the disclosures would be too far removed from the ads to which they apply.
Accordingly, the regulations proposed in the NPRM would not serve the public interest.
A. The NPRM’s Overly Broad Definition of “AI-Generated Content” Will
Burden Broadcasters While Detracting from Beneficial Uses of Generative
AI.
Requiring disclosures for broadcast ads that use “AI-generated content” would be
problematic for broadcasters and consumers alike. The NPRM proposes to define “AI-generated
content” as “an image, audio, or video that has been generated using computational technology
3
or other machine-based system that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an
event, circumstance, or situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that sound like
human voices, and AI-generated actors that appear to be human actors.”5 This sweeping
definition extends far beyond the FCC’s expressed concern about “‘deepfakes’ and other
deceptive and misleading information” that could create “confusion and distrust.”6 Indeed, the
term “generated using computational technology” is particularly broad and would seemingly
encompass digital recording devices and audiovisual editors that are common in the broadcasting
industry and use “computational technology” to generate images, audio, and video.
The sphere of AI-generated content would necessarily capture some beneficial uses of AI
for which disclosures would either be unnecessary or counterproductive. For example, the
NPRM acknowledges that generative AI “can serve the public interest in fostering an informed
electorate” by, among other things, helping to “speed up and automate the generation of political
ads, enabling campaigns and issue advertisers to create new content quickly. . . .”7 Yet, the
NPRM’s definition of AI-generated content would seemingly sweep in important generative AI
applications and advertisements that use AI in a manner that is most certainly not deceptive.
Therefore, the proposal would flood the airwaves with disclosures, as discussed in Section I.B
infra, which will lead to notice fatigue and confusion among the broadcast audience—causing
many viewers and listeners either to think that truthful ads are deceptive or to ignore the
disclosures altogether.
5 NPRM ¶ 12.
6 Id. ¶ 1 (footnote omitted). Moreover, the use of deepfakes in the election context is already
illegal, as 19 states currently have laws to restrict the use of synthetic media and deepfake
technology in the election context. Indeed, Alabama, Arizona, California, Colorado, Florida,
Hawaii, Idaho, Indiana, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, New Hampshire, New Mexico, New
York, Oregon, Texas, Utah, Washington, and Wisconsin have enacted such laws.
7 Id. ¶¶ 1, 9.
4
The problems described above are inherent in any approach that is premised on generic
disclosures about the use of AI. Accordingly, the Commission’s proposals are likely to cause
more harm to consumers than good and should not be adopted.
B. The FCC Should Not Require Broadcasters to Ask Advertisers Whether
Each of Their Political Advertisements Contains AI-Generated Content.
If the FCC were to overlook the fundamental problems with a selective disclosure
requirement for AI-generated political advertisements, it should nevertheless minimize the
burden on broadcasters relevant to determining which ads include AI-generated content. The
Commission proposes to obligate all broadcasters to “inquire whether political ads scheduled to
be aired on stations contain any AI-generated content” and asks whether “a station that makes a
simple inquiry consistent with the Commission’s rules [should] be deemed to have satisfied its
obligations even if there is no response to the inquiry.”8 Even mandating a simple inquiry will
require stations to divert critical resources to identify content that is entirely out of their control.
Requiring anything more, meanwhile, would place broadcasters in the impossible position of: (1)
re-inquiring about every advertisement that does not disclose the use of AI-generated content; or
(2) trying to ascertain without any visibility into how an ad was created whether it might contain
any AI-generated content. A rule that ties a requirement to “re-inquire” to third-party reports, as
raised by the NPRM,9 would place broadcasters in the middle of disputes over political
advertising content that they did not create and have no feasible way of resolving. Nexstar
already expends considerable resources to address complaints about the content of political
ads—complaints that are often frivolous and intended merely to harass the advertiser. The
Commission’s proposal to force broadcasters to re-inquire based on third-party reports would
8 Id. ¶ 15.
9 Id.
5
exacerbate the situation by encouraging parties on opposing sides of a political issue to make
broadcasters the arbiters of which content is AI-generated—a duty local broadcasters are not
economically, operationally, or topically equipped to assume.
At the most, then, the FCC should impose a standard that would require disclosure only
when a broadcaster has actual knowledge that an advertisement contains AI-generated content.
There is no basis to place any more stringent burden on broadcasters.
C. The NPRM’s Proposed On-Air Disclosure Requirement Will Detract from
the Commission’s Goal of Informing the American Electorate and Will
Impose Significant Costs on Broadcasters.
Appending a generic disclosure about the presence of AI-generated content to on-air
advertisements would offer no benefit to viewers and listeners and would come at a considerable
cost to local stations. The FCC proposes to “require that all radio and television broadcast
stations . . . provide an on-air announcement for all such ads disclosing the use of AI-generated
content in the ad.”10 But the Commission does not provide any evidence that a general disclosure
that does not describe the nature of the AI-generated content will result in a more informed
electorate. In practice, such disclosures are likely to create widespread confusion as each viewer
or listener struggles to determine what portion of the advertisement contains AI-generated
content and what the impact of the AI-generated content is on the message.
Even more problematic, the exceptions here will swallow the rule. As proposed, the
requirement would only apply to broadcast stations and the narrow subset of cable operators,
direct broadcast satellite (“DBS”) providers, and SDARS licensees that originate programming.
Applying a different standard to the same advertisements broadcast on-air versus disseminated
through MVPDs or online, however, will create consumer confusion and reduce the informative
10 Id. ¶ 13.
6
impact of the proposed on-air disclosure requirement. That is, if the on-air disclosures achieve
their intended purpose, not only would consumers associate the on-air disclosures with the
presence of AI-generated content, but they also, conversely, would reasonably believe that
advertisements lacking such disclosures do not contain AI-generated content. Uneven political
advertising disclosure requirements across mediums will thus foment audience confusion. And
even amongst distributors of linear video programming, the rule would only apply to
broadcasters and the small group of cable operators, DBS providers, and SDARS that originate
programming. The rule would not extend to some of the largest cable networks that are not
associated with a cable operator or a DBS provider, including Fox News, ESPN, Hallmark
Channel, TBS, History Channel, CNN, and Discovery Channel, to name just a few. Also
excluded are virtual MVPDs—given the FCC’s inaction in its virtual MVPD classification
proceeding.11 These platforms currently receive a significant amount of political spending and
are likely to become even more attractive to advertisers if the Commission imposes its selective
disclosure mandate. Given the narrow sliver of political advertising that the proposed rule will
reach, it will be impossible to achieve the Commission’s stated goal of ensuring that “listeners
and viewers have the necessary information to evaluate such ads for themselves.”12
Beyond the problems the Commission’s disclosure proposal will have for consumers, it
could also result in significant economic and operational costs for stations. Particularly
problematic is the proposal to obligate broadcasters to add the necessary disclosure—even for
candidate ads which broadcasters cannot censor.13 As a result, the FCC apparently expects
11 Promoting Innovation and Competition in the Provision of Multichannel Video Programming
Distribution Services, MB Docket No. 14-261, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 14-210
(rel. Dec. 19, 2014).
12 NPRM ¶ 13.
13 Id. ¶¶ 16, 35.
7
broadcasters to allocate their own airtime (i.e., on top of the time allocated to the political ad) to
broadcast the disclosures. But broadcast stations only have a finite amount of airtime, and the
Commission’s proposal would force stations to reallocate time that could have been spent on
informing or engaging viewers or on additional revenue-generating advertising content. And
although the Commission suggests that making these disclosures will be operationally “simple,”
its assumption is misplaced—stations will be required to dedicate staff to implement these
disclosures, which will require reviewing and modifying advertisements, altering traffic logs,
modifying adjacent programming to accommodate the extended disclosures, and potentially
notifying program suppliers if the disclosures necessitate even a brief preemption of scheduled
programming. In effect, this will slow the advertising approval process, limit the ability of
campaigns to change spots on short notice, and reduce the amount of overall airtime available for
political advertising. These burdens are significant and strongly counsel against imposing the
proposed on-air disclosure proposal for political advertisements that include AI-generated
content.
D. Obligating Local Broadcasters to Include a Notice Disclosing the
Advertisements That Contain AI-Generated Content in Their Online
Political File Will Not Increase Transparency.
The proposal to “require all broadcast stations to include in their online political files a
notice disclosing the use of AI-generated content for each political ad that contains such content”
is based on the incorrect assumption that viewers and listeners will visit a station’s online
political file “to confirm which ads aired by a station contained AI-generated content.”14 Even if
a viewer or listener did want to verify information about whether a specific advertisement
contained AI-generated content, the viewer or listener would need to remember everything about
14 Id. ¶ 18.
8
the ad, including the sponsor and the content. Moreover, the proposed disclosure will be of
limited benefit because neither the information that broadcasters are currently required to submit
to the online political file nor the FCC’s proposed disclosure would allow a listener or viewer to
easily identify with particularity which specific ads either contained or will contain AI-generated
content.
The limited benefits of a political file disclosure requirement cannot possibly justify the
burdens it would impose on local stations nationwide. Accordingly, no matter how the FCC
resolves the remainder of this proceeding, it should not impose a requirement to include
disclosures about the use of AI-generated content in the political file.
III. THE COMMISSION LACKS THE STATUTORY AUTHORITY TO
PROMULGATE ITS ON-AIR DISCLOSURE PROPOSAL.
Whatever merits a disclosure requirement for political ads with AI-generated content may
or may not have, the agency lacks statutory authority to adopt such a requirement. Because the
disclosure proposal triggers the Supreme Court’s major questions doctrine, relevant precedent
requires the Commission to identify a clear grant of statutory authority, which it fails to do. This
failure alone is sufficient for a reviewing court to reject the disclosure proposal. The item also
fails to identify a source of authority under the “single best meaning” of the Communications
Act of 1934, as amended (“Communications Act” or “Act”).15 Finally, additional, independent
textual and structural flaws with the Commission’s reading of the Act confirm that the FCC lacks
authority.
15 Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo, 144 S. Ct. 2244, 2266 (2024) (cleaned up).
9
A. The NPRM Fails to Identify a Clear Congressional Grant of Authority for Its
On-Air Disclosure Proposal.
The major questions doctrine provides that there are “extraordinary cases” where the
“history and the breadth of the authority that the [agency] has asserted,” coupled with the
“economic and political significance” of that assertion provide a “reason to hesitate before
concluding that Congress” intended to confer such authority.16 Specifically, the Supreme Court
has held that “[a] decision of such magnitude and consequence . . . must rest with Congress
itself, or an agency acting pursuant to a clear delegation from that representative body.”17
The on-air disclosure at issue here presents such an extraordinary case. This is most
obvious from the breadth of the Commission’s proposed interpretation of the Act. If, as the FCC
contemplates, the Act allows it to mandate “on-air announcement[s]” to “assist voters in making
informed decisions,” there is no limit to what could come next.18 That same interpretation could
conceivably be used to conscript stations into becoming FCC-sanctioned fact-checkers for all
manner of content. Under that view, if content goes over the airwaves, the Government has free
rein to order stations to supplement it with the Government’s preferred message. The “breadth
of the Government’s claimed authority” would thus effect an “unprecedented power” over the
free flow of information in this country.19 Accordingly, the Commission must identify a clear
grant of authority. It has failed to do so here.
The FCC instead invokes Section 303(r)—its ancillary authority.20 That provision allows
the FCC to “make such rules and regulations . . . as may be necessary to carry out the provisions
16 FDA v. Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., 529 U.S. 120, 159–160 (2000).
17 Biden v. Nebraska, 143 S. Ct. 2355, 2374 (2023) (quotations omitted).
18 NPRM ¶¶ 16, 1.
19 W. Virginia v. EPA, 597 U.S. 697, 728–29 (2022).
20 NPRM ¶ 27; 47 U.S.C. § 303(r).
10
of” the Communications Act.21 And according to the NPRM, the agency is purporting to “carry
out” its “general standard” for licensees to act in “the public interest, convenience or
necessity.”22
These provisions do not offer the clear statement required by the major questions
doctrine. Neither Section 303(r) nor the FCC’s public interest standard articulated in Title III of
the Communications Act reference AI, deception, or political advertising. Instead, the
Commission’s broad assertion of authority relies on exactly the sort of “vague language of an
ancillary provision” that the Supreme Court has determined to fall short of its clear statement
requirement.23 The lack of this clear statement is sufficient for a reviewing court to reject the
Commission’s reliance on its Section 303(r) ancillary authority. Accordingly, the FCC’s on-air
disclosure proposal cannot survive a judicial challenge under the Supreme Court’s major
questions doctrine.
B. Even Absent a Clear Statement of Authority, the Commission’s Assertion
that It Can Rely on Its Ancillary Authority Is Not the Single, Best Meaning
of the Communications Act.
Notwithstanding the applicability of the major questions doctrine to the NPRM’s on-air
disclosure proposal, reviewing courts will, when assessing an agency’s statutory authority to
promulgate a rule, consider whether the agency has identified a source of authority under the
“single, best meaning” of the Communications Act “fixed at the time of its enactment.”24 The
21 47 U.S.C. § 303(r).
22 NPRM ¶ 27 (citing 47 U.S.C. §§ 307(a), 309(a)); accord Comcast Corp. v. FCC, 600 F.3d
642, 644 (D.C. Cir. 2010) (explaining that FCC may invoke “‘ancillary’ authority only if it
demonstrates that its action . . . is reasonably ancillary to the effective performance of its
statutorily mandated responsibilities”) (cleaned up).
23 W. Virginia, 597 U.S. at 724 (cleaned up).
24 Loper Bright, 144 S. Ct. at 2266 (cleaned up).
11
Commission’s asserted authority under Section 303(r) and the Title III public interest standard
fail to meet this standard.
Although Section 303(r) and Title III “authorize[ ]” the Commission “to exercise a
degree of discretion,” the agency is required to stay within “the boundaries of [that] delegated
authority.”25 Courts examining the contours of this standard have held that the FCC’s public
interest authority must not “be interpreted as setting up a standard so indefinite as to confer an
unlimited power.”26 Instead, it must be “interpreted by its context.”27 Both the Supreme Court
and the Commission have long interpreted the Commission’s public interest objectives to be
“promoting competition, localism, and viewpoint diversity.”28 However, “the Act does not essay
to regulate the business of the licensee,” and the “Commission is given no supervisory control of
the programs, of business management or of policy.”29 The FCC’s proposal here would regulate
beyond the single, best meaning of the Communications Act by seeking “supervisory control of
the programs” aired by broadcasters. It is untethered from the well-understood goals of
“competition, localism, and viewpoint diversity” and, therefore, outside the FCC’s authority.
C. Additional Constitutional and Textual Infirmities Require That the
Commission Abandon Its On-Air Disclosure Proposal.
Other textual and structural considerations also independently undercut the
Commission’s asserted authority over on-air disclosures for AI-generated political content.
To begin, Congress’s specific and limited grants of authority over broadcast content—
including political programming—foreclose reading a general and unlimited grant of authority
25 Id. at 2263.
26 Nat’l Broad. Co. v. United States, 319 U.S. 190, 216 (1943).
27 Id.
28 FCC v. Prometheus Radio Project, 592 U.S. 414, 419 (2021).
29 FCC v. Sanders Bros. Radio Station, 309 U.S. 470, 475 (1940).
12
over the content of political programming into the Communications Act. Congress has spoken
clearly when it wants to regulate broadcast content—for example, where content is “false” or
“obscene.”30 Congress has also spoken clearly when it wants the Commission to wade into
political advertising, giving the Commission specific authority over disclosures related to
political programming pursuant to Sections 312 and 315 of the Communications Act.31 At the
same time, Congress has imposed strict limits on the Commission’s authority to regulate political
broadcasts beyond those express grants of authority, foreclosing any kind of “censorship.”32
Courts presume that these choices by Congress are intentional,33 confirming that Congress did
not intend to give the FCC broad, general authority to regulate broadcast content.
The Commission’s interpretation would also render Congress’s targeted Title III
provisions “meaningless.”34 For example, the Act provides specific authority over such matters
as sponsorship identification, political recordkeeping requirements, and even “the painting and/or
illumination of radio towers.”35 If the Commission’s “public interest” authority allows it to order
any policy that the Commission considers to be in the public interest—disregarding the well-
settled limits of that term—then none of these provisions would be necessary. They would all
