already be within the (unbounded) scope of the public interest. That result would flatly
contradict the maxim that statutes should not be interpreted to render provisions “superfluous.”36
There are still further reasons why the NPRM’s assertion of authority rests on shaky
statutory grounds. For one, an interpretation giving the FCC unbounded authority to define the
“public interest” would raise serious constitutional concerns under the nondelegation doctrine
because—absent the traditional constraints on that authority—the Act would be without an
intelligible principle.37 Moreover, the agency’s interpretation would extend the FCC’s authority
over the content of political advertising notwithstanding the fundamental assumption that
“Congress likely did not give [multiple agencies] separate authority to develop . . . conflicting
[sets of] rules.”38 In a letter to the FCC, the Chairman of the Federal Election Commission
raised this very concern, explaining that the FCC’s proposals would “directly conflict with
existing law and regulations, and sow chaos among political campaigns for the upcoming
election.”39
In the absence of clear authority to implement a rule mandating disclosures for political
advertisements containing AI-generated content, the Commission’s proposal is ultra vires and
should not be adopted.
