IV. THE NPRM’S ON-AIR DISCLOSURE PROPOSAL WOULD VIOLATE THE
FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHTS OF BROADCASTERS AND ADVERTISERS
ALIKE.
The Commission’s on-air disclosure proposal would violate the First Amendment of the
U.S. Constitution, which prohibits the agency from adopting regulations that would “abridg[e]
the freedom of speech. . . .”40
The disclosure proposal would be subject to strict scrutiny under First Amendment
precedent because it is a content-based restriction on political speech41 that also compels speech.
As such, the FCC must identify a compelling government interest to justify its regulation and
demonstrate that the proposed rules are narrowly tailored to achieve that interest.42 The
Commission has done neither, nor can it. Accordingly, the proposal, if adopted, would violate
the First Amendment.
A. The NPRM’s Disclosure Proposal is Subject to Strict Scrutiny as Both a
Content-Based Restriction on Speech and a Regulation That Compels
Speech.
The First Amendment “bars the government from dictating what we see or read or speak
or hear.”43 Accordingly, laws that regulate speech based on its content or viewpoint are subject
to strict scrutiny—they “are presumptively unconstitutional and may be justified only if the
government proves that they are narrowly tailored to serve compelling state interests.”44 The
disclosure proposal is subject to strict scrutiny because it is content-based on its face as it only
regulates “political advertising” speech.45 Indeed, application of the disclosure “depend[s]
40 U.S. Const. Amend. I
41 FEC v. Cruz, 596 U.S. 289, 302 (2022); see also Ariz. Free Enter. Club’s Freedom Club PAC
v. Bennett, 564 U.S. 721, 734 (2011).
42 Bennett, 564 U.S. at 734, 776.
43 Ashcroft v. Free Speech Coal., 535 U.S. 234, 245 (2002).
44 Reed v. Town of Gilbert, 576 U.S. 155, 163 (2015); see id. at 168–69.
45 NPRM ¶ 2.
15
entirely on the communicative content of” the message.46 The on-air disclosure proposal is also
independently subject to strict scrutiny because it compels “speech that a speaker would not
otherwise make,” meaning that the proposal would “necessarily alter[ ] the content of the
speech.”47
The Commission is incorrect that its restriction may be entitled to a lower standard of
review under the Supreme Court’s “scarcity rationale.”48 For one, the scarcity rationale has been
“long ago abandoned” by the Supreme Court.49 Supreme Court Justices openly “doubt” the
“continued validity” of the scarcity rationale.50 And the Supreme Court has repeatedly declined
to extend the scarcity rationale in new contexts.51 Given that the scarcity rationale is no longer
good law, the Commission should not rely on it here.
Next, even if the scarcity rationale remained good law, it would not apply to the
Commission’s proposal. The Supreme Court has explained that “given spectrum scarcity, those
who are granted a license to broadcast must serve in a sense as fiduciaries for the public by
presenting those views and voices which are representative of their community and which would
