otherwise, by necessity, be barred from the airwaves.”52 But here, the Commission’s goal is not
to ensure “representative” views. Rather it is to offer “transparency” and prevent “deception.”
See infra. Whatever the merits of those interests, they have nothing to do with the scarcity of
broadcast spectrum; the Commission seeks to address a situation present on all media.53
Finally, even if the scarcity rationale applied, the FCC must still establish that the
proposed regulations further “the government’s legitimate, content-neutral interests” and do so
by means that are “narrowly tailored to serve the government’s legitimate, content-neutral
interests. . . .”54 The Commission cannot satisfy even this lower standard because, as explained
below, its proposal lacks a legitimate government interest and fails to tailor its speech regulation.
B. The FCC Lacks a Compelling or Even an Important Interest to Justify Its
Proposed On-Air Disclosure Requirement.
The FCC has not identified a legitimate interest to support the proposed regulation of
speech under either strict or intermediate scrutiny. The Commission’s purported interest is “in
providing greater transparency regarding the use of AI-generated content in political
advertising.”55 Courts have repeatedly held, however, that it is “not enough for the Government
to say simply that it has a substantial interest in giving consumers information.”56 The agency
