But the FCC has no interest, much less one that is compelling or important, in “better balanc[ing]
the speech market.”58
Moreover, the FCC claims that AI-generated content “creates a potential for providing
deceptive, misleading, or fraudulent information to voters.”59 However, the NPRM has not
identified a single example of an AI-generated broadcast-media political ad that has deceived,
mislead, or defrauded voters.60 Indeed, the NPRM’s justification is insufficient—the agency
“must provide evidence establishing ‘that the harms it recites are real.’”61 The agency fails to
make this requisite showing under First Amendment precedent.
C. The NPRM’s On-Air Disclosure Proposal Is Not Tailored to Achieve Its
Purported Goal of Informing Listeners and Viewers About the Presence of
AI-Generated Content in Political Advertisements.
Even if the Commission had identified “an ‘actual problem’ in need of solving,” its
proposed disclosure obligation is not “actually necessary to the solution.”62 Indeed, the proposed
disclosure rule is “vastly overinclusive”63 because, despite the agency’s stated interest in
