preventing deception in political advertising, it does not propose to limit the disclosure to AI-
generated content that is deceptive in nature.64 Instead, it requires broadcasters to make
disclosures with respect to all political ads that utilize AI-generated content in any way,
regardless of their potential to deceive.65
The FCC’s imprecise approach is further magnified by its cavernous “AI-generated
content” definition, which, as stated in Section II.A supra, would seemingly encompass any
audio or audiovisual spot produced or edited using digital technologies.66 The Commission
provides no rationale for why a disclosure requirement that would conceivably sweep in every
political advertisement produced using digital recording devices and audiovisual editors
equipped with computational technology is necessary to prevent deception.67 Given the
“dramatic mismatch . . . between the interest that the [FCC] seeks to promote and the disclosure
regime” it has proposed,68 the proposed on-air disclosure obligation is not narrowly tailored.
The Commission’s disclosure proposal is also underinclusive.69 As explained above, the
proposal would only apply to on-air broadcasts and to a discrete subset of MVPD transmissions.
But it would not extend to some of the most popular cable networks or to online advertisements
that have millions of viewers, such as those disseminated on social media platforms or even
64 NPRM ¶¶ 1-2.
65 Id. ¶ 16.
66 Cf. id. (Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Brendan Carr at 5) (noting that “CGI, image
cropping, or tools to amplify the quality of a person’s voice” may fall under agency’s capacious
definition).
67 Congress commonly limits restrictions on speech to only “deceptive” speech. See, e.g., 15
U.S.C. § 45(a)(1) (prohibiting “deceptive acts or practices”).
68 Americans for Prosperity Foundation v. Bonta, 594 U.S. 595, 612 (2021).
69 See Brown, 564 U.S. at 802 (explaining “[u]nderinclusiveness raises serious doubts about
whether the government is in fact pursuing the interest it invokes, rather than disfavoring a
particular speaker or viewpoint”).
19
linear video distribution platforms not subject to the proposed rules.70 More fundamentally, if
the FCC’s concern is with deception in political advertising, an exclusive focus on AI-generated
content is fatally underinclusive. Indeed, voice actors and lying—without any artificially
generated content—can deceive voters and spread disinformation just as easily as AI-generated
content. Accordingly, the Commission’s disclosure proposal is not tailored to achieve its stated
interest and would violate the First Amendment if adopted.
V. CONCLUSION
Nexstar is committed to ensuring that its viewers receive reliable, truthful information
necessary to make informed decisions about candidates for public office. The proposals in the
NPRM, although seemingly well-intended, would not further this objective. Instead, the
proposed disclosure requirements would be counterproductive and impose significant burdens on
broadcasters. In addition to being ill-advised, the proposed disclosure requirements go beyond
the authority Congress has granted to the FCC and constitute government compelled speech that
cannot survive judicial scrutiny. While Nexstar commends that FCC for attempting to address
the potential pitfalls of artificial intelligence, the Commission must not adopt the proposed rules.
70 NPRM (Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Brendan Carr at 5) (explaining that the FCC’s
proposal would exclude “over-the-top content, like online streaming video and social media,
where millions of Americans see political ads”).
