COMMENTS OF THE NRSC
The NRSC (National Republican Senatorial Committee) submits these comments in
response to the Federal Communications Commission’s (“FCC” or “the Commission”) Notice of
Proposed Rulemaking (“NPRM”) proposing to require on-air disclosures for any political
advertisement that uses artificial intelligence (“AI”)-generated content (“AI-Disclosure
Proposal”).1
The FCC’s approach is misguided. To start, the AI-Disclosure Proposal is overly broad.
Even though the proposed rule purports to target only “AI-generated content,” its definition of that
term appears to reach all content generated by any computational technology, potentially including
basic tools to produce digital media. And even though the proposed rule purports to burden only
broadcasters, it would in fact broadly regulate speech by many speakers on a wide range of public
issues, including speech by political committees about candidates and campaigns for public office.
It is also unlawful. If adopted, the AI-disclosure mandate would regulate speech in violation of
the First Amendment, and the agency’s sweeping theory of authority would contravene the
Communications Act. Finally, the NPRM’s proposed approach is bad policy. It is duplicative of
existing prohibitions on false speech, such as defamation law and restrictions on unfair and
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, MB Docket No. 24-211, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 24-74, ¶ 15 (2024)
(“NPRM”).
deceptive acts. Worse yet, it is counterproductive: it would exacerbate regulatory fragmentation;
it would create confusion by applying inconsistent rules across different media; it would stifle the
positive impacts of AI in political advertising; and it would spawn enormous operational
difficulties for broadcasters and political advertisers. For all of these reasons, the Commission
should abandon its AI-Disclosure Proposal.
I. THE AI-DISCLOSURE PROPOSAL IS UNNECESSARILY BROAD.
The breadth of the Commission’s AI-Disclosure Proposal is striking. Although the NPRM
says that it seeks to regulate “[t]he use of AI technologies,” its proposed approach is far broader
than that.2 One need look no further than the proposed definition of “AI-generated content” to see
why. The Commission proposes to define that term as:
an image, audio, or video that has been generated using computational technology or other
machine-based system that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an
event, circumstance, or situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that sound
like human voices, and AI-generated actors that appear to be human actors.3
That definition would sweep in political-advertising practices that nobody would consider
to be a product of AI and that have been commonplace in political advertising for decades. As
Commissioner Carr rightly explained: “It would be difficult, in this day and age, to imagine an
advertisement (political or not) that does not use a ‘computational technology’ to ‘depict’ an
‘event, circumstance, or situation.’”4 For example, the Commission’s interpretation would
presumably cover ads that:
• Use a computer program to blur the background setting in order to draw the
viewer’s focus to a candidate running for office.
2 Id. ¶ 1.
3 Id. ¶ 12.
4 NPRM, Carr Dissent 41.
2
• Apply “image cropping” in video-editing software to format raw footage so that it
can be displayed on a television screen.5
• Contain a still image of a candidate that has been given a photoshop touchup to
remove a blemish.
• Display a graphic that applies a highlighting effect over a pertinent newspaper
headline.
• Apply a black-and-white filter to indicate to the viewer that an event depicted
occurred in the past.
The list could go on. The point is that the public does not understand any of these common
and well-accepted practices to be “AI.” Yet all would presumably be covered by the Commission’s
AI-Disclosure Proposal.
For this reason, the Commission is wrong to assume that the burdens of the AI-Disclosure
Proposal are minor and would fall only on broadcasters.6 Instead, the disclosure appears to apply
to virtually every political ad in the modern era because virtually all political ads use the common
practices described above, as well as other similar practices. And the compliance burdens would
fall disproportionately on the political advertisers themselves. After all, it is the advertisers that
would lose out on precious airtime and screen space when the disclosure is required. It is the
advertisers that would be tasked with developing ads that would avoid triggering the disclosure,
while still retaining the professional polish and communicative impact necessary to appeal to
voters. And it is the advertisers that would have to interpret the definition and make the call on
what is compliant.
As explained below, this broad scope creates issue after issue with the AI-Disclosure
Proposal. It magnifies the proposal’s burden on protected speech. It contributes to the proposal
5 Id.
6 See NPRM ¶ 36.
3
triggering the major questions doctrine and leads the Commission far beyond its statutory
authority. And it creates serious compliance issues for political advertisers. This scoping issue
alone is a sufficient reason to withdraw the NPRM.
II. THE AI-DISCLOSURE PROPOSAL IS UNLAWFUL.
The AI-Disclosure Proposal is unlawful under both the First Amendment and the
Communications Act.
A. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Violate the First Amendment.
The Supreme Court has held many times that “speech on public issues occupies the highest
rung of the hierarchy of First Amendment values.”7 “The First Amendment,” the Supreme Court
has also explained, “has its fullest and most urgent application precisely to the conduct of
campaigns for political office.”8 Indeed, “there is practically universal agreement that a major
purpose of th[e] Amendment was to protect the free discussion of governmental affairs, of course
including discussions of candidates.”9
Despite the Supreme Court’s teaching that the First Amendment most jealously guards
against government intrusions on political speech, the Commission proposes to single out precisely
this type of speech for heavy regulation under its AI-Disclosure Proposal. Because the proposed
mandate is content-based, it would be subject to strict scrutiny. But the proposal cannot survive
that First Amendment standard (or any other) because the Commission has failed to tailor its
proposal to any legitimate government interest.
7 Snyder v. Phelps, 562 U.S. 443, 452 (2011) (quoting Connick v. Myers, 461 U.S. 138, 145
(1983)); see also Ariz. Free Enter. Club’s Freedom Club PAC v. Bennett, 564 U.S. 721, 755 (2011)
(“debate on public issues should be uninhibited, robust, and wide-open”).
8 FEC v. Cruz, 596 U.S. 289, 302 (2022) (quotations omitted).
9 McIntyre v. Ohio Elections Comm’n, 514 U.S. 334, 346 (1995) (cleaned up).
4
1. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Impose Heavy Burdens on Political
Speech.
The Commission’s proposed AI-disclosure mandate would burden political speech in at
least two interrelated ways. First, the proposed mandate would compel speech—by requiring an
“on-air announcement” to disclose when political advertisements “contain[ ] AI-generated
content.”10 It is black-letter law that the First Amendment guards against laws that “compel a
person to speak [a government] message when he would prefer to remain silent” or to “force an
individual to include other ideas with his own speech that he would prefer not to include.”11 The
proposed mandate would thus intrude upon “the right” of both political advertisers and
broadcasters “to refrain from speaking” a government message.12
Second, the AI-Disclosure Proposal would prohibit speech because it would occupy a
substantial portion of the already-limited time and space in political advertisements. It is axiomatic
that government regulation triggers the First Amendment when it “restrict[s] expression.”13 The
Commission would restrict expression by imposing an additional government-disclosure mandate
that takes up “four percent” of an ad’s visual space and “four seconds” of its runtime.14 Because
an ad has only finite space—typically running for 15 or 30 seconds—a disclosure mandate would
force political advertisers to, “as a practical matter, omit something else.”15 And of course,
