12 Janus v. Am. Fed’n of State, Cnty., & Mun. Emps., Council 31, 585 U.S. 878, 892 (2018)
(quotations omitted); see NetChoice v. Bonta, ___ F.4th ___, 2024 WL 3838423, at *9 (9th Cir.
Aug. 16, 2024).
13 Reed v. Town of Gilbert, 576 U.S. 155, 163 (2015).
14 NPRM ¶ 17.
15 Miami Herald Pub. Co. v. Tornillo, 418 U.S. 241, 257 n.22 (1974); accord Am. Beverage Ass’n
v. City & Cnty. of San Francisco, 916 F.3d 749, 757 (9th Cir. 2019) (en banc).
5
political ads are already subject to other state and federal disclosure requirements, making these
burdens cumulative.16 The result is that a four-second disclosure could result in a cumulative
burden of more than eight seconds reserved to the government on a 15- or 30-second ad.17 And
that foregone runtime is expensive, adding a dollars-and-cents harm on top of the expressive
burden. Thus, government occupation of an additional four seconds of runtime or four percent of
the screen imposes a significant burden on political speakers.
Other aspects of the proposed mandate would amplify these speech burdens. For one, the
speech being compelled would require political advertisers to denigrate their own messages. As
the NPRM itself makes clear, the FCC’s driving concern behind the proposed AI-disclosure
mandate is that AI-generated content may be deceptive—e.g., “deepfakes,” “manipulated media,”
and depictions of “people doing or saying things they did not actually do or say.”18 While the
NPRM’s doomsday predictions about AI-generated content being deceptive are overstated and
one-sided, they reveal a fundamental truth: when viewers see a government-mandated AI
disclosure, they will believe—often incorrectly—that they are being shown false or misleading
content. The result is a First Amendment burden that is all the “more constitutionally offensive”
because it requires the political speaker “to publicly condemn itself.”19
These burdens are also further magnified by the Commission’s third-party reporting
