proposal, under which stations may be obligated to take “appropriate actions” when “informed by
a credible third party that a political ad contains AI-generated content” in some circumstances.20
The result of this proposal will be to “invite highly motivated politicos to file a flood of complaints
alleging ‘AI-generated content,’ not for the sake of the truth, but as a cudgel to chill opponents’
speech.”21 That flood promises to drown out the “breathing space” necessary for “First
Amendment freedoms” to “survive.”22
2. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Trigger Strict Scrutiny.
The AI-Disclosure Proposal’s heavy speech burdens trigger strict scrutiny because the
proposed mandate is “content-based”—for two reasons.23 First, the proposed mandate is content-
based on its face because it applies to only one type of speech: “political advertising.”24 Where a
law “singles out one particular topic of speech—campaign-related speech—for regulatory
attention,” it is a “content-based regulation on speech.”25 Second, the proposed mandate is
content-based because it compels “speech that a speaker would not otherwise make,” which
“necessarily alters the content of the speech.”26
Under strict scrutiny, the AI-disclosure mandate would be “presumptively
