interest in giving consumers information.”33 Thus, the FCC has to muster more than transparency
for transparency’s sake to satisfy the First Amendment. And while the Commission also claims
that the disclosure mandate will “ensur[e] that the public can assess the substance and credibility
of the information they receive,” thereby “fostering an informed electorate,”34 that is just the
transparency rationale with a different coat of paint. The Government simply does not have an
interest in “better balanc[ing] the speech market.”35
Perhaps recognizing these issues, the agency next claims AI-generated content “creates a
potential for providing deceptive, misleading, or fraudulent information to voters.”36 But the
NPRM fails to offer any evidence to support this interest—in fact, the NPRM does not cite even a
single political broadcast that has deceived voters. The Commission cannot just “posit the
existence of the disease sought to be cured.”37 Rather, it “must provide evidence establishing ‘that
the harms it recites are real.’”38 Thus, hypothetical deception does not suffice as a government
interest.
But even if the Commission’s speculative concerns constituted “an ‘actual problem’ in
need of solving,” the proposed AI-disclosure mandate is inadequately tailored to accomplish that
