even though the proposal is nominally aimed at curing deception, it would require disclosure in all
political ads with AI-generated content—regardless of the ad’s propensity to deceive.40 Yet, as
the Commission notes, there are beneficial, non-misleading uses of AI-generated content, such as
creating ads “in multiple languages.”41 For these ads, there is no deception to cure, but they are
swept in anyways. Another element of the proposal’s overinclusiveness is its expansive definition
of “AI-generated content”—i.e., all content “generated using computational technology” that
depicts individuals or events. As discussed above, that unbounded definition could be read to
reach everything generated by a computer, from Chat-GPT-generated scripts to photoshop
touchups.42 Thus, while nominally targeted at AI, the proposal would reach all kinds of content
created with tools that are not understood to be AI.
The overinclusiveness of the NPRM’s proposal is underscored when compared to other,
less speech-restrictive alternatives.43 For example, other statutes that are concerned with deception
rightly limit their application to only activities that are “deceptive.”44 And defamation law imposes
liability only for mistruths concerning public figures that are made with “actual malice”—precisely
