appropriately tailored to deception confirms that its proposal is fatally overbroad.
Finally, even if the proposed AI-disclosure mandate was tailored to cover potential
deception—and, to be clear, it is not so tailored, and there is no evidence of deception—it would
still be overbroad. That is because even “false speech receives some constitutional protection.”46
Indeed, our country has made a “profound national commitment to the principle that debate on
public issues should be uninhibited, robust, and wide-open.”47 To preserve that commitment, the
Supreme Court’s “interpretations of the First Amendment guarantees have consistently refused to
recognize an exception for any test of truth.”48 Because the proposal’s broad approach fails to
accommodate any protections for (entirely speculative) false speech, it is overbroad for that reason
too.
But these are not the only tailoring issues. In other respects, the proposed mandate is
“seriously underinclusive,” raising “serious doubts about whether the government is in fact
pursuing the interest it invokes.”49 Foremost, the FCC’s exclusive focus on AI is woefully
underinclusive to combat potential deception. The Commission offers no reason why it omits non-
