AI forms of deception (e.g., impersonators, lighting tricks, props) from its regulatory scheme. And
its proposal would “single[ ] out [broadcast media] for disfavored treatment,”50 excluding “over-
the-top content, like online streaming video and social media, where millions of Americans see
political ads.”51 The Commission offers no justification for this omission, either.
For these reasons, the AI-Disclosure Proposal would violate the First Amendment.
B. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Is Not Authorized by the Communications Act.
The Commission “has no power to act … unless and until Congress confers power upon
it.”52 Except for specific, limited provisions that all agree do not apply here, Congress has
conferred no power on the Commission to regulate AI, broadcast content, or political advertising.
Thus, adopting the NPRM would exceed the FCC’s statutory authority.
1. The Commission Lacks Authority To Impose the AI-Disclosure Proposal.
The onus is on the Commission to identify a clear statement of authority for its proposal—
for two reasons. First, the AI-Disclosure Proposal is a proposed rule of “vast economic and
political significance” that requires a “clear statement” under the “major questions doctrine.”53
This is because the agency’s assertion of authority has “no limiting principle” and would “by its
own terms … empower the FCC to operate as the nation’s speech police.”54 The result is an
interpretation that has all the hallmarks of a major question. The Commission “has never
previously claimed” such a power to regulate the free expression of ideas in the nation’s
