elections.55 Its proposed authority—as articulated in the NPRM—would give it “staggering,”
“virtually unlimited power” to deputize every broadcaster in the country to weigh in on the truth
or falsity of electoral advocacy.56 And the role of disinformation in elections—and AI
specifically—is “a matter of earnest and profound debate across the country.”57 Indeed, “Congress
is not unaware of” the Commission’s concerns,58 as shown by pending legislation on this exact
topic.59 Second, as explained, the proposal would put the Communications Act on a “constitutional
collision” course with the First Amendment, triggering “the canon of constitutional avoidance.”60
Under that canon, the Commission must identify “clear statutory language” authorizing its
proposal.61
The Commission fails to identify a clear statement that would be necessary to authorize its
AI-Disclosure Proposal. It in fact does the opposite, relying on arguably the two vaguest grants
of authority in the Communications Act: (i) Section 303(r), which allows the Commission to make
rules that are “necessary to carry out” other provisions of the statute,62 and (ii) its “general
standard” for licensees to act in “the public interest, convenience or necessity,” which it purports
to carry out.63 But these provisions say nothing about AI, deception, or political advertising. They
