interpretation fails both major questions and constitutional avoidance, and it should be rejected on
those grounds alone.
Even absent a clear-statement requirement, the Commission would lack statutory authority.
To proceed with its proposal, the Commission must identify a source of authority under the “single,
best meaning” of the Communications Act.65 Although the Commission’s ancillary and public-
interest authority allow it “to exercise a degree of discretion,” it must still act within “the
boundaries of [that] delegated authority.”66 Indeed, even under the deferential, now-overruled
Chevron standard, the Supreme Court rejected agency interpretations of broad grants of
rulemaking authority, such as provisions authorizing “regulation[s]” that are “appropriate and
necessary.”67 And the D.C. Circuit has repeatedly rejected the FCC’s invocations of ancillary
authority where “the regulations had not been justified as reasonably ancillary to the Commission’s
power over broadcasting.”68
Here, the AI-Disclosure Proposal would exceed the Commission’s claimed authority under
Section 303(r) and the general public-interest standard. The Supreme Court has long recognized
that the Communications Act’s “public interest” standard does not give the agency “unlimited
