that authority has never been understood to allow the Commission “to regulate the business of the
licensee” or to give the Commission “supervisory control of the programs, of business
management or of policy.”71 Thus, the proposed AI-disclosure mandate is not within the
Commission’s public-interest authority (nor reasonably ancillary to that authority) because it has
nothing to do with the traditional public-interest goals and instead purports to exercise the kind of
supervisory control over programming that the Supreme Court has forbidden.
