Finally, the Commission’s unbounded interpretation of its public-interest authority would
raise a host of new problems. If “public interest” is not understood as limited to the Commission’s
traditional public-interest goals, then it would give the Commission an “unlimited power” over
broadcast.80 Such a blank check would lack an intelligible principle and thus raise grave
constitutional doubts under the nondelegation doctrine.81 It would also render much of Title III
unnecessary, given that the “public interest” would swallow any substantive policy in the statute—
including the limited and specific grants of authority over political advertising. And it would place
broadcasters in an impossible position by subjecting them to liability for running certain kinds of
political content, while simultaneously prohibiting them from “censor[ing]” any political
content.82 Congress would not have imposed such an impossibility.
For these reasons, the Communications Act cannot bear the expansive interpretation that
would be required to justify the AI-Disclosure Proposal.
2. The Commission Lacks Authority Over Political Advertisers.
The Commission also lacks statutory authority to enact its proposed AI-disclosure mandate
for a second, independent reason: political advertisers do not fall within the ambit of the
Communications Act or the FCC’s expertise. Indeed, the Communications Act is concerned with
