17
the transmission of “communication[s] by wire or radio,”83 not with electioneering.
While the NPRM nominally accepts this limitation by framing its proposal as applying to
“radio and television broadcast stations,”84 in reality, the Commission seeks to impermissibly
regulate political advertisers. The Commission’s AI-disclosure mandate is triggered solely by the
content produced by political advertisers. The disclosure is solely about that content. The
disclosure will appear “immediately preceding or during” the broadcast of that content.85 And the
disclosure will primarily impose burdens on political advertisers. Indeed, political ads use
numerous “computational” elements that might be subject to the proposed AI-disclosure mandate’s
broad scope, meaning political advertisers will need to spend time understanding the elements of
the ad, and exactly how the ad was created and edited. This will of course create practical
problems. For example, production vendors frequently obtain licenses to use stock footage in
political ads (e.g., children waving American flags). Unless a stock footage database voluntarily
discloses whether the stock footage incorporates “AI-generated content,” the vendor—and the
political advertiser—will have no way of knowing its origin. It will be primarily up to political
advertisers to navigate these compliance hurdles.
It is well-established that the Commission may not use “a device to accomplish indirectly
83 47 U.S.C. § 152(a).
84 NPRM ¶ 13. In the Commission’s telling, the “station” will “make an on-air announcement
disclosing that the ad contains AI-generated content.” Id. ¶ 16.
85 NPRM ¶ 16.
18
what the statute clearly forbids.”86 Because the Commission proposes to regulate political
advertisers that are beyond its jurisdiction, its proposal is unlawful.
III. THE AI-DISCLOSURE PROPOSAL RAISES SERIOUS POLICY ISSUES.
A. The Commission’s AI-Disclosure Proposal Is Unnecessary and Duplicative.
The Commission suggests that its “particular concern” with AI in political advertising is
the creation and distribution of deepfakes, which the FCC defines as “altered images, videos, or
audio recordings that depict people doing or saying things they did not actually do or say, or events
that did not actually occur.”87 Leaving aside that the AI-Disclosure Proposal would regulate much
more than just deepfakes, the proposal is not necessary to achieve the Commission’s purported
concern because harmful deepfakes are already regulated.
State defamation law already addresses deepfakes and provides a remedy to injured
candidates. For example, if, as the NPRM posits as a hypothetical, a political advertiser released
a “deepfake” that falsely showed “a candidate drunk, or speaking incoherently, or consorting with
a disreputable figure,”88 the candidate in question could bring a civil suit alleging “a false and
defamatory statement.”89 And unlike the Commission’s misguided proposal, defamation law is
longstanding and has been interpreted by the Supreme Court to conform with the First
86 Ass’n of Commc’ns Enters. v. FCC, 235 F.3d 662, 665 (D.C. Cir. 2001); see also id. at 668
(vacating FCC order in part); accord City of Eugene v. FCC, 998 F.3d 701, 711 (6th Cir. 2021)
(agreeing Government “may not end-run the Act’s limitations by using . . . sources of authority to
accomplish indirectly what” it is “prohibited from doing directly.”) (cleaned up) (quoting FCC);
McManus, 944 F.3d at 517 (“we hazard giving government the ability to accomplish indirectly …
what it cannot do through direct regulation”).
87 NPRM ¶ 10.
88 See id. ¶ 10 n.45.
89 Restatement (Second) of Torts § 558 (Am. L. Inst. June 2024 update).
19
Amendment.90 Accordingly, the FCC’s proposal is unnecessary to address its purported concerns.
B. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Exacerbate the Problem of Regulatory
Fragmentation.
The NPRM and accompanying Commission statements claim to bring uniform
requirements to on-air disclosures.91 However, the proposal would have the exact opposite impact.
As Commissioner Carr’s dissent recognizes, “[t]he FCC is legally powerless to adopt uniform rules
in a technologically neutral fashion.”92 “Its legal authority claimed here extends only to legacy
media—broadcast, cable, and satellite television—but not over-the-top content, like online
streaming video and social media, where millions of Americans see political ads.”93 “As a result,
AI-generated political ads that run on traditional TV and radio will come with a government-
mandated disclaimer but the exact same ad that runs on a streaming service or social media site
would not.”94 The proposal will thus create more confusion and add to the patchwork of state and
federal disclosure laws.
C. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Result in Confusion Across the Political-
Advertising Ecosystem, Including for Voters.
Another unintended consequence of the AI-Disclosure Proposal would be to increase
confusion for voters around political advertisements. Despite the FCC’s intent to “provide greater
transparency regarding the use of AI-generated content in political advertising,”95 the proposal
would do the opposite.
90 See New York Times, 376 U.S. at 279–80.
91 See e.g. NPRM, Rosenworcel Statement 35; id. ¶ 8.
92 NPRM, Carr Dissent 41.
93 Id.
94 Id.
95 NPRM ¶ 2.
20
By placing disclosure rules on only one distribution channel, the FCC would create more
consumer confusion than clarity. Radio and television broadcasting are only two of the numerous
channels used to distribute political ads, and the avenues of distribution for advertising continue
to grow. In addition to broadcast, political ads are shared on social media, individual websites,
digital platforms, and in more traditional ways such as in newspapers and direct mail. To deploy
an advertising strategy effectively and efficiently, the same political ad is usually shared across
multiple platforms. In fact, the exact same ad is usually shared on a television broadcast and across
social-media platforms, streaming services, and other websites. Similarly, an ad aired on the radio
is used on podcasts. Thus, identical ads would be presented to voters both with and without the
disclosure. Yet, because the FCC will have required a disclosure in some instances, voters are
likely to believe (incorrectly) that ads without the disclosure are not digitally altered. As a result,
the proposed disclosure requirement would both confuse voters and undermine the agency’s
alleged transparency goal.96
Additionally, the breadth of the proposed definition of “AI-generated content” would lead
to confusing and misleading disclosures. As discussed above, “AI-generated content” is defined
incredibly broadly and would encompass almost any type of digital media. As Commissioner Carr
notes, “[i]t would be difficult, in this day and age, to imagine an advertisement (political or not)
that does not use a ‘computational technology’ to ‘depict’ an ‘event, circumstance, or situation.’”97
As a result, the AI-Disclosure Proposal would result in disclosures on ads that may not use
generative AI and only some digital element instead. Overuse of the “AI” disclosure would dilute
96 As explained, “transparency” is not a sufficient justification. See nn.31–35 and surrounding
text, supra.
97 NPRM, Carr Dissent 41.
21
its value, and consumers often begin ignoring disclosures when they are overapplied. This
outcome defeats the Commission’s goal of informing the electorate of whether a political ad uses
AI. For this reason too, the FCC’s proposal, rather than creating greater transparency, would create
more voter confusion.
D. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Stifle the Important Benefits that AI
Promises for Both Political Advertisers and Voters.
The NPRM correctly identifies that AI can provide substantial benefits to political ads.98
Political candidates, campaigns, and public officials—across both major parties—are choosing to
use AI for a variety of unobjectionable reasons. Some have used AI to make their advertisements
and positions stand out. For example, a California congressional candidate utilized AI in his
political advertisement to provide illustrations of his background and experience. A major political
party committee debuted an ad last year that provided an AI-generated look into the country’s
possible future. Others have utilized AI to reach a broader range of constituencies. For example,
New York City’s mayor used AI to translate announcements into a different language. AI can also
be used to write scripts for an ad and to streamline video editing by, as an example, blurring all
corporate logos in an ad or changing a clip from color to black and white.
AI can be used across the political ecosystem for a wide range of other beneficial reasons,
as well. For example, AI can generate more efficient and effective communications, which can
help a small campaign budget go further.99 AI can be used “to optimize ad placements” and deliver
“personalized messages” to voters on issues that are important to them.100 The FCC should
98 See id. ¶ 9.
99 See Neil Sahota, The AI Factor In Political Campaigns: Revolutionizing Modern Politics,
Forbes (Jan. 12, 2024), https://tinyurl.com/4ry9urcx.
100 See id.
22
highlight and support these benefits of AI in the election space. Unfortunately, as drafted, the AI-
Disclosure Proposal would instead stifle these beneficial uses by mandating a disclosure that
(incorrectly) implies that any ad with AI-generated content is deceptive or otherwise warrants
scrutiny.
E. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Result in Significant Operational Issues.
1. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Allow Partisan Interests To Weaponize
the FCC’s Rule Against Political Opponents.
The NPRM questions “the appropriate actions for stations to take in cases where a station
is informed by a credible third party that a political ad contains AI-generated content.”101 As
explained by Commissioner Carr in his dissent, “these ‘credible third parties,’ whoever they are,
will not be disinterested observers without skin in the game.”102 Indeed, many political ads display
digital depictions of a candidate’s opposition. Thus, the proposal would place the FCC in the
middle of political battles between opponents. Politically-motivated opponents will be able to
dispute ads as a way to throw roadblocks into the campaign of their opposition. The proposal
would thus create a mechanism for political adversaries to “chill” their “opponents’ speech,”
rendering the FCC a pawn in the political arena.103
2. The FCC Underestimates the Operational Costs of the Proposed Inquiry
Requirement.
As part of the AI-Disclosure Proposal, the NPRM proposes “to require that all broadcast
stations that air political ads inquire whether political ads scheduled to be aired on their stations
101 NPRM ¶ 17.
102 NPRM, Carr Dissent 40.
103 See id.
23
contain any AI-generated content.”104 The NPRM tentatively concludes that this proposal would
only require broadcasters to “make a simple inquiry” that the Commission does not believe will
“impose a significant burden.”105 In drawing this tentative conclusion, the NPRM fundamentally
misunderstands and underestimates the complexity of the process of buying and selling an ad,
which is far from simple and involves numerous steps and players.
Before the ad-buying process even begins, the candidate or entity running the ad will create
an ad and advertising campaign to carry a specific message to specific voters. The creation of the
ad requires a production team to shoot the necessary footage and then edit the ad into the final
form for distribution. The production team may include in-house team members, but generally
consists of third-party contractors. Next, a team of individuals provides market research, outlining
the target audience for the ads and determining what television and radio stations and time slots
include the most target-audience members. The ad buy itself is usually done by a media buyer
whose job is specifically focused on identifying the political ad campaign’s goals, target audience,
and budget. The buyer also typically handles the negotiations with networks over the time slots
for airing the ad—though a campaign may also utilize a third party who specializes in the
negotiation process. None of these individuals is necessarily involved in the development and
production of the political ad itself, and these individuals would not be aware of whether the ad
contains relevant elements that might be subject to disclosure under the proposal.
Given the complexity of this process, broadcasters would typically not be able to merely
ask a “simple” question to get the information needed to comply with the proposed disclosure
mandate. The FCC thus underestimates the costs to the regulated entities who will need to dedicate
104 NPRM ¶ 15.
105 Id. ¶ 36.
24
additional resources to identify whether an ad uses AI-generated content, especially given the
remarkable breath of that term in the proposal.
3. The AI-Disclosure Proposal Would Result in Practical Difficulties for
Political Advertisers.
The FCC fails to acknowledge or account for other serious operational impacts the AI-
Disclosure Proposal would have on the political advertising ecosystem. For example, the
proposal—if adopted—would (i) significantly slow down the ad-buying process; (ii) create
uncertainty in the ad-creation and production process, particularly when using footage not filmed
by the advertiser (e.g., licensed stock footage, other short clips consistent with the Fair Use
Doctrine); (iii) impede political advertisers from placing and airing ads to respond to current events
or opponents, which is a common and important practice in the fast-moving political environment;
and (iv) meaningfully cut into the advertisement time. These impacts would be felt broadly, as the
AI-Disclosure Proposal would apply to both candidate and issue ads, and would apply to political
ads at both the federal and state level. While the impacts are serious throughout the ecosystem,
they may be particularly acute for small campaigns and organizations that are not well-funded.
Further, the timing of the proposal is already creating operational obstacles. Comments on
this proposal are due a mere 47 days before the election. Entities that engage in political
advertising and who will feel direct impacts from this proposed regulation are having to divert
critical resources to engage with the FCC, in the midst of the final days the campaign season.
IV. CONCLUSION
For all these reasons, the Commission should abandon the AI-Disclosure Proposal.
