become increasingly common in other countries’ elections—including in Argentina,
where a leading presidential candidate’s campaign circulated a deepfake of his opponent
endorsing the sale of human organs;9 India, where voters have been “bombarded” with
8F
deepfakes of living candidates and deceased politicians;10 the United Kingdom, where
9F
deepfakes circulated of the opposition leader at the time supposedly berating and hurling
obscenities at his staff;11 and Slovakia, where an infamous last-minute audio deepfake of
10F
one of the leading candidates for prime minister supposedly conspiring to commit
election fraud and raise the price of alcohol may have helped sway a close national
election.12
11F
Deepfakes are not limited to spurious depictions related directly to candidates.
Increasingly they are also used in political communications to depict fictitious events that
evoke hot button issues. For instance, one ad disseminated early in the presidential
campaign depicted fake scenes of urban chaos and migrants streaming across the
southern border.13 Another video that was widely-circulated online, and appears to have
12F
originated from Russia, purports to show a U.S. State Department official claiming a
Russian city is a legitimate target for Ukrainian strikes using U.S. weapons.14
13F
As Election Day approaches, we are especially concerned about disinformation related to
the electoral process. For the last four years, the election denial movement has
relentlessly pushed a false narrative undermining the legitimacy of the 2020 presidential
election and encouraging baseless claims of widespread election fraud. Among other
