2222,10919624022815,2024-09-19T22:45:47.995Z,American Civil Liberties Union,,,"September 19, 2024
Federal Communications Commission
Secretary Marlene H. Dortch
45 L Street NE
Washington, DC 20554
Submitted electronically via https://www.fcc.gov/ecfs/
Re: Comment In the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-
Generated Content in Political Advertisements; MB Docket No. 24-211
Dear Secretary Dortch,
The American Civil Liberties Union (“ACLU”) respectfully submits these comments in
response to the above-referenced Notice of Proposed Rulemaking published by the Federal
Communication Commission (“FCC” or “Commission”) that would require television and radio
broadcasters to disclose when political advertisements use artificial intelligence.
The FCC has not shown the proposed regulation is appropriately tailored to withstand First
Amendment scrutiny. The FCC’s proposed definition of AI-generated content sweeps far more
broadly than deliberately deceptive or otherwise harmfully fraudulent content—including where
AI tools merely provide aesthetic enhancement or improve accessibility of content—undermining
the effectiveness of any potential disclaimer. Indeed, imposing a disclaimer requirement under
these circumstances may give an appearance of illegitimacy to advertisements that use generative
AI for nondeceptive purposes, while bolstering the perceived accuracy of advertisements that are
in fact deceptive but that do not use generative AI. In crafting regulations to address the bona fide
harms of deliberately misleading AI-generated political advertisements, the Commission must
ensure any rule ultimately comports with the First Amendment and is appropriately tailored to an
overriding governmental interest.
Moreover, imposing a regulatory burden on broadcasters, cable operators, and other
licensees in the form of investigative and disclosure requirements may unconstitutionally burden
the speech of third parties and the public’s interest in robust political debate, as well as the First
Amendment rights of the licensees themselves. Faced with investigative and disclosure
requirements that are too stringent or burdensome, licensees may pass resulting costs onto speakers
or forgo political advertising in favor of less costly alternatives, thereby diminishing the public’s
access to information about local candidates and issues.
I. The FCC’s Proposed Regulation is not Appropriately Tailored to its Cited Interests.
In light of its imprecise wording and overinclusive definition of AI-generated content, the
FCC has not shown that the proposed regulation, which burdens political speech, is appropriately
tailored to an overriding governmental interest.1 In its proposed rule, the Commission seeks to
address the “use of AI-generated content in political ads” that “provid[es] deceptive, misleading,
or fraudulent information to voters.”2 The Commission would apply its proposed requirement to
all AI-generated content and proposes to define AI-generated content as “an image, audio, or video
that has been generated using computational technology or other machine-based system that
depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation,
including, in particular, AI-generated voices that sound like human voices, and AI-generated actors
that appear to be human actors.”3 This proposed definition is imprecise and sweeps far too broadly,
encompassing a wide range of content that is not deceptive, misleading, or fraudulent.
The FCC’s proposed definition of AI-generated content would subject to its proposed rule
a broad range of advertisements that do not involve deceptive deepfakes. Increasingly, engineers
have incorporated AI-driven software into basic, commonly used features like automatic image-
and video-enhancement.4 AI-generation tools may improve accessibility, enabling scalable and
real-time voice-to-text generation5 and sign language translation6. Over-labeling AI-generated
content beyond advertisements that involve deceptive deepfakes risks rendering any disclosure
requirement meaningless because it clouds the legitimacy of substantially accurate content.7 At
the same time, the absence of a mandated disclaimer on political advertisements that do not use
generative AI may be deceptively invoked as proof of accuracy, even if the advertisement is
substantially misleading in other respects.
II. Government-Imposed Investigative and Disclaimer Requirements on Broadcasters
may Violate the First Amendment Because They Burden the Speech of Third
Parties.
In Citizens United, the Supreme Court noted that, applied directly to campaign speakers,
“[d]isclaimer and disclosure requirements [that] burden the ability to speak” without acting as a
prior restraint on speech are permissible where they meet “exacting scrutiny” under the First
Amendment.8 However, applied to platforms that publish or host the speech of others, such as
broadcasters, investigation and disclosure requirements like the ones proposed here raise distinct
First Amendment concerns.
1 Citizens United, 558 U.S. 310, 340 (2010).
2 Notice of Proposed Rulemaking in the Matter of Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated
Content in Political Advertisements, MB Docket No. 24-211 at ¶ 10 (NPRM)
3 NPRM at ¶ 12.
4 Steve Dent, “Apple’s new iPhones use AI ‘Portrait Lighting’ to improve shots,” Engadget, September 12, 2017
https://www.engadget.com/2017-09-12-apple-iphone8-camera-portrait-lighting.html
5 Christopher Groux, “Samsung Announces New Audio Subtitles Feature at CES 2024,” USA Today, January 8, 2024
https://reviewed.usatoday.com/accessibility/features/samsung-audio-subtitles-ces-01-08-2024
6 “Google sign language AI turns hand gestures into speech,” BBC News, August 20, 2019
https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-49410945
7 Claire Leibowicz, “Why watermarking AI-generated content won’t guarantee trust online,” MIT Technology
Review, August 9, 2023 https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/08/09/1077516/watermarking-ai-trust-online/
8 Citizens United v. Federal Election Com’n, 558 U.S. 310, 340 (2010).
The Supreme Court has rejected the notion that media platforms have a duty to investigate
advertisements they place about public officials or public figures.9 And the Fourth Circuit has
further observed that unlike direct regulations, disclosure obligations on political advertisements
hosted by “neutral-third party platforms” chill protected speech because they make political
advertisements more costly for platforms to host, relative to other competing types of speech,
creating an incentive for platforms to drop certain political advertisements altogether.10
In Washington Post v. McManus, the Fourth Circuit considered a First Amendment
challenge to disclaimer and recordkeeping requirements that a Maryland statute placed on
publishers who chose to host paid political advertisements.11 Although the disclaimer requirement
challenged in McManus “mandate[d] little more than the disclosure of a line or two of factual
information,” the Fourth Circuit determined that the regulatory burden imposed by this
investigation and disclosure requirement was constitutionally problematic.12 As the court
observed, the main problem with even minor regulatory requirements placed on platforms and
aimed specifically at one type of advertisement, especially political advertisements, is that those
requirements make a single category of advertisement more costly relative to others.13 This cost
disparity encourages platforms to carry lesser-regulated types of advertisement, ultimately
allowing more profitable alternatives to “crowd out” the regulated category of speech – effectively
silencing it.14
Such disclosure and disclaimer regulations selectively burden platforms hosting political
advertisements and is likely to diminish the market for this type of speech altogether, thus limiting
political debate and the public’s access to electoral information, particularly about candidates and
political issues that already receive lesser press attention. Artificial intelligence detection is a
costly, logistically challenging moving target.15 To the extent broadcasters bear the burdens of
investigation and disclosure required by the proposed rule, those burdens are more readily borne
by better-resourced, centralized broadcasters whose advertisement space is less accessible to state
and local candidates and backers of state and local issues. And insofar as broadcasters pass any
regulatory burden onto advertisement purchasers, well-resourced candidates and issue-backers are
better able to bear those costs. In short, the burdens imposed by the proposed regulation are likely
to be felt most keenly by smaller licensees and cash-strapped candidates and causes, raising serious
equity concerns.
We appreciate the Federal Communications Commission’s attention to our comments. If
you have any questions about these comments, please contact us at jleventoff@aclu.org.
