COMMENTS OF GRAY LOCAL MEDIA, INC.
Robert Folliard
Senior Vice President
Gray Local Media, Inc.
September 19, 2024
Executive Summary
As one of the nation’s leading local broadcast television affiliate groups, Gray Local
Media, Inc. (“Gray”) shares the FCC’s (“FCC” or “Commission”) goal of fostering an informed
electorate. Gray’s commitment to providing accurate information to viewers that makes a
difference in the communities Gray serves is beyond repute. In 2024 alone, Gray has received 8
National Edward R. Murrow awards for excellence in journalism, 78 regional Edward R.
Murrow awards for excellence in journalism, 3 awards from the Investigative Reporters and
Editors (“IRE”) for outstanding watchdog journalism, 2 Service to America Awards for
outstanding community service, 2 duPont-Columbia Awards for outstanding reporting in the
public interest, and numerous other state and regional awards.
The issue of potentially deceptive or misleading political advertisements is nothing new.
For decades, campaigns and other political groups have accused their opponents and other
entities of misconstruing statements, taking speeches out of context, using stock footage to create
false impressions, and otherwise misleading voters in political advertisements. Gray and other
local broadcasters are often thrust into the middle of these disputes as the recipients of takedown
notices and, increasingly, the targets of litigation. While artificial intelligence (“AI”) provides
political advertisers with another tool to use in their production process, it does not change the
overall nature of or approach to political advertising.
While Gray understands the Commission’s overall goal in this proceeding of addressing
the use of false, misleading, or deceptive material in political advertisements, the FCC is poorly
suited to address the content of political ads, and the approach proposed in the Notice of
Proposed Rulemaking (“NPRM”), therefore, is too narrow in one regard and too broad in another
such that it almost certainly will prove counterproductive. For a disclosure-based regime to
2
work, the disclosures must be clear, and consumers must understand their application. The
standardized disclosures proposed in the NPRM fail in both regards.
First, the FCC’s approach is overly broad in that it would extend beyond what is
traditionally considered AI to include any “image, audio, or video that has been generated using
computational technology.” This would encompass technologies that are used in the production
of many, if not most, broadcast advertisements today to enhance production quality and not for
deception or other nefarious purposes. As a result, the proposed rules would be overinclusive.
And because the disclaimers would be standardized, they would provide no assistance to viewers
in identifying how AI-generated content was used in the ad or whether or not it was deceptive.
Next, the proposed rules would be underinclusive because they are limited to
advertisements appearing on broadcast and other select platforms. They would not extend to the
same advertisement appearing on some of the most popular platforms for political
communications today, such as social media services, streaming video services, and virtual
multichannel video programming distributors. Therefore, the same advertisement could include
a statement that it includes AI-generated content when it appears on broadcast television, but no
disclaimer on TikTok, YouTube, Facebook, or Hulu. The result of the Commission’s approach
would be to create more confusion for viewers about what ads contain AI-generated content and
what that AI-generated content entails.
Meanwhile, the FCC’s proposal would be extremely burdensome for broadcasters to
implement. Broadcasters would need to adopt procedures to screen for ads that require
disclosures, to add the disclosures where needed, and to modify traffic logs to account for
changing ad lengths. Moreover, many advertisers will try to shift the burden to local
broadcasters to allocate time for the disclosures rather than taking that time from their ads. As a
3
result, Gray and other local broadcasters will need to displace paid advertisements or other
programming (including local news) to accommodate the mandatory disclosures—at a
significant cost to each station.
Beyond the concerns about the merits of the FCC’s approach, there are also serious
questions about the legality of the proposed disclosure regime. The Commission has not
identified any statutory authority for mandating disclosures for a subset of advertisements
appearing on a subset of platforms. Moreover, the proposed disclosures—which unquestionably
would compel broadcasters and advertisers to replace their speech for that of the government—
cannot withstand First Amendment scrutiny.
For all of these reasons, the FCC should refrain from adopting the rules proposed in the
NPRM.
4
