COMMENTS OF GRAY LOCAL MEDIA, INC.
Gray Local Media, Inc. (“Gray”) hereby submits these comments in response to the
Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (“NPRM”) in the above-referenced proceeding regarding
proposed disclosure requirements for the use of Artificial Intelligence (“AI”) technologies in
political advertisements.1 As one of the nation’s leading providers of local, over-the-air
broadcast television, Gray takes seriously the threat of misinformation and shares the Federal
Communications Commission’s (“FCC” or “Commission”) concern about false or misleading
advertising that could harm Gray’s brand and the local communities it serves.
The rules proposed in the NPRM, however, would not advance the FCC’s interest in
“fostering an informed electorate, which in turn is vital to the effective operation of the
democratic process.”2 Rather, the proposed rules would place broadcasters like Gray, who take
great pride in their impartiality, in the untenable position of having to decipher what is and is not
AI. The proposed rules also would cause substantial harm to broadcasters who not only will
need to develop processes and redirect staff resources to comply with the disclosure
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements, MB Docket
No. 24-211, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 24-74 (rel. July 25, 2024).
2 NPRM ¶ 3.
6
requirements, but who would potentially be forced to use their own airtime to add the disclosures
at a significant cost both to stations and their viewers. Finally, the proposed disclosures will
harm viewers, first, by creating confusion about what part of an ad contains AI or what kind of
AI an ad contains and, second, by providing a false sense of security to U.S. voters when they
encounter ads on platforms that are not subject to the proposed rules.
Beyond the substantive flaws with the Commission’s proposal, it suffers two more
fundamental problems. First, the FCC lacks authority to regulate artificial intelligence in this
manner. It is telling that the NPRM does not cite any specific authority but instead relies on the
Commission’s general supplemental authority notwithstanding the Supreme Court’s recent
directive that agencies must “abide by the boundaries of [their] delegated authority.”3 Second,
the proposed rules would significantly burden political speech in violation of the First
Amendment.
For all of these reasons, the FCC should not adopt the rules proposed in the NPRM.
I. THE PROPOSED RULES WOULD IMPOSE UNDUE BURDENS ON
BROADCASTERS, WOULD NOT ACHIEVE THE COMMISSION’S GOALS,
AND IN MANY CASES WOULD BE COUNTERPRODUCTIVE.
A. The Proposed Definition of AI-Generated Content is Overly Broad and Will
Have Unintended Effects on Potential Beneficial Uses of AI-Generated
Content.
By encompassing all uses of AI, no matter how trivial or beneficial, the FCC’s proposed
definition of AI-generated content is overly broad and would prove counterproductive. As
proposed in the NPRM, the definition of “AI-generated content” would include “an image,
audio, or video that has been generated using computational technology or other machine-based
system that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or
3 Loper Bright Enters. v. Raimondo, 144 S. Ct. 2244, 2263 (2024) (cleaned up).
7
situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that sound like human voices, and AI-
generated actors that appear to be human actors.”4 This proposed definition goes well beyond
the Commission’s expressed concern about “deepfakes and other deceptive and misleading
information”5 (which is already illegal in many states),6 and would instead capture any uses of
AI no matter how trivial or even beneficial.
The phrase “generated using computational technology” is particularly broad and would
at least arguably include almost any audio or audiovisual spot that is produced using digital
technologies. Digital recording devices and video and audio editors routinely used in the
industry use “computational technology” to generate images, audio, and video. Even if the term
“generated using computational technology” could be narrowed, the proposed definition has the
potential to apply to beneficial uses of AI for which disclosures would be unnecessary at best and
distracting at worst. For instance, the presence of a generic disclaimer on an ad that uses AI to
“produce content in the candidate’s voice in multiple languages”7—a use the Commission has
recognized as potentially beneficial—would be confusing for a viewer who would not know
what part of the ad actually contains AI. The rule could apply to other innocuous uses of AI,
such as voice integration, detection of deepfakes, object recognition and imagery analysis, and
the use of AI to make interstitials more accessible. The excessive use of disclaimers that the rule
would require will not “foster[] an informed electorate. . .”8 but will instead merely congest
airtime with disclosures that provide no value to viewers at best and are confusing at worst.
4 NPRM ¶ 12.
5 Id. ¶ 1 (quotations omitted).
6 See S. 751, 86th Leg. (Tex. 2019); H.R. 1133, 123d Gen. Assemb., 2d Reg. Sess. (Ind. 2024).
7 NPRM ¶ 9.
8 Id. ¶ 1
8
A narrower definition of AI-generated content, meanwhile, risks creating an even more
egregious form of content-based speech regulation. Threading the needle to address potential
harms from deceptive uses of AI-generated content in a manner that is both targeted and easy for
consumers to understand is fraught with constitutional challenges on all sides—demonstrating
why the Commission should wait for specific direction from Congress before embarking on a
nearly impossible task. Additionally, as further discussed below, the Commission’s disclaimer
obligations take valuable and limited airtime away from advertisers and broadcasters- making the
widespread use of disclosures an expensive prospect. The Commission should significantly
narrow the scope of the proposed definition to specific AI uses where informing the electorate of
their use serves a public interest.
B. Imposing Disclosure Obligations Only on Advertisements That Air on
Certain Platforms Will Create Consumer Confusion
The Commission’s focus on only a subset of political advertisements will create a
disparate approach to disclosures that will further undermine whatever efficacy the disclosures
would otherwise have. In the NPRM, the Commission initially proposes to apply the inquiry and
disclosure requirement to “all radio and television broadcast stations that air political ads.”9
The FCC then proposes to extend the rules to “cable operators, Direct Broadcast Satellite
(“DBS”) providers, and Satellite Digital Audio Radio Service (“SDARS”) licensees engaged in
origination programming.”10 The FCC proposal would not, however, extend to Multichannel
Video Programming Distributor (“MVPD”) programming not controlled by a cable operator or a
DBS provider or to any content distributed online, by virtual MVPDs (“vMVPDs”), or on social
media networks. In fact, the NPRM does not include any consideration of the fact that the same
9 NPRM ¶ 13 (emphasis added).
10 Id. ¶ 22 (cleaned up).
9
political advertisements can and will appear on a variety of platforms, only some of which would
be subject to a disclosure requirement.
Having a different standard apply to online and on-air advertisements will send mixed
messages to consumers that will ultimately prove more harmful than having no disclosures at all.
Successful implementation of the disclosure requirements would result in viewers and listeners
understanding that they need to be extra diligent about messages in advertisements that contain
the disclosures. But those same viewers and listeners could then be lulled into a false sense of
security: assuming that political advertisements appearing on other platforms do not include AI-
generated content because those advertisements would not include disclaimers. Worse yet, a
disclosure requirement could result in a “path of least resistance” approach where political
advertisements containing AI-generated content gravitate toward platforms that do not require
disclosures, undermining the very transparency that the Commission is seeking to provide.
While the confusion from having different requirements for different platforms may be
unintended, is a foreseeable consequence of adopting a piecemeal approach to disclosures of AI-
generated content.11
Illustrating this point, the Commission’s proposal would create a disparity even among
distributors of linear video programming. While a political advertisement containing AI-
generated content would require disclosures on a local broadcast station, on Comcast-owned
MSNBC and Bravo, and on Charter Communications owned Spectrum SportsNet, the same
political advertisement would not require disclosures on Fox News Channel, Discovery, ESPN,
or even within system breaks on virtual MVPDs such as Hulu, YouTube TV, and Fubo that are
not currently regulated as MVPDs. This will further add to the inconsistency in messaging that
11 See Ohio v. EPA, No. 23A349, slip op. at 12 (U.S. June 27, 2024) (failing to address an important and obvious
problem when adopting a new regulation is arbitrary and capricious).
10
the public will receive and dilute any purported public interest benefit of the disclosure
obligation. All in all, because so many different platforms today are beyond the regulatory reach
of the FCC but at the same time are the home to substantial amounts of political speech, it is the
role of Congress to decide how best to address the role of artificial intelligence in political
speech.
C. Imposing Disclosure Obligations on Broadcast Stations Will Have Significant
Economic and Operational Costs.
The Commission significantly underestimates the economic impact that the proposed
rules will have on broadcasters. While there may be minimal cost to simply broadcast an
advertisement that is provided to a broadcaster with the required disclosures in place, that is only
part of the Commission’s proposal. The Commission proposes to require broadcast stations
provide an on-air announcement for all ads containing AI-generated content and places the
responsibility of inquiring whether the content is AI generated on the broadcaster. Broadcast
stations, therefore, will need to have staff available to implement the disclosures and field
concerns regarding conflicting reports of AI-included material, thus slowing the advertising
approval process and limiting the ability of campaigns to quickly change their messaging during
a campaign. Gray has already expended significant legal expense to draft a unique political
disclosure form and provide additional training for sales staff and news personnel in response to
state laws requiring AI disclaimers. The proposals in the NPRM would exacerbate this,
requiring Gray to thoroughly train over 1,000 sales employees to ensure compliance and redirect
resources from other departments (such as local news), all with the corresponding costs and loss
in productivity.
Additionally, although the FCC seems to assume the disclosures will come out of an
advertiser’s time (e.g., four seconds in a 30 second ad), that assumption is misplaced when there
11
is no incentive for the advertiser to include these disclosures. If the advertiser faces no
ramifications for failing to include the disclaimer, there is no reason to think they will bear the
additional production costs of creating a distribution-specific, unwanted disclaimer. To put a
finer point on it, it is more than likely broadcasters will bear the onus of not only producing the
disclosures, but allocating time from its own inventory to air them: (1) where the AI-generated
content appears in a candidate advertisement that is subject to the prohibition on censorship in
Section 315 of the Communications Act;12 and (2) where an advertiser prepares an advertisement
to air on multiple platforms and insists that the broadcaster provide any additional time for
disclosures (or risk losing the sale to a platform where no disclosures are required). Thus, if
implemented, the rules threaten to take a significant amount airtime from broadcasters and force
unnecessary and burdensome changes to current processes for logging advertisements.
Even if each break has only one ad that requires a station-produced disclaimer from its
own airtime, a station will have to drop a 30 second commercial spot from each break (three total
in each newscast, for instance) to create room for the FCC-required adjacent disclaimers. In a
market like Charlotte, NC, this will cost WBTV an estimated $2700 in a single half-hour alone,
assuming lowest unit rate spots are preempted for the disclaimers. If standard commercial ads
are removed instead, the loss could be triple that.
While broadcasters may have an opportunity to sell shorter spots to accommodate these
changes, politicians may be unable or unwilling to create shorter advertisements to fit the new
shorter, and limited time slots. These changes may have the unintended consequence of scaring
political advertisers off air and pushing them into other platforms with fewer restrictions. The
Commission must factor this unintended, yet foreseeable, consequence when considering the
12 47 U.S.C. § 315.
12
public interest benefit of the disclosure requirement.
Even assuming a broadcaster could adequately traffic shorter ads without these
consequences, calculating just the loss of a four-second disclosure before each political ad in the
2022 political window would have cost Gray’s Atlanta station WANF an estimated two million
dollars in revenue, revenue that is critical for Gray to serve its mission of informing its local
community.
As an alternative to sacrificing commercial inventory, stations may reduce station
controlled programming time, including local news, to lengthen the commercial blocks for the
required disclosures. It would not serve the public interest, however, to curtail news coverage to
air government-mandated content. First Amendment concerns aside, this wildly complicates the
news production process. News producers may find the length of their news segments varying
from block to block and day to day – with extraordinarily short notice. In non-station-produced
programming, meanwhile, the station would not have the “luxury” of shortening the
programming. Rather, the station would only be left with the option to preempt syndicated and
network programming to leave sufficient time for these imposed disclosure obligations, forcing
the station to breach its programming contracts.
Accommodating last minute changes to commercial and program logs to accommodate
added disclosures will also require significant operational changes. Advertising logs are
formatted for each Gray station 12-months in advance. For example, one station with thirty (30)
minutes of news creates a year-long format that contains three commercial breaks with sixteen
(16) total spots. While the formats are long-predetermined, specific political advertisements are
set just the day before to permit flexibility to political candidates who often change course on
messaging. Under the proposed rules, log deadlines would need to be shifted either to a later
13
time to meet the needs of political advertisers or to an earlier time for administrative efficiency
(at a cost of being unable to air certain political advertising) to permit the inclusion of an
additional 4 second slot before each political advertisement. This entails having to reopen the
standard format and creating a one-time-only format – expanding each individual break,
reapplying the copy, and then finalizing each log. This will take multiple hours per day, per
station and will prove especially difficult to implement in the weeks before an election, where in
some markets at least 90% of the advertising time is expected to be devoted to political ads.
While the Commission should be reluctant to adopt any proposals that would impose
such significant costs and inconvenience on broadcasters, it should be particularly cautious
where, as here, the countervailing benefits are speculative at best.
D. The Commission Should Not Make the Proposed Requirement Any More
Burdensome by Requiring Broadcasters to Follow Up After an Initial
Inquiry.
Should the Commission impose its burdensome disclosure requirement, it should do its
best to make rules that are easily adaptable by deeming any obligation to inquire satisfied
regardless of the response (or lack thereof) and by not requiring broadcasters to act in response to
a third-party claim that an advertisement contains AI-generated content. The Commission seeks
comment on whether “a station that makes a simple inquiry consistent with the Commission’s
rules be deemed to have satisfied its obligations even if there is no response to the inquiry.”13
Gray strongly encourages the Commission to deem any obligation to inquire satisfied regardless
of response to the inquiry. The FCC took a similar approach in its 2019 Order clarifying online
political file requirements for broadcast stations, finding that “[i]n cases where a licensee makes
13 NPRM ¶ 15.
14
further inquiry yet is not provided with additional information, the licensee will be deemed to
have discharged its duty by disclosing the information it has been given.”14
The Commission should not require broadcasters to act in response to a third-party claim
that an advertisement contains AI-generated content. This proposal, if adopted, would
needlessly place broadcasters in the middle of disputes over content they did not create and
whose authenticity they have no way to confirm. The FCC should not allow candidates to
weaponize its rules by creating additional potential liability for broadcasters. Rather, if the
Commission imposes any requirement on broadcasters to inquire about the use of AI-generated
content, it should be enough for a station to make only an initial inquiry of the advertiser.
II. THE COMMISSION SHOULD NOT REQUIRE BROADCASTERS TO INCLUDE
A NOTICE DISCLOSING USE OF AI GENERATED CONTENT IN THEIR
POLITICAL FILE.
A. Requiring Local Broadcasters to Include a Notice Disclosing Use of AI-
Generated Content in Political Ads in Their Political File Will Create an
Unnecessary Additional Filing Requirement.
The Commission should not require separate disclosures in the online public inspection
file. In the NPRM, the Commission proposes to “require all broadcast stations to include in their
online political files a notice disclosing the use of AI-generated content for each political ad that
contains such content.”15 It should not. The Commission’s goals of maintaining an informed
electorate are commendable and Gray understands the vital role that its programming plays in
fostering an informed electorate. However, adding another filing requirement for broadcasters
would be both unnecessary and burdensome.
14 Complaints Involving the Political Files of WNCN-TV, Inc., licensee of Station WNCN-TV, Charlotte, NC, et al,
Memorandum Opinion and Order, 34 FCC Rcd 10048 (12) (2019).
15 NPRM ¶ 18.
15
Any requirement for local broadcasters to include a notice disclosing the use of AI-
Generated content in political advertisements in their political file would be based on a flawed
assumption that listeners, viewers, and other interested parties will review a station’s political
file “to confirm which ads aired by a station contained AI-generated content.”16 The
Commission does not provide any support for its conclusory assumption that viewers or listeners
would check the political file, nor does it explain why a disclosure removed from the ad itself
would serve any benefit. Finally, the Commission can point to no specific statutory authorizing
this new burdensome disclosure obligation.
Rather than facilitating transparency or preventing negative use of artificial intelligence,
adding information to the public file will merely create additional clutter and make the public file
more difficult to navigate.
B. Imposing Obligations on Local Broadcasters for Political Ads in Network
Programming Would Be Unreasonable and Unnecessarily Burdensome.
The Commission should not impose an obligation on affiliated stations with regard to
network programming in the course of this proceeding. Advertisements that appear in network
programming are typically sold by the networks, and it is the networks, not local broadcasters,
that have a relationship with network advertisers. In most cases, Gray and other local
broadcasters have no insight into what advertisements will air during network programming, and
local broadcasters never have an opportunity to screen advertisements in advance. It would be
unreasonable, therefore, to impose obligations on local broadcasters regarding the content of
network advertisements, and it would be particularly unreasonable to require local broadcasters
to upload information to their political files about whether advertisements broadcast by the
network include AI-generated content.
16 Id.
16
The Commission’s proposal would go further than the existing rules for political
programming, which are ambiguous at best with regard to their applicability to network
programming. For example, Section 73.1943(a) of the FCC’s Rules requires licensees to make a
record of whether a request to purchase broadcast time was “accepted or rejected by the
licensee.”17 The rule does not include any reference to requests made to third parties providing
programming to the licensee, such as a network. Rather, in adopting the political file
requirement, the Commission recognized the limits on information available to the licensee.
Even if the FCC could shift the burden to local broadcasters for the use of AI-generated
content in political advertisements contained in network programming, that does not mean it
should do so. The Commission has recognized that networks can maintain their own public
files.18 This approach makes sense because it is the network that has a relationship with the
advertiser, and it is the network that can obtain any required information. Requiring networks to
disseminate this information to affiliates, which have no means to verify its accuracy, and who
must then individually upload such information to their individual public files, would place an
unnecessary burden on local broadcasters with no corresponding public interest benefit.
To the extent the Commission wants to revisit the obligations of broadcasters with regard
to network programming, that goes well beyond the subject matter of this proceeding. The FCC
should, if it so desires, thoughtfully approach the filing requirements for network advertisements
more holistically in a separate proceeding.
17 47 CFR § 73.1943 (b)(1) (emphasis added).
18 Id. § 73.1212 (e) (allowing networks to retain information “at the headquarters office of the network”).
17
III. THE FCC LACKS THE STATUTORY AUTHORITY NECESSARY TO
PROCEED WITH THE PROPOSED REGULATION.
A. The FCC Cannot Identify the Clear Statement That Would Be Necessary To
Impose Its Proposed Regulation.
The FCC must identify a clear grant of authority for its proposal for at least two reasons.
First, the Commission’s proposal raises a major question of “vast economic and political
significance” that requires a “clear statement” under the “major questions doctrine.”19 The
Commission’s proposed rules are a major question because they encompass issues of
misinformation and an informed electorate that were not delegated to the agency to resolve and
thus must be left to Congress. Absent clear congressional delegation, the Commission should
not place itself in the position of regulating broadcasts based on the content of their speech or
coopting broadcasters into ad hoc fact-checkers.
Second, and relatedly, the proposal would raise serious concerns under the First
Amendment, as explained in Section IV, infra. As a result, “the canon of constitutional
avoidance” counsels against the proposed construction because it would result in a
“constitutional collision” between the Communications Act and the First Amendment.20 To
overcome this hurdle, the agency must identify “clear statutory language” to support its
constitutionally dubious proposal.21
As further explained in Section III(B), infra, Congress did not delegate at all—let alone,
clearly—authority for the Commission to mandate disclosures for AI-generated content.
Accordingly, the Commission’s proposal extends beyond the boundaries of its authority under
19 W. Virginia v. EPA, 597 U.S. 697, 716 (2022) (citation omitted); see also In re: MCP No. 185, No. 24-7000, 2024
WL 3650468, at *3 (6th Cir. Aug. 1, 2024).
20 United States v. Hansen, 599 U.S. 762, 781 (2023).
21 FBI v. Fazaga, 595 U.S. 344, 355 (2022).
18
the Communications Act and should not be implemented. Instead, this issue should be left to
Congress, which is the only body equipped to pursue a consistent and comprehensive approach.
B. The Commission’s Authority Under Section 303(r) and Title III’s Public
Interest Standard Fail to Provide it Authority Under the Best Meaning of the
Statute.
The Commission cannot cite any clear or direct authority from Congress to support its
proposed rules. Instead, it cites its ancillary authority stretching the limits of the
Communications Act beyond what is legally acceptable. In the NPRM, the Commission asks
whether it “has the authority to adopt the proposed on-air disclosure and political file
requirements for AI-generated content in political ads.”22 The sole statutory authority that the
FCC cites, however, is usually a fallback position: its ancillary authority under section 303(r).23
That provision says the Commission can make “rules and regulations … as may be necessary to
carry out the provisions of” the Communications Act.24 The provision the agency purports to
“carry out” here is its “general standard” for licensees to act in “the public interest, convenience
or necessity.”25 But neither Section 303(r) nor Title III’s public-interest standard say anything
about artificial intelligence, deception, or political advertising. The Commission’s assertion of
authority is thus quite literally “the vague language of an ancillary provision” that the Supreme
Court has held does not satisfy a statutory clear-statement requirement. 26 As the D.C. Circuit
has explained multiple times, “[t]he FCC must act pursuant to delegated authority before any
22 NPRM ¶ 27.
23 Id.
2447 U.S.C. § 303(r).
25 NPRM ¶ 27 (citing 47 U.S.C. §§ 307(a), 309(a)); accord Comcast Corp. v. FCC, 600 F.3d 642, 644 (D.C. Cir.
2010) (explaining that FCC may invoke “‘ancillary’ authority only if it demonstrates that its action … is reasonably
ancillary to the effective performance of its statutorily mandated responsibilities”) (cleaned up).
26 W. Virginia, 597 U.S. at 724 (cleaned up).
19
‘public interest’ inquiry is made under Section 303(r).” 27 Section 303(r) is not a standalone
provision of the Communications Act giving the FCC blanket authority to act in the “public
interest.” The lack of a any statement in the Communications Act regarding AI content in
political advertisements is alone sufficient to reject the Commission’s reliance on Section 303(r).
But even if the Commission did not need to identify a clear statement—and, to be clear, it
does—it would still lack authority under the best reading of the Communications Act. As the
Supreme Court recently explained in Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo, the Commission
must identify a source of authority under the “single, best meaning” of the statute, with its
meaning “fixed at the time of [its] enactment.”28
The Commission’s ancillary authority under Section 303(r) and Title III’s public-interest
standard fail to provide it authority under the best meaning of the statute. Although these
provisions “authorize[ ]” the Commission “to exercise a degree of discretion,” the agency must
nevertheless abide by “the boundaries of [that] delegated authority.”29 Here, those boundaries
stem from Congress’s understanding of “public interest.” The Commission’s “public interest”
standard may not “be interpreted as setting up a standard so indefinite as to confer an unlimited
power.”30 Rather, it must be “interpreted by its context.”31 In context, both the Commission and
the Supreme Court have long understood “the agency’s traditional public interest goals” to be
“promoting competition, localism, and viewpoint diversity.”32 But “the Act does not essay to
27 Motion Picture Ass’n of Am., Inc. v FCC, 309 F.3d 796, 806 (D.C. Cir. 2002) (emphasis in original). See also
Comcast Corp., 600 F.3d at 661 (vacating the Commission’s order “[b]ecause the Commission has failed to tie its
assertion of ancillary authority over Comcast’s Internet service to any ‘statutorily mandated responsibility’”); Am.
Library Ass’n v FCC, 406 F.3d 689, 692 (D.C. Cir. 2005) (“[T]he disputed broadcast flag regulations rest on no
apparent statutory foundation and, thus, appear to be ancillary to nothing.”).
28 Loper Bright Enters., 144 S. Ct. at 2266 (cleaned up).
29 Id. at 2263.
30 Nat’l Broad. Co. v. United States, 319 U.S. 190, 216 (1943).
31 Id.
32 FCC v. Prometheus Radio Project, 592 U.S. 414, 419 (2021).
20
regulate the business of the licensee,” and the “Commission is given no supervisory control of
the programs, of business management or of policy.”33
Here, the Commission’s proposal flunks every one of these limits. Its conception of
“public interest” would give the agency an unlimited power that is divorced from statutory
context. It has nothing to do with the agency’s traditional public interest goals. And it would
exercise supervisory control of the programs, business management, and policy of broadcasters.
Thus, the AI-disclosure proposal is not within the Commission’s public-interest authority.
Other textual clues confirm that the Act’s generic public-interest standard does not give
the Commission authority to mandate disclosures in political broadcasts. First, Congress speaks
clearly when it wants to give the Commission authority over political programming. As the
Commission acknowledges in its NPRM, “[t]he relevant statutory political programming
provisions applicable to broadcasters are set forth in sections 315 and 312(a)(7) of the
Communications Act of 1934, as amended (Act).”34 These provisions specify that licensees
must afford all candidates equal opportunities, not censor candidates, and provide reasonable
access to purchase air time. Because Congress gave the Commission specific, targeted authority
over political programming (including disclosures), its failure to give the Commission authority
to address artificial intelligence or viewer transparency in political programming confirms that
the omission was intentional.35
Next, Congress speaks clearly when it wants to regulate broadcast content – including
deceptive content. Section 303 allows the Commission to “suspend the license of any operator”
that “has transmitted … communications containing profane or obscene words, language, or
33 FCC v. Sanders Bros. Radio Station, 309 U.S. 470, 475 (1940).
34 NPRM ¶ 4.
35 See Jennings v. Rodriguez, 583 U.S. 281, 300 (2018) (“expressio unius est exclusio alterius”).
21
meaning, or has knowingly transmitted … false or deceptive signals or communications.”36 Title
18 penalizes one who “utters any obscene, indecent, or profane language by means of radio
communication.”37 These narrow, limited provisions governing broadcast content show that
Congress did not intend to give the FCC broad, general authority to regulate broadcast content.38
Provisions that limit the FCC’s authority over broadcast content - and political broadcasts
specifically - confirm these limits. Section 326 provides that the Commission lacks “the power
of censorship” over communications and that the Commission may not “interfere with the right
of free speech by means of radio communication.”39 Section 315 prohibits licensees from
“censor[ing]” broadcasts by “a legally qualified candidate for any public office.”40 These
provisions reinforce that Congress did not intend for the Commission to exercise the kind of
plenary control over election broadcasts that is contemplated by the NPRM.
Moreover, the Commission’s reliance on Title III’s public-interest standard would render
Congress’s targeted provisions covering political programming and much of Title III
meaningless.41 After all, if the Commission’s theory of authority authorizes its AI disclosures,
there is no reason it would not also authorize everything from sponsorship ID rules42 and
political recordkeeping requirements43 to classification of applications44 or revocation of
licenses45 or virtually any other substantive policy in Title III that could further a conceivable
