conception of the “public interest.” That “kind of superfluity, in and of itself, refutes [the
NPRM]’s reading.”46
Similarly, an interpretation that gave the Commission unbounded discretion to define the
“public interest” and regulate in further of it would raise grave constitutional doubts under the
nondelegation doctrine.47 “Congress may grant regulatory power to another entity only if it
provides an “intelligible principle” by which the recipient of the power can exercise it.”48 Here,
the Commission’s interpretation of “public interest” disregards the traditional public interest
factors of “promoting competition, localism, and viewpoint diversity.” By ignoring these
factors, the Commission interprets its authority beyond any “intelligible principle” that Congress
has provided the agency in conflict with the non-delegation doctrine.
IV. THE PROPOSED MANDATORY DISCLOSURE REQUIREMENTS WOULD
VIOLATE BROADCASTERS’ FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHTS.
In addition to all of the foregoing arguments, the Commission also should reject the
proposed mandatory disclosure requirement because the proposal raises serious First
Amendment concerns due to its significant burden on political speech.
A. The Proposed Mandatory Disclosure Requirements Would Burden Political
Speech.
The Commission’s proposed mandatory disclosures would be contrary to the First
Amendment by significantly burdening political speech in two ways. First, by mandating a
disclosure that speakers would not otherwise include, the FCC would “compel a person to speak
[a government] message when he would prefer to remain silent,” and it would “force an
46 Pulsifer, 601 U.S. at 143.
47 See, e.g., Jarkesy v. SEC, 34 F.4th 446, 459–63 (5th Cir. 2022), aff’d, SEC v. Jarkesy, 144 S. Ct. 2117 (2024);
Gundy v. United States, 588 U.S. 128, 173-79 (2019) (Gorsuch, J., Roberts, C.J., and Thomas, J., dissenting); cf.
Consumers’ Rsch. v. FCC, No. 22-60008, 2024 WL 3517592, at *31 (5th Cir. July 24, 2024).
48 Jarkesy, 34 F.4th at 459–63(quoting J.W. Hampton, Jr., & Co. v. United States, 276 U.S. 394, 409 (1928)).
