individual to include other ideas with his own speech that he would prefer not to include.”49
Second, the disclosure mandate prohibits speech because it would displace other speech by
requiring “four percent”50 of an ad’s visual space and “four seconds” of an ad’s runtime.
Because an ad has only “finite” space—typically running for 30 seconds—being “forced to
publish” the FCC’s disclosure will require the speaker to, “as a practical matter, omit something
else.”51
These agency-imposed burdens are particularly onerous since political ads are already
subject to statutory disclosure requirements that take up a significant portion of their runtime.52
Thus, an additional four-second audio disclosure and a four-percent space disclosure cannot be
assessed in a vacuum. They are cumulative of existing requirements and thus eat into the limited
ad space that remains after application of those existing requirements. Additionally, the
Commission’s proposed third-party-reporting scheme encroaches on the “breathing space”
necessary for “First Amendment freedoms” to “survive.”53 Specifically, the Commission
contemplates that stations may have to act in response to complaints by “a credible third
party.”54 As Commissioner Carr notes, this “proposal will invite highly motivated politicos to
file a flood of complaints alleging ‘AI-generated content,’ not for the sake of the truth, but as a
cudgel to chill opponents’ speech.”55 Broadcasters should not be forced to abandon their
impartiality with a government directive to arbitrate or opine upon who is, and who is not, a
