credible third party.56
B. The Proposed Mandatory Disclosure Requirements Would Be Subject To
Strict Scrutiny.
The Commission’s proposal would, if adopted, be subject to strict scrutiny for two
reasons: (1) it is content based on its face because it applies only to one type of speech: “political
advertising”57 and (2) by compelling “speech that a speaker would not otherwise make,” the
proposal would “necessarily alter[ ] the content of the speech.”58 Under strict scrutiny, laws that
regulate speech based on its content or viewpoint “are presumptively unconstitutional and may
be justified only if the government proves that they are narrowly tailored to serve compelling
state interests.”59 At minimum, the compelled disclosure is subject to “exacting scrutiny,” which
requires that a speech regulation be “narrowly tailored” to further a “sufficiently important
interest.”60
The Commission is incorrect that its restriction may be entitled to a lower standard of
review under the Supreme Court’s “scarcity rationale”—for three reasons.61 First, the scarcity
rationale is no longer good law. The FCC itself repudiated the scarcity doctrine over 35 years
ago in Syracuse Peace Council.62 Moreover, as Justice Thomas has explained, the cases
