announcing that rationale “were unconvincing when they were issued, and the passage of time
has only increased doubt regarding their continued validity.”63 Second, even if it were still good
law, it would not apply in this context. The Supreme Court has explained the scarcity rationale
as follows: “given spectrum scarcity, those who are granted a license to broadcast must serve in a
sense as fiduciaries for the public by presenting those views and voices which are representative
of their community and which would otherwise, by necessity, be barred from the airwaves.”64
But here, the Commission’s goal is not to ensure “representative” views. Rather it is to offer
“transparency” and prevent “deception.”65 Whatever the merits of those interests, they have
nothing to do with the scarcity of broadcast spectrum; the Commission seeks to address a
situation present on all media.66 Third, as previously discussed, Section 326 provides that the
Commission lacks “the power of censorship” over communications and that the Commission
may not “interfere with the right of free speech by means of radio communication.”67 Thus,
Section 326’s prohibition on interference with the right to free speech acts as an independent
statutory bar to FCC speech regulation that forecloses speech regulation under the scarcity
rationale.
