C. The Proposed Mandatory Disclosure Requirements Would Fail To Satisfy
Any Standard.
The Commission’s proposal would not satisfy any form of First Amendment scrutiny
because it lacks any legitimate government interest and is not properly tailored.
First, the Commission lacks any government interest—let alone an important one. Here,
the Commission describes its interest as “providing greater transparency regarding the use of AI-
generated content in political advertising.”69 But transparency alone cannot justify a
disclosure—especially when government mandated regulation is “more extensive than necessary
to serve the State’s purported goal.”70 Courts have repeatedly held that it is “not enough for the
Government to say simply that it has a substantial interest in giving consumers information.”71
Relatedly, the Commission also claims its proposal will “ensur[e] that the public can assess the
substance and credibility of the information they receive”72 and will “foster[ ] an informed
electorate.”73 However, the Government does not have an interest in “better balanc[ing] the
speech market.”74
Next, the Commission’s proposal is not sufficiently tailored because the Commission has
not identified a problem in need of solving and, even if the Commission had identified a
