problem, the proposed solution is not necessary to solve the problem. Although the Government
claims AI-generated content “creates a potential for providing deceptive, misleading, or
fraudulent information to voters,”75 that is not enough. The Commission “must provide evidence
establishing ‘that the harms it recites are real.’”76 The FCC, however, has not identified a single
example of an AI-generated broadcast-media political ad that has deceived, mislead, or
defrauded voters.77 Even if there was evidence of misleading AI-generated media appearing on
broadcast stations, “false speech receives some constitutional protection.”78 Because “some
false statements are inevitable if there is to be an open and vigorous expression of views,” the
usual “remedy for speech that is false is speech that is true.”79
Moreover, the FCC’s proposed “curtailment of free speech” is not “narrowly tailored” to
further a “sufficiently important interest” because it is not “actually necessary to the solution.”80
The Commission’s proposed solution is vastly overinclusive. Despite its asserted interest in
preventing deception, the NPRM does not limit the disclosure to AI-generated content that may
mislead. It instead requires disclosures in all political ads, regardless of propensity to deceive.81
Yet, as the Commission notes, and as previously discussed, there are beneficial, non-misleading
uses of AI-generated content, such as creating ads “in multiple languages.”82 The inelegance of
