the Commission’s approach is magnified by its proposed expansive definition of “AI-generated
content.”83 For example, “an image … that has been generated using computational technology
or other machine-based system that depicts an individual’s appearance” could well include a
photoshop touchup of a candidate’s face.84 The Commission offers no reason to sweep in all of
these ads instead of limiting its proposal to deceptive uses of AI-generated content. Indeed, the
Government commonly limits restrictions to only deceptive speech.
In addition to being overinclusive, the Commission’s proposed rules are incredibly
underinclusive as well. As explained in Section I.B of these Comments, the proposed rules only
apply to political advertisements with AI-generated content on broadcast stations and a limited
number of cable networks. Left unregulated are streaming platforms, social media platforms,
connected TV platforms, vMVPDs, and cable networks that are not controlled by an MVPD.
According to BIA Advisory Services’ most recent estimates, broadcast radio and television will
garner only 46% of total political ad spending in 2024, meaning that more than half of the
political dollars spent in the 2024 election cycle would be shielded from the FCC’s rules.85 All
in all, the proposal is not narrowly tailored because there “is a dramatic mismatch … between the
interest that the [FCC] seeks to promote and the disclosure regime” it has proposed.86
