COMMENTS OF NCTA – THE INTERNET & TELEVISION ASSOCIATION
NCTA – The Internet & Television Association (“NCTA”) submits these comments in
response to the Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (“Notice”) in the above-captioned proceeding.1
INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY
NCTA appreciates the Federal Communications Commission’s (“Commission” or “FCC”)
concern that “manipulated media” could be used to “mislead the public about candidates’
assertions or positions on particular issues or about whether certain events actually happened.”2
However, Congress has made the Federal Election Commission (“FEC”) the “cop-on-the-beat” in
this area, and the FEC has been considering measures to address deepfakes in political ads. In
contrast, the Commission’s authority in this area is circumscribed and does not support the
proposals in the Notice. Moreover, the proposal raises First Amendment and other legal issues, as
well as significant implementation concerns. For these and other reasons, the Commission should
not move forward with the proposed rules.
First, the Commission lacks statutory authority to adopt the proposed on-air disclosure and
political-file requirements with respect to both candidate and issue advertisements. To the extent
1
Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements,
Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, MB Docket No. 24-211, FCC 24-74 (rel. July 25, 2024) (“Notice”).
2
Notice ¶ 10.
1
Congress has delegated any authority to regulate in this area, it has given primary responsibility to
the FEC, which directly regulates the candidates and political committees that create political
advertising; in contrast, the delegations to the Commission with respect to political advertising
disclosures are expressly limited. The candidates and committees regulated by the FEC are the
proper entities to be charged with making any disclosures related to artificial intelligence (“AI”)
included in their advertisements. The best reading of the statutes referenced in the Notice provides
no support for applying the proposed requirements to cable operators. Particularly after the
Supreme Court’s recent decision in Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo,3 this lack of clear
statutory authority is fatal to the Commission’s ability to act.
Second, even if the Commission had authority to implement the proposed rules, they would
violate the First Amendment. The rules as proposed are content- and speaker-based restrictions
that would burden political speech and compel cable operators to carry the government’s message.
The proposed rules would trigger strict scrutiny, but would fail even under intermediate scrutiny
because they are not sufficiently tailored to advance the Commission’s asserted interest in
transparency: the rules are both overinclusive (as they apply to essentially every political
advertisement under the broad proposed definition of “AI-generated content” regardless of
whether the advertisement is actually misleading) and underinclusive (as they do not include the
vast category of online political advertising).
Finally, the proposed rules, if adopted, would be unworkable, unduly burdensome, and
potentially inconsistent with current law. The duty to inquire about AI-generated content would
impose significant burdens on cable operators—who often receive requests to air political
advertisements with little lead time—and would create potential liability for operators who rely on
3
144 S. Ct. 2244 (2024).
2
representations from advertisers that may later turn out to be false or inaccurate. The duty to add
on-air disclosures to advertisements containing AI-generated content also would require cable
operators to make technical modifications to advertisements that could conflict with existing
Commission rules and copyright law. And the overbroad definition of AI could require disclosures
of longstanding practices like video editing that do not result in deceptive images.
I. REQUIRING CABLE OPERATORS TO DISCLOSE AI-GENERATED CONTENT
IN POLITICAL ADVERTISEMENTS IS BEYOND THE COMMISSION’S
STATUTORY AUTHORITY.
The Commission lacks statutory authority to promulgate the proposed rules. To the extent
Congress has delegated any authority to regulate in this area, it has given primary responsibility to
the FEC, which directly regulates the candidates and political committees that create political
advertising; in contrast, the delegations to the Commission with respect to political advertising
disclosures are expressly limited. The Notice fails to identify any statutory provision that permits
the Commission to promulgate the proposed requirements.
A. The FEC Is the Appropriate Agency to Address AI Disclosures in Political
Advertising.
The FEC, not the FCC, is the principal agency charged with regulating disclosures in
political advertising. “Congress gave the Federal Election Commission—not the FCC—the
exclusive statutory authority to interpret, administer, and enforce [the Federal Election Campaign
Act (‘FECA’)],” and that authority “includes the authority to establish disclosures for political
communications on television and radio.”4 Crucially, the FEC has jurisdiction to impose certain
