disclosure requirements directly on candidates and political committees, which are the appropriate
entities to make such disclosures.5 Moreover, FECA already contains provisions addressing
efforts to deceive the public, including a prohibition against the fraudulent misrepresentation of
campaign authority.6 Seeking transparency with respect to AI-generated content in political and
electioneering communications therefore falls to the FEC.7
The FEC has recently focused on these issues.8 At its meeting on September 19, 2024, the
FEC voted to adopt an interpretive rule clarifying that the FECA’s existing prohibition against
fraudulent misrepresentation of campaign authority applies to the use of AI.9 The FEC’s
interpretive rule notes that for purposes of the FEC’s enforcement of the statute and its
implementing regulations, “it does not matter whether a regulated person uses any particular form
