2. Section 315 Does Not Support the Proposed Requirements.
The Commission sought “comment on whether the proposed on-air disclosure and political
file requirements are within the Commission’s authority under sections 315(d) and/or 315(e).”26
Although Section 315 applies to cable operators,27 it does not authorize either of the proposed
requirements. Section 315(d) simply authorizes the Commission to “prescribe appropriate rules
and regulations to carry out the provisions of [Section 315],”28 but no provision in Section 315
authorizes the on-air disclosure requirement. Likewise, Section 315(e) sets forth the political file
obligations of entities covered by Section 315 (“covered entities”), but nothing in that carefully-
crafted provision justifies requiring cable operators to include a notice in its online political file
regarding an advertisement’s use of AI-generated content.
On-Air Disclosure Requirement. The proposed on-air disclosure requirement would
mandate that a cable operator “inquire whether any political advertising scheduled to be aired on
its system contains any artificial intelligence-generated content,” and, if so, to “make an on-air
announcement, immediately preceding or during the airing of the advertising” disclosing the use
of such content.29 Aside from referencing Section 315(d), the Commission does not identify any
authority in Section 315 that could justify this disclosure requirement. And there is none.
