3. Section 317 Does Not Support the Proposed Requirements.
The Commission also refers to Section 317 and its sponsorship identification regulations,
noting that “[p]ursuant to section 317 of the Act and section 73.1212 of the Commission’s rules,
broadcast stations are required to make on-air sponsorship identification announcements when any
valuable consideration is paid or promised to them in exchange for the broadcast of program
material.” 45 As relevant here, the Commission has by regulation extended sponsorship
identification requirements to cable operators engaged in origination cablecasting.46
Section 317 and the sponsorship identification regulations do not support the proposed
rules. The scope of Section 317 as applied to cable operators is very narrow and limited. The
Commission defines “[o]rigination cablecasting” as “[p]rogramming (exclusive of broadcast
signals) carried on a cable television station over one or more channels and subject to the exclusive
control of the cable operator.”47 At most, therefore, the existing sponsorship identification rules
apply only to advertisements that run during programming produced by the cable operators, i.e.,
