Commission to impose an on-air disclosure requirement only with respect to sponsorship
identification. Congress has said nothing about doing so with respect to the use of AI-generated
content in political advertisements. The best reading of this provision is that it does not contain
such authority. Indeed, in recently finding that the Commission lacked statutory authority under
Section 317 to impose an additional verification requirement for foreign governmental entities, the
D.C. Circuit made clear that an “agency must identify statutory authority for any action it takes.”50
The court found in that case that the FCC “ha[d] not done so” because it had “decreed a duty that
the statute does not require and that the statute does not empower the FCC to impose.”51 The same
is true here. Section 317 forecloses the Commission from imposing robust duties on licensees to
investigate or make inquiries beyond what Congress has specified.
The legislative history of Section 317 confirms its narrowness. “Section 317 traces its
lineage to . . . the Radio Act of 1927,” and the “legislative history of the Radio Act of 1927 shows
that the sponsorship identification provision imposed only a very limited obligation upon
broadcasters: to announce that a program had been paid for or furnished to the station by a third-
