II. REQUIRING CABLE OPERATORS TO DISCLOSE AI-GENERATED CONTENT
IN POLITICAL ADVERTISEMENTS WOULD VIOLATE THE FIRST
AMENDMENT.
Even if the Commission had statutory authority to proceed, it should not promulgate the
rules as currently proposed because they would violate the First Amendment. The proposed rules
trigger strict scrutiny because they are content- and speaker-based, and they both compel and
burden political speech. But even if the rules are subject to only intermediate scrutiny, they would
fail because they are not sufficiently tailored to advance the Commission’s stated interest in
transparency.68
A. The Proposed Requirements Trigger Strict Scrutiny.
The proposed requirements trigger strict scrutiny as applied to cable operators. As the
Notice recognizes, the “less rigorous” First Amendment scrutiny that applies to broadcast
regulation does not extend to cable operators because it is premised on spectrum scarcity.69 Cable
