political messages.”91 The same kind of risk is present here.
B. Even if Intermediate Scrutiny Applies, the Proposed Rules Are Not Narrowly
Drawn to Serve a Substantial Governmental Interest.
The proposed rules cannot be sustained under strict scrutiny. But, even if only intermediate
scrutiny applies, the proposed rules likewise fail. The Commission has asserted a “compelling
interest in providing greater transparency regarding the use of AI-generated content in political
89
Notice ¶ 33.
90 Id. ¶ 21.
91 Loveday, 707 F.2d at 1458; cf. Compl., Hovde v. WinSenate, Case No. 2024CV001144 (Brown County
Cir. Ct., Wis.) (filed Aug. 9, 2024) (alleging that numerous broadcast stations are liable for defamation for
continuing to air a political advertisement after the plaintiff sent cease-and-desist letters contending the
advertisement contained false and misleading claims).
22
advertising.”92 Accepting for these purposes that this constitutes a compelling (and therefore also
at least a substantial/important) interest, the proposed regulations cannot satisfy intermediate
scrutiny because they are both overinclusive and underinclusive and “burden substantially more
speech than is necessary” to further the government’s asserted interest.93
First, the proposed regulations are wildly overinclusive. They are not limited to
advertisements that are intended to mislead or deceive voters, but instead extend to all political
advertisements involving AI-generated content. This problem is compounded by the Notice’s
unbounded definition of “AI-generated content” as “an image, audio, or video that has been
generated using computational technology or other machine-based system that depicts an
individual’s appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation, including, in
particular, AI-generated voices that sound like human voices, and AI-generated actors that appear
to be human actors.”94 The first part of the definition potentially sweeps in all digital content.95
The proposed rules thus sweep well beyond the government’s asserted interest in preventing AI
from “mislead[ing] the public about candidates’ assertions or positions on particular issues or
about whether certain events actually happened.”96
92
Notice ¶¶ 30-31.
93
Turner, 512 U.S. at 662 (quotation marks omitted).
94
Notice ¶ 12.
95
See Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Carr, Notice at 41 (“It would be difficult, in this day and age,
to imagine an advertisement (political or not) that does not use a ‘computational technology’ to ‘depict’ an
‘event, circumstance, or situation.’”); Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Simington, Notice at 43
(brackets in original) (“a lot of photo, video, and audio editing and engineering software uses
‘computational technology or other machine-based system’ to modify the ‘depict[ion of] an individual’s
appearance, speech, or conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation[.] A lot. Like, all of it.”).
96
Notice ¶ 10.
23
Second, the proposed rules are significantly underinclusive. As discussed above, they do
not cover critical parts of the political advertising marketplace, like online advertising and social
media, where political advertising is increasingly common and where AI-generated content is
likely to appear. Thus, the proposed rule is unlikely to achieve the Commission’s stated interest
in greater transparency in political advertising; it will simply encourage advertisers to advertise
via media that do not require disclosure. Indeed, the proposed rule actually undermines the
Commission’s stated interest in transparency given that Americans are likely to be confused by
seeing the “same” political advertisement containing AI content with disclosures on television and
without disclosures online. Indeed, because the proposed rule regulates only a part of the political
advertising marketplace, it could be counterproductive: Americans may assume that any
advertisement they see without a disclosure contains entirely “real” content, even though the
absence of a disclosure in fact reflects only the limitations of the Commission’s legal authority.
III. THE PROPOSED RULES ARE UNDULY BURDENSOME, UNWORKABLE, AND
POTENTIALLY CONTRARY TO EXISTING LEGAL OBLIGATIONS.
The Commission tentatively concluded that requiring cable operators and other distributors
to “make a simple inquiry to the candidate or other entity that requests airtime as to whether a
political ad contains AI-generated content would not impose a significant burden on these entities,”
and that the “candidate or other entity that requests airtime generally would be aware whether or
not a particular ad contains AI-generated content.”97 These statements underestimate the technical
challenges and costs associated with implementing the proposal.
First, the proposed rules would be extremely burdensome to cable operators. The
Commission asserts, without any basis, that since regulated entities “would be required to make
97
Notice ¶ 36.
24
on-air and political file disclosures only in instances where the ad contains content meeting [the
Commission’s] definition, and would be allowed to rely on the information provided to them by
the person or entity making the request for the purchase of airtime, any administrative burden
would be modest.”98 But NCTA’s member companies sell thousands of political advertisements
during an election cycle, and, in practice, the inquiry process is unlikely to be as straightforward
as the Commission describes. The Commission itself contemplates the possibility of a station
being “informed by a credible third party that a political ad contains AI-generated content where
there was no previous affirmative response to the station’s inquiry,” which potentially could
require the station to “follow up with the purchaser of the ad and/or insert the required
disclosure.”99 The Commission further notes the possibility that the person or entity requesting
airtime may “fail[] to respond to a station’s inquiry,” creating the possibility of additional
responsibilities for licensees in that scenario.100 And the Commission suggests that the inquiry
scheme as proposed may be insufficient, asking whether “such an inquiry [would] be expected to
identify all political ads that use AI-generated content” and implying that the “person or entity
making the request for airtime” may not “know whether the ad was created using AI-generated
content.”101 Yet in all of these scenarios, the proposed rules would still impose responsibility on
cable operators and distributors for failing to make a disclosure.
Second, the inquiry requirement is not logistically feasible within the short window in
which distributors review proposed advertisements prior to airing. Candidates often submit
98
Id. ¶ 32.
99
Id. ¶ 17.
100
Id. ¶ 15.
101
Id.
25
advertisements with the expectation that a distributor will be able to serve the advertisement in a
short period of time (e.g., for the next day or the day after). Orders for airtime are received along
with the advertisement itself, sometimes with less than an hour before the distributors’
technological deadline to process the order and encode the advertisement so that it can begin airing
the next day.102 In addition, a campaign may buy a “run” of advertising spots and change the
content mid-run, for example to respond to intervening events.
This timing problem is compounded by the breadth of the proposed definition of “AI-
generated content,” which would seem to cover even simple, non-deceptive changes (e.g., making
the sky look more blue). Many advertisements already use AI techniques to improve
advertisement quality, and that practice will only increase over time. As a result, cable operators
are likely to be deluged with advertisements that may require disclosures and must process such
advertisements on a very short timeframe. Cable operators currently lack the infrastructure or
means to review and make accurate, consistent determinations about complicated AI issues—
issues that are far more complicated than the sponsorship identification requirements that
distributors screen for at present—under such severe time and volume constraints. A cable
operator may be airing an array of local and regional advertisements inserted into dozens of
channels.103 Some advertisements will be inserted on the whole system, while others will only be
placed on specific targeted parts of the system. Complying with the proposed requirements will
therefore be exceedingly onerous. Even if cable operators were technically able to comply, the
102
NCTA members report that most ad spots are received with just one day of lead time. One member
estimated the number of individual spots to be encoded and run for political advertisers is about 1,400 for
2024 with most submitted for next-day starts.
103
For example, one NCTA member reported that it takes orders for approximately 115-120 political ads a
day during election season, which are placed across more than 70 channels on its systems.
26
likely proliferation of these disclosures on routine advertisements could serve to dilute the
importance of the disclaimer itself.
Third, inserting the required disclosure into political advertisements would be unworkable
and potentially inconsistent with the existing prohibitions on distributors modifying political
advertisement.104 The on-air disclosure requirement requires an announcement either immediately
before or during the broadcast of any political advertisement containing AI-generated content.
Cable operators and other distributors are typically allotted two minutes per hour for
advertisements, and those advertisements can only run for 30 or 60 seconds. Adding a disclaimer
within an existing advertisement break would likely require cable operators to (1) develop the
production capabilities to squeeze a 30-second advertisement into 26 seconds to allow for extra
time (presumably 4 seconds) for the announcement at the beginning of the advertisement, or
(2) develop the ability to add the disclaimer as an overlay to the advertisement itself. Neither
approach is technically feasible and both would impose considerable costs on cable operators. In
addition, both approaches would impact the appearance and content of the advertisement, which
is not permissible under existing law.105 And such disclosures will also reduce the amount of time
allotted to advertisements, thereby reducing the value proposition of airing political advertisements
on regulated entities’ systems and stations.
104
See 47 U.S.C. § 315(a); 47 C.F.R. § 76.205(a).
105
47 U.S.C. § 315(a); 47 C.F.R. § 76.205(a).
27
Fourth, FEC Chairman Cooksey has already said that he “fear[s] [the FCC’s] proposed
regulations may create irreconcilable conflicts between” the FEC and FCC’s “respective statutes
and rules.”106 The likely result would be voter confusion and “a patchwork of inconsistent rules.”107
Finally, incorporating the disclosure into existing advertisements could violate the
advertisement creator’s copyright. Distributors do not have the unilateral right to make editorial
changes over the content of advertisements. The disclaimers that are currently required by the
FEC do not raise this concern because, under the FEC regulatory regime, the advertiser (not the
distributor) inserts the disclaimer. The potential for committing copyright violations and
allegations against the distributor by the advertisement creator raises yet another complication and
potential liability for cable operators with respect to the proposed rules.
CONCLUSION
For the reasons discussed above, NCTA believes that requiring cable operators to disclose
AI-generated content in political advertisements and to report on such content in political-file
requirements would exceed the Commission’s statutory authority, violate the First Amendment,
106
Cooksey Letter at 2.
107
Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Carr, Notice at 38. Indeed, Congress is actively considering a
comprehensive approach to this important subject that would resolve the potential for confusion and
conflicting rules. Both the Senate and the House have introduced legislation that would allow the FEC—
not the FCC—to specifically regulate disclosures and uses of AI-generated content in electioneering
communications. For example, the REAL Political Advertisements Act would amend 52 U.S.C. § 30120
to require disclaimers regarding the use of AI in political advertisements, and it further directs the FEC to
promulgate a regulation defining content generated by AI and the criteria to be used in determining whether
a political advertisement contains such content. See S. 1596, 118th Cong. (2023); H.R. 3044, 118th Cong.
(2023). The Protect Elections from Deceptive AI Act would amend FECA to define “deceptive AI-
generated audio or visual media” and prohibit the knowing distribution of such content for the purpose of
influencing an election or soliciting funds. See S. 2770, 118th Cong. (2023); H.R. 8384, 118th Cong.
(2023). And the Candidate Voice Fraud Prohibition Act would amend FECA to prohibit the distribution,
with actual malice, of political communications that contain materially deceptive AI-generated audio that
impersonates a candidate’s voice and are intended to injure the candidate’s reputation or deceive voters.
See H.R. 4611, 118th Cong. (2023).
28
and raise numerous practical concerns. The Commission should not proceed with its proposed
rules.
Respectfully submitted,
/s/ Rick Chessen
Rick Chessen
Mary Beth Murphy
Radhika Bhat
