V. Conclusion ............................................................................................................................... 9
I. Introduction and Summary
CMG Media Corporation (“CMG”) respectfully submits these comments in response to
the Federal Communications Commission (“FCC”) Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (“NPRM”)
proposing to require disclosures on political advertisements aired on broadcast stations and select
cable networks that contain content generated using artificial intelligence (“AI”).1
CMG is an integrated and award-winning media company serving more than 60 million
Americans across the country. With 50 top-performing radio stations, 15 high-quality, market-
leading television brands in 9 markets, and numerous streaming platforms, CMG is committed to
disseminating trusted content that informs the communities it serves. CMG’s dedication to
developing valuable local and national news content is exemplified by its numerous awards,
including serving as the first local broadcast media company to be named a finalist for the
prestigious Pulitzer Prize in Public Service.2 Just last month, three CMG TV and radio stations
earned National Edward R. Murrow Awards, such as the “Best Newscast” award for WSB
Radio’s “Atlanta’s Morning News” broadcast.3 Integrity in journalism and reporting has fueled
CMG’s more than one-hundred year legacy in broadcasting.
While CMG shares the Commission’s desire to combat potentially deceptive advertising,
the Commission’s proposed rules focused on broadcast platforms overshoot the problem and
undercut the opportunity for positive results. And even if the FCC’s proposals could be justified
1 Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political
Advertisements, MB Docket No. 24-211, Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, FCC 24-74, ¶¶ 13-14
(rel. July 25, 2024) (“NPRM”).
2 CMG, Cox Media Group and KFF Health News Named Finalist for Prestigious Pulitzer Prize
in Public Service (May 6, 2024), https://tinyurl.com/2w2j9349.
3 CMG, CMG Earns 3 National Edwards R. Murrow Awards (Aug. 20, 2024),
https://tinyurl.com/yc5bwdpw.
1
as a matter of policy, there are legitimate questions about their legality that would result in a
cloud of uncertainty hovering over any rules for years after they are adopted and further muddle
any messaging about the use of AI in political advertisements.
CMG does not believe the proposed disclosure requirement will advance the shared
objective of broadcasters and the Commission to ensure that truthful and accurate information is
provided to the public. Accordingly, CMG encourages the FCC not to adopt the rules proposed
in the NPRM and to take the time to ensure that unintended consequences that are antithetical to
its goals are avoided.
II. Broadcasters Embrace Their Position of Trust in the Political Advertising Process.
CMG recognizes that it operates from a position of trust as a platform for political
advertising. In preparation for and during each election cycle, CMG expends considerable
resources to comply with the extensive rules and laws applicable to political advertising. This
includes training sales and administrative staff on sales and recordkeeping requirements,
reviewing disclosure statements and advertisements as they are received, uploading the required
materials to the political file on a timely basis, issuing rebates when required, and reviewing
demands from candidates and other groups to take down advertisements they believe are false or
deceptive. Notably, out of the dozens of “takedown requests” that CMG’s stations have received
this election cycle, none have related to the use of deepfakes or any other allegedly deceptive use
of AI.
The approach proposed in the NPRM to try to expose and mitigate deceptive advertising
is problematic as a matter of both policy and law. Although the Commission portrays the
proposed disclosures as a “simple” matter of transparency, in practice, the standardized
disclaimer will result in confusion for listeners and viewers about what part of an advertisement
2
contains AI, what the use of AI indicates about the veracity of the advertisement, and why the
same advertisement includes a disclosure on some platforms, but not on others. Additionally, the
proposal would be burdensome for stations to implement—particularly during an election cycle
in which broadcaster staffs are already trained and focused on compliance with the stringent
political advertising requirements that exist today. A rush to usher in new rules specific to local
broadcasters is misaligned with the goal of curbing deepfakes that are infiltrating online media
platforms.
III. The Proposed Rules Would Sow Confusion Among Listeners and Viewers While
Significantly Burdening Local Broadcasters.
The proposed requirements would not achieve the Commission’s goal of creating
transparency and, instead, would create needless confusion for listeners and viewers while, at the
same time, imposing a significant burden on local broadcasters. Much of the confusion would
stem from the fact that the proposed disclosures are both under-inclusive and over-inclusive:
they are under-inclusive in that they would only apply to political advertisements on certain
platforms; yet they are over-inclusive in that they would apply to any use of AI in a political
advertisement, no matter how innocuous. Complying with the proposed requirements,
meanwhile, would substantially burden local radio and TV broadcasters across the country. The
Commission significantly underestimates the burden its proposal would impose on broadcasters,
who already must comply with unique requirements for political advertisements that do not
extend to any other forms of media.
A. The Proposed Rules Would Confuse, Not Inform, Audiences.
The rules proposed in the NPRM would not provide transparency to persons viewing and
listening to political ads and would instead sow confusion due to a combination of: (1) the broad
definition of “AI-generated content”; (2) the standardized nature of the proposed disclosures; and
3
(3) the disparate disclosure requirements based solely on the platform on which an advertisement
is distributed. As a result, the proposed rules could inadvertently end up magnifying deceptive
uses of AI-generated content when they appear on platforms that would not be subject to the
proposed rules.
First, the proposed definition of “AI-generated content” is extremely over-inclusive,
extending to any “image, audio, or video that has been generated using computational
technology or other machine-based system that depicts an individual’s appearance, speech, or
conduct, or an event, circumstance, or situation, including, in particular, AI-generated voices that
sound like human voices, and AI-generated actors that appear to be human actors.”4
Disclosures, therefore, would be required where even the shortest portions of an ad contain AI-
generated content or where AI is used in the production process in a manner that does not affect
the ad’s message.
Second, because the disclosures would be “standardized,” it would be up to the listener or
viewer to discern what portion of the ad contains AI-generated content. It is foreseeable that a
listener or viewer exposed to a standardized disclaimer will assume that some portion of the
accompanying ad includes manipulated content even if AI is only used as a production tool (e.g.,
to adjust audio levels or correct the colors).
Third, requiring disclosures for ads aired on radio and TV stations—but not streaming or
digital platforms or even most cable networks—would impose an unreasonable burden on
listeners and viewers to identify what platform they are using and understand the rules applicable
to that platform. With a plethora of content options in the marketplace, audiences may consume
news and other programming on various streaming or digital platforms in addition to radio or
4 NPRM ¶ 12.
4
TV. But they would only be exposed to disclosures on radio and TV ads. At best, then,
consumers would never be able to truly rely on the disclosures to identify ads with AI-generated
content. At worst (and perhaps most likely), consumers will fail to appreciate the distinction
between broadcast and non-broadcast and wrongly assume that ads on non-broadcast platforms
that do not include disclosures must not contain AI-generated content. Thus, the proposed rule
may inadvertently exacerbate the harms of AI-generated content on non-broadcast platforms.
Worse yet, the proposed rules could drive advertisers to avoid broadcast altogether if they
believe the disclosures are confusing or undercut their advertising strategy. To be clear, this will
not eliminate the use of AI-generated content in political ads: it will merely drive those ads to
unregulated platforms, depriving broadcast listeners and viewers of information about political
matter and depriving local broadcast stations of much needed revenue to fund local
programming.
Providing listeners and viewers with transparency requires information that is specific
and easy to understand. Disclosures that only reach a subset of political advertisements will
never be able to achieve this goal and will instead prove counterproductive. Accordingly, while
CMG shares the Commission’s goal of fostering an informed electorate, CMG does not believe
the proposals set forth in the NPRM will achieve that goal and, furthermore, believes they are
likely to cause more harm than good.
B. Compliance with the Proposed AI Disclosure Rules Would Significantly
Burden TV and Radio Stations’ Operations.
Determining what political advertisements require disclosures and ensuring that the
disclosures are properly included will impose a significant burden on broadcasters’ operations.
The Commission’s proposal would require “all radio and television broadcast stations that air
political ads [to] inquire whether political ads scheduled to be aired on their stations contain AI-
5
generated content.”5 Rather than facilitating “a simple inquiry,”6 as the FCC suggests, the
proposed requirement would complicate stations’ operations. First, radio and TV stations would
bear the burden of engaging in a potentially complex process of determining whether each
political ad includes AI-generated content. Broadcasters will need to educate their own sales and
traffic staff and then their advertisers about what constitutes AI-generated content under the rule.
Even still, the person or entity making the request may not “be expected to know whether the ad
was created using AI-generated content,”7 so further inquiry may be required. Moreover, the
person or entity requesting airtime may delay their response or not respond at all to a station’s
inquiry.8 As a result, complying with the FCC’s requirements could be particularly onerous for
local radio and TV stations.
Furthermore, the Commission’s proposed requirements would compound the existing
load that broadcasters are already carrying to comply with political advertising rules that do not
apply to other entities that distribute political messages. For one thing, broadcasters must
provide reasonable access and are prohibited from censoring the content of federal candidate
ads.9 Additionally, the Commission’s rules require broadcasters to maintain political files for
public inspection.10 Broadcasters must also sell ads to candidates at the lowest unit rate.11 The
5 Id. ¶ 13.
6 See id. ¶ 15 (stating that “a broadcast station would fulfill its obligation by making a simple
inquiry to the person or entity making the request for the purchase of airtime as to whether a
political ad includes AI-generated content”).
7 Id.
8 See id.
9 47 U.S.C. §§ 312 & 315(a).
10 NPRM ¶ 5 (citations omitted); 47 U.S.C. § 315(e); 47 CFR § 73.1943.
11 47 U.S.C. § 315(b).
6
additional requirements proposed in the NPRM would add yet another administrative burden for
broadcasters, and a significant one at that.
Implementing the disclosures in compliance with the Commission’s requirements would
stall the advertising approval process as broadcasters would need to wait for confirmation of
whether an ad includes AI-generated content and then make sure the appropriate disclaimers are
included in the ad. If the disclaimers are not included, the broadcaster would need to either
create and add the disclaimer itself or go back to the buyer to request that they add the
disclaimer. This process would make it impossible to allow advertisers to change their ads on
short notice, which is a frequent occurrence during election season.
Holding local broadcasters responsible not only for ads sold within their local inventory,
but also for network programming, would amplify these challenges. Local broadcasters typically
do not receive information about network ads in advance, so local stations have no ability to
assess whether the ads require disclaimers or not. Even if they did, the logistics of interrupting a
network feed to add a disclosure would be challenging if not impossible.
Particularly concerning is the prospect that the proposed rules could force broadcasters to
have to sacrifice their limited airtime to broadcast the required disclosures, costing broadcasters
revenue and depriving listeners and viewers of programming on which they rely. Under the
proposed rules, stations “would be required to make [an] on-air announcement immediately
preceding or during the broadcast of any ad by or on behalf of a legally qualified candidate for
public office and any issue ad that contains AI-generated content” using standardized language.12
The rules do not consider whether the disclosures would come out of the time allotted to the
advertisement or out of the other station airtime. In practice, broadcasters likely will need to use
12 NPRM ¶¶ 16-17 (footnotes omitted).
7
other time for many of the disclosures because: (1) broadcasters are legally prohibited from
censoring candidate ads; and (2) advertisers will have leverage to demand that additional time be
required for the disclosures given the absence of a disclosure requirement on other platforms.
Sacrificing additional airtime to accommodate the disclosures, however, would trigger a stark
reality: broadcasters will either need to reduce the number of advertisements in each commercial
break or they will need to preempt other programming, including news and other essential
content, to accommodate longer commercial breaks. This burden would be acutely damaging to
local radio and TV broadcasters, like CMG, which would be forced to choose between reducing
the revenue used to produce important local content or reducing the amount of local content
instead.
IV. Concerns About the Legality of the Proposed AI Disclosure Requirements Will
Create Additional Burdens and Confusion.
There are legitimate questions both about whether the FCC has statutory authority to
adopt the proposed rules and whether they are constitutionally sound. The only authority that the
Commission cites for the proposed rules is Section 303(r) of the Communications Act,13 which
the agency itself notes does not provide any specific authority and instead merely enables the
Commission to proscribe regulations to carry out other provisions of the Act.14 Additionally, the
proposed rules would require CMG and other broadcasters to engage in government compelled
speech in violation of their constitutional rights.15
13 47 U.S.C. § 303(r).
14 See id.; NPRM ¶ 27 (citations omitted); see also Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo, 144 S.
Ct. 2244, 2266 (2024) (cleaned up) (compelling the FCC to discern the “single, best meaning” of
the Communications Act “fixed at the time of its enactment”).
15 See 303 Creative LLC v. Elenis, 600 U.S. 570, 586–87 (2023) (citations omitted).
8
The questions lingering over the proposed requirements’ legality would spawn greater
uncertainty for broadcasters and audiences. This would be particularly problematic during a
contentious election where disclosures could appear and disappear with no explanation as the
rules work their way through the legal process. Whatever the ultimate result of any legal
challenges may be, the uncertainty that would arise during the process should provide reason
enough for the FCC not to adopt rules that are on such unsteady legal ground.
V. Conclusion
For the foregoing reasons, CMG respectfully urges the Commission to refrain from
adopting the proposed disclosure requirements for AI-generated content in political
advertisements.
Respectfully submitted,
Alysia Long
Senior Vice President and Associate General
Counsel, Law & Policy
CMG Media Corporation
1601 W. Peachtree St., NE
Atlanta, GA 30309
September 19, 2024
