2308,1004085881463,2024-10-04T20:30:27.628Z,UnidosUS,,,"September 19, 2024

The Honorable Jessica Rosenworcel, Chair
The Federal Communications Commission
45 L Street NE
Washington, DC 20554

Re: Request for Written Comment on Proposed Rule – Disclosure and Transparency of Artificial Intelligence-Generated Content in Political Advertisements (MB Docket No. 24-211)
On behalf of UnidosUS, we respectfully submit these comments in reply to the request by Federal Communication Commission’s (herein called “the Commission”) for public comment on its proposed rule related to the disclosure and transparency of Artificial Intelligence-generated content in political advertisements.
UnidosUS is a nonprofit, nonpartisan organization that serves as the nation’s largest Hispanic civil rights and advocacy organization. Since 1968, we have challenged the social, economic, and political barriers that affect Latinos through our unique combination of expert research, advocacy, programs, and an Affiliate Network of more than 300 community-based organizations across the United States, including Puerto Rico.
We welcome the Commission’s goal of providing greater transparency regarding the use of AI-generated content in political advertising and believe these rules are essential to safeguard the integrity of our democratic process and ensure that voters are fully informed about the origins and nature of political ads they may encounter. 
The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence technologies, particularly in the creation of sophisticated ""deepfakes,"" presents a significant challenge to the integrity of political and public discourse. AI-generated content can convincingly depict candidates or individuals saying or doing things they never actually said or did, with the potential to deceive voters and manipulate public opinion. The compelling public interest in electing our representatives based on facts, values, and policies—rather than deception, defamation, and intimidation—necessitates prompt action.
Our brains have evolved to believe what we see with our eyes. Mounting bodies of evidence indicate the significant deceptive impact that AI-generated content can have on public perception and decision-making, particularly in the electoral and voting rights contexts. The proposed disclosure requirements represent a common-sense extension of the Commission’s existing mandates to ensure transparency in broadcasting, particularly in political advertising on radio and TV.
The proposed rules are particularly crucial and timely because of existing regulatory gaps governing AI technologies that leave voters vulnerable to sophisticated disinformation campaigns that leverage evolving AI technologies and could maliciously generate disinformation that interferes with an informed citizenry’s exercise of the franchise. 
The potential for AI to “supercharge” deceptive voter suppression tactics cannot be overstated. As these technologies continue to evolve—becoming increasingly capable of producing persuasive voice imitations and photorealistic images—the risk to fair and informed democratic participation grows exponentially. Without proper guardrails, we face the prospect of elections that are influenced more by technological manipulation than by genuine policy debates and candidate qualifications.
UnidosUS Support for Proposed Rules
Aligned with comments submitted by Public Citizen and other pro-democracy groups, we strongly endorse the following aspects of the proposed rules:
On-Air and Written Disclosure Requirements
We support mandating both on-air disclosures and written disclosures in broadcasters' political files when AI-generated content is used, especially to create potentially deceptive deepfakes. This dual approach ensures immediate viewer/listener awareness and creates a permanent record for future reference and accountability.
Application to Both Candidate and Issue Advertisements
Extending the disclosure requirements to both candidate-specific and issue-based advertisements recognizes the broad impact of AI-generated content across all forms of political messaging. This comprehensive approach ensures that all political advertising is subject to the same rigorous transparency standards.
Inclusive Application to Broadcasters and Other Entities
Applying these disclosure requirements to all relevant content carriers under the FCC's jurisdiction ensures comprehensive coverage at local, state, and federal levels. This broad application helps prevent potential loopholes and maintains a level playing field across different media platforms.
Structural AI Limitations Result in Language Access Gaps
An additional consideration in the implementation of AI disclosure requirements is the limitation of large language models (LLMs) in non-English languages, particularly in the context of political advertising. Language access continues to be a barrier to civic participation for historically marginalized communities, and disinformation is left online longer when it occurs in Spanish, as a study by Avaaz demonstrates.
Further, f existing language access protections, like Section 203 of the Voting Rights Act (VRA), have resulted in the use of tools like Google translate and chatbots that produce poor or inaccurate translations. This is especially pertinent given the growing multiculturalism of American communities, heightening the need to ensure equitable access to accurate electoral and political information for all communities.
AI models are also inappropriate sources for election information because they generalize across information and can produce inaccurate outcomes in response to specific and localized questions.
Limitations of Large Language Models in Non-English Languages
While LLMs have significantly advanced in recent years, they have inherent limitations because of the predictive relationships, based in language and training data, that drive outcomes. These limitations can result in “hallucinations,” in which an LLM “perceives patterns or objects that are nonexistent or imperceptible to human observers, creating outputs that are nonsensical or altogether inaccurate.” This has clear implications for AI-generated content meant to be used to convey critical and rights-impact electoral or political information. 
However, the quality of non-English language outputs generated by an LLM are even worse and more unpredictable. LLMs are trained on immense datasets, with much of this training data scraped directly from content already living in the online ecosystem. As a recent Amazon Web Services paper outlines, “a shocking amount of the web is machine translated.” In other words, most of the non-English content online is derived from non-human translation tools like Google translate, which are notorious for their low quality and habit of missing contexts or cultural nuance, leading to mistranslations. With English as the primary language of development and training for many of these models, there exists an inherent lack of parity between the quality of an LLM output in English with other non-English languages.
This lack of parity results in a number of specific risks in the electoral information context:
Reduced Accuracy: Translations and content generation in non-English languages may lack the nuance, cultural context, and linguistic accuracy necessary for sensitive information, like political discourse.
Mistranslation Risk: Inaccurate or low-quality translations of electoral or political content can lead to misunderstandings or misinterpretations of candidates' positions, policy proposals, or important political issues.
Inequitable Information Access: Low quality AI-generated content in non-English languages creates a multi-tiered information system, potentially disadvantaging non-English speaking voters.
Cultural Insensitivity: LLMs may struggle with cultural nuances and contextual understanding in languages other than English, potentially leading to culturally insensitive or inappropriate content in political advertisements.
Importance of AI Disclosures for Language Access
Given these limitations, the requirement for AI disclosures becomes even more crucial in addressing language access issues:
Transparency in Content Origin: Disclosures allow audiences to understand that the content they are viewing or hearing may have been generated or translated by AI, prompting them to seek additional verification if needed.
Quality Assurance Incentive: Mandatory disclosures can encourage political advertisers to critically review AI-generated content, as well as invest in high-quality human translations and culturally appropriate content creation, rather than relying solely on potentially inadequate AI-generated outputs.
Protection of Linguistic Minorities: By highlighting the use of AI in content creation or translation, disclosures can help stem the tide of potential disinformation or low-quality political messaging.
Promoting Equitable Political Discourse: Awareness of AI involvement in content creation can encourage a more critical evaluation of political advertisements across all language communities, promoting a more equitable and informed political discourse.
Encouraging Human Oversight: AI disclosures may incentivize the use of human oversight in the creation and translation of electoral and political content, ensuring cultural and linguistic appropriateness.
Conclusion
The integrity of our democratic processes depends on voters' ability to make informed decisions based on accurate information. By implementing the proposed disclosure requirements, the Commission will take a significant step toward safeguarding the transparency and fairness of political advertising in the era of artificial intelligence. We also encourage the Commission to consult with the Federal Election Commission (FEC) as part of the rulemaking process, as the FEC is engaged in a similar rulemaking process around regulating the use of AI in campaign ads. 
We commend the Commission’s leadership in addressing this critical issue and look forward to continued collaboration in efforts to provide transparency about the use of AI in broadcast political advertisements. The proposed rules represent a vital safeguard for our democratic institutions, ensuring that technological advancements do not undermine the quality of our political processes.
For questions or additional dialogue on these issues, please contact Laura MacCleery, Senior Director of Policy, at lmaccleery@unidosus.org, and Claudia Ruiz, Senior Civil Rights Analyst, at cruiz@unidosus.org.",10520
