2312,102059230917,2024-10-20T05:43:41.258Z,Mr. Gary Chapman,,,"I am writing to express my concerns regarding your proposed rule for AI-generated content in political advertisements. In light of the Supreme Court's decision in Loper Bright v. Raimondo, it is clear that the FCC does not possess the authority to enact this proposed rule.

Agencies cannot extend their regulatory reach beyond the specific authority granted by Congress. The FCC's authority over candidate ads is limited to ensuring that broadcasters provide candidates with equal access. The FCC's proposed regulations exceed this narrow mandate and encroach on the jurisdiction of the Federal Election Commission (FEC).

Congress intentionally restricted the FCC's role over political ads to specific, targeted matters. This limitation was designed to prevent the kind of overreach that the Commission is now attempting.

None of the laws cited in the proposed rule provide the agency with the sweeping authority it claims over political speech. The Supreme Court has decisively ruled against such novel interpretations t

Sincerely,
Mr. Gary Chapman",1053
